<FIRST>r i PM-China-Movies     10-25 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Movies,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Reins in Newly Creative Film Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uncertain times lie ahead for China's movie
industry, which faces new political constraints just as a
generation of young, ambitious directors strives to compete on
international screens.
   Like others in the art world, studio heads and directors are
waiting to see the full impact of the crackdown on liberalism that
has followed the June crackdown on student-led demonstrations for
democratic reform.
   The early signs have not been encouraging.
   The central government's Film Bureau, which supervises all
movies, has fired the head of the Beijing Film Studio for
unspecified political errors, and sent in a special team led by
bureau director Teng Jingxian to ``rectify'' the studio.
   Liu Cheng, in charge of censorship at the bureau, said he sent
``urgent telegrams'' this fall to China's two most innovative
studios, the Xian Film Studio in western China and the Pearl River
Film Studio in Canton, warning them to ``pay special attention to
problems in ideological tendencies.''
   Asked what that meant, Liu laughed and said, ``When they see
(the warning), they understand.''
   Film officials did not even try to select this year's best movie
in the Golden Rooster competition, China's politically charged
version of the Academy Awards. The selection was hard enough in
past years, when awards were sometimes delayed for months while
officials debated the political merits of films nominated for
artistic reasons. This year, officials said no movies were
acceptable.
   All studios, like other work units, have been ordered to hold
special classes to study recent Communist Party documents on the
battle against ``bourgeois liberalism,'' or anti-socialist ideas,
and the need for art to serve socialism.
   Liu said at the Film Bureau, the classes take up two half-days a
week _ far more than ordinary work units.
   Two of China's leading film directors were overseas when the
crackdown began, and one, Chen Kaige, has said he won't return. He
plans to make a documentary about the June army attack on Beijing
protesters, in which hundreds and possibly thousands were killed.
   The other, Xian studio head Wu Tianming, has not been in touch
with his studio since he left for Canada in April to attend the
opening of a joint Chinese-Canadian movie about China's first
emperor.
   Studio officials say they don't know if Wu will return, and Liu
acknowledged it was ``hard to say'' if Wu would be allowed to keep
his job if he did. Wu's blunt criticisms of government censors long
have gotten him in trouble, and his studio's movies have angered
some officials by depicting rural poverty and mindless bureaucracy.
   But the debt-ridden studio in arid, impoverished northern China
also has won more international prizes than any other studio,
beginning with Wu's 1987 ``Old Well,'' which won awards in Tokyo
and Hawaii.
   The movie's frank depiction of rural poverty and daring story of
a love triangle set off a small storm within the Chinese movie
industry, more accustomed to socialist morality tales.
   Young directors at other studios joined the movement to make
realistic movies of modern life, adopting film techniques from
abroad, and critics said China's film industry had finally matured.
   No movies of the new school have been released since the June
crackdown, only epics of the Communist revolution timed to
celebrate the 40th anniversary of its victory in October 1949.
   But Wang Jin, vice president of the Pearl River studio, said in
an interview that the Film Bureau recently approved a movie the
studio shot before June depicting smuggling and other illegal
activities.
   Last spring, Pearl River released what it billed as China's
``first sex movie,'' a story of love and marriage in a 1940s
fishing village. ``I think we can still make this kind of movie,''
Wang said.
   But the studio will no longer test the censors by sending them
love scenes it thinks likely to be cut _ it will make the cuts
itself, he said.
   Directors Yan Xueshu and Zhou Xiaowen at the Xian studio also
said they hope to continue their experimental work.
   ``Movements happen. We are used to them,'' Zhou said. If the
government insisted on changing a movie he made, he added boldly,
``I'd resign.''
   ``And start your own studio?'' Yan asked him sarcastically.
</TEXT>
