<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0042EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Thatcher     10-25 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Thatcher,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Leader's Anti-Sanctions Stand Elicits Strong Reactions</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DAVID CRARY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Thatcher provokes
outrage, admiration, bewilderment, and few South Africans who
follow foreign affairs are neutral about the British prime minister.
   From the Commonwealth summit meeting in distant Malaysia this
week, Mrs. Thatcher consolidated her status as a dominant figure in
South Africa's political disputes.
   Her determined opposition to tougher economic sanctions against
South Africa was praised by conservative whites and denounced by
anti-apartheid leaders.
   ``Thank you, Maggie,'' said an editorial Tuesday in The Citizen,
a pro-government Johannesburg daily. ``We South Africans appreciate
your brave, honest and lone battle against sanctions.''
   President F.W. de Klerk, in a speech Monday night, lauded the
leader of Britain's Conservative Party and said intensified
sanctions would undermine his proposals for political reform.
   Murphy Morobe, a senior spokesman for the anti-apartheid
movement, said with understatement that Mrs. Thatcher's position
``does not coincide with ours.'' Moses Mayekiso, a black trade
union leader, said Mrs. Thatcher went to the summit ``to defend the
apartheid regime.''
   The 49-nation Commonwealth, composed of Britain and its former
colonies, adopted a declaration Sunday calling for tougher
financial measures against South Africa and giving the white-led
government six months to fulfill promises to dismantle apartheid.
   The declaration incorporated Mrs. Thatcher's objections but an
hour later, to the dismay of other participants, she issued a
separate statement outlining her reasons for dissent.
   She said tougher sanctions will hurt South Africa's blacks and
increase white resistance to de Klerk's reform program.
   On Tuesday she told a news conference in Kuala Lumpur, ``I am in
step with the people of South Africa.''
   South Africa, a former British colony, withdrew from the
Commonwealth in 1961 as other members increased their demands that
it end its policies of racial separation.
   Business Day, a Johannesburg-based financial newspaper often
critical of the government, said Mrs. Thatcher performed more
honorably at Kuala Lumpur than two pro-sanctions advocates, Prime
Ministers Robert Hawke of Australia and Brian Mulroney of Canada.
   Hawke and Mulroney ``have found in South Africa a rare
opportunity for moral posturing,'' Business Day said. ``They don't
know or care what harm they do.''
   Mrs. Thatcher has ``the good sense to recognize fundamental
changes when they occur, sufficient faith in human nature to dare
to hope for better times, and the courage to back her judgment,''
the editorial said. ``That is why she towers over men like Hawke
and Mulroney; even if she turns out in the end to be wrong, at
least she is not a pygmy.''
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate residential districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
