<FIRST>r a PM-Names     10-25 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0837</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul McCartney says his better relations with other
former Beatles has made it possible for him to play the legendary
group's songs in public again.
   ``My relations with former members of the band have improved.
Those songs are wonderful memories for me and that is why I am
playing them again,'' he told reporters Tuesday before his Rome
concert, part of a world tour promoting his latest album ``Flowers
in the Dirt.''
   Those songs include ``Can't Buy Me Love,'' ``Eleanor Rigby,''
``Back in the USSR,'' ``Hey Jude'' and ``Yesterday,'' which he
called his favorite.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old high school senior will
preside as queen of the 101st Tournament of Roses on New Year's Day.
   ``My reaction was very surprised, and I'm very excited,''
Yasmine Begum Delawari said Tuesday after she was named by Don W.
Fedde, president of the Tournament of Roses Association.
   Miss Delawari, a Pasadena area resident, was chosen from seven
finalists who constitute the tournament's royal court. The queen
and six attendants were chosen from more than 800 applicants
following four interviews, said Kristin Mabry Tranquada, a
tournament spokeswoman.
   Judges made their selections based on the candidates' public
speaking ability, poise, academic achievement and personality.
   ``This is the start of a new century for the Tournament of
Roses, so I just plan to do the best I can to represent them,''
said Miss Delawari, who hopes to attend the University of
California, Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Gaston Caperton says he wants to
get back to running the state after a judge issued a no-fault
divorce award ending his 23-year marriage to former Miss America
runner-up Dee Caperton.
   The governor didn't attend Monday's brief proceedings during
which Kanawha County Circuit Court Judge Herman Canady approved the
divorce on the grounds of irreconcilable differences.
   The action halted a tandem $12 million fraud suit Mrs. Caperton
had filed in federal court against the governor and two others.
   ``I'm pleased to have it behind us,'' the governor said in a
statement. ``I think it's time to move forward.''
   No details were released on the settlement, but Mrs. Caperton's
attorney, Stanley Preiser, said as he left Canady's office: ``Both
cases have been settled. Everybody's happy and she's extremely
satisfied.''
   ``You can underline extremely,'' Mrs. Caperton added.
   In July, Mrs. Caperton filed for divorce and in August followed
it up with her fraud suit, alleging she had been duped into selling
her stock in the family insurance business for $2.98 million when
the stock was worth far more.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Who, The Four Tops, the Four Seasons, the
Kinks, the Platters, Hank Ballard, Bobby Darin and Simon and
Garfunkel have been selected for induction Jan. 17 to the Rock and
Roll Hall of Fame.
   The selections bring to 43 the number of recording acts chosen
for the hall and represent ``a good cross section'' of musical
style, rock historian Norm N. Nite said Tuesday. It also represents
an effort to honor people long overdue for recognition, he added.
   ``We're trying to get caught up on a lot of people owed getting
in. As years go by, it will get tighter and tighter,'' said Nite,
who has two syndicated radio rock 'n' roll oldies shows.
   Besides the recording artists, three ``early influencers'' were
selected to be honored at the as-yet unbuilt hall of fame and
museum _ jazz singer-trumpeter Louis Armstrong, jazz guitarist
Charlie Christian and blues pioneer Ma Rainey.
   Two songwriting teams will be inducted in the non-performing
music industry category, although some have been important
performers as well. The writers include the teams of Brian Holland,
Lamont Dozier and Eddie Holland, and Gerry Goffin and Carole King.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hockey's great one was escorted down Main
Street U.S.A. by the squeaky one, the incoherent one and the goofy
one as the Magic Kingdom paid tribute to Wayne Gretzky.
   Gretzky, 28, wife Janet Jones and their 10-month-old daughter
participated in a parade Tuesday to the Town Square Train Station.
Also in the parade were Mickey Mouse, Donald Duck and Goofy,
Disneyland spokesman Bob Roth said.
   Disney has produced many commercials featuring athletes who have
just won a Super Bowl or World Series saying they plan to go to
Disneyland next, but Roth said there are no plans to ask Gretzky,
`` ... what are you going to do now?''
   The Los Angeles Kings' center last week became the National
Hockey League's all-time scoring champion, eclipsing Gordie Howe's
record.
   ``This is special in that with most honors you get a trophy or a
plaque and you can just enjoy those by yourself,'' Gretzky said.
``But this way I can enjoy the day with my wife and daughter. Just
to spend the day here is quite an honor.''
</TEXT>
