<DOCNO> AP891025-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0043EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ConneautExplosion 2ndLd-Writethru a0782 10-25 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Conneaut Explosion, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0782,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion Destroys House; At Least Two People Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with five grafs to UPDATE with fire chief now saying only
two people died, increase injured to 13. Picks up 4th graf, `Orrenmaa said...'.
SUBS 10th graf, `At least...', to update number of injured.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONNEAUT, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Explosions that may have been caused by
illegal fireworks leveled one house and set two others on fire
Tuesday, killing at least two people and injuring 13 others,
authorities said.
   Crews worked into the night, searching the rubble for other
possible victims of the blast, said Fire Chief Bim Orrenmaa.
   He said illegal fireworks were suspected as the cause of the
explosions which rocked this city of 13,000 on Lake Erie at the
northeast corner of Ohio.
   The fire chief initially said the explosion killed three people,
but later revised the number to two, saying he had been incorrectly
told that one injured person had died.
   Brian Hubbard, an investigator with the Ashtabula County
coroner's office, confirmed two deaths.
   Orrenmaa said firefighters found devices that looked like
fireworks in the home where the explosion and two subsequent blasts
occurred just before noon.
   ``We had a lot of small bangs,'' before the big explosion and
two subsequent blasts, Orrenmaa said.
   Students were evacuated from a nearby elementary school, but
there were no other evacuations.
   Patrolman Michael Strine said the explosion blew out windows of
at least 20 homes in a six-block area.
   The victims were not immediately identified.
   A 46-year-old woman who lived at the house where the explosions
occurred was taken to Hamot Medical Center in Erie, Pa., 25 miles
east of Conneaut, said hospital spokeswoman Wendy DePalma. She was
in satisfactory condition.
   Twelve people were taken to Brown Memorial Hospital in Conneaut,
then released, said hospital administrator George Whitney. He said
most of the injuries did not appear serious.
   John Kingsolver, an agent with the federal Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms, said 10 agents were at the scene. Kingsolver
said that tubes, resembling parts of fireworks, were found.
   The state Emergency Management Agency in Ashtabula County said
it was investigating.
</TEXT>
