<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0201EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SheppardCase     10-25 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sheppard Case,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son Says Father Feared Re-Imprisonment in Wife's 1954 Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Samuel H. Sheppard, acquitted in the
murder of his wife after the U.S. Supreme Court reversed his
conviction due to pretrial publicity, always feared he would be put
back in prison, his son said.
   Ending 20 years of silence on the case, Sam R. Sheppard said in
a speech that he is speaking out in hopes of clearing his father's
name.
   ``Every reference to that (landmark Supreme Court) decision 23
years ago calls my father a convicted murderer,'' he said Tuesday,
35 years after his father was first brought to trial. ``That's not
fair. That conviction was thrown out.''
   The elder Sheppard, an osteopath who was well known in the
Cleveland suburb of Bay Village, was convicted of murder in the
1954 bludgeoning of his pregnant wife, Marilyn. He served nine
years in prison before the nation's high court reversed the
conviction.
   Sheppard was acquitted after a second trial. He died in 1970 at
age 46. The case remains unsolved.
   The younger Sheppard, 42, had been long silent on the case until
this week's speaking tour. On Tuesday, he spoke at Youngstown State
University.
   He was 7 years old at the time of the slaying, and lived with an
uncle after after his father was imprisoned. After the Supreme
Court decision, the elder Sheppard feared constantly that he would
be forced to return to prison, his son said.
   His exoneration in 1966 eased those worries but created new ones.
   ``There is still this stigma in our society that if you're
accused, you're guilty,'' he said. ``He couldn't cope with society.
... He was a great guy, but, I kept my distance. I didn't want to
go down with him. That was the agreement between us.''
   Sheppard said the person he believed responsible for his
mother's killing was the same person who broke into his family's
house two days before the slaying. That person, he said, later was
convicted in an unrelated slaying.
   He said he knew the identity of the alleged killer, but would
not reveal the name to the audience.
   Last summer, police indicated they might consider re-opening the
investigation into Mrs. Sheppard's slaying following the murder
conviction of the Sheppards' one-time window washer.
   Richard Eberling was arrested in 1959 after being found with a
large amount of jewelry belonging to Marilyn Sheppard and her
husband's brother, Richard Sheppard.
   In August, Eberling told The (Cleveland) Plain Dealer from
prison that he was familiar with the circumstances surrounding Mrs.
Sheppard's death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
