<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0146EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Veto     10-25 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Veto,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Line-Item Veto Would Prompt Court Case: Edwards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Any effort by President Bush to exercise a
line-item veto will prompt a lawsuit by members of Congress, the
chairman of a House Judiciary subcommittee says.
   The line-item veto ``is an idea that many of us would resist
very diligently,'' Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., chairman of the
civil and constitutional rights subcommittee of the House Judiciary
Committee, said Tuesday after White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said Bush was considering such a move.
   Bush, Fitzwater said, is prepared to take such a step despite
lack of specific constitutional authority ``to see if it works.''
   Although Bush has called for a constitutional amendment to give
him the ability to veto just one item in a bill while leaving the
rest intact, such a proposal has never made much headway in
Congress.
   Former President Reagan tried unsuccessfully for eight years to
persuade Congress to propose such a constitutional change to the
states for ratification.
   Some legal scholars contend that line-item veto powers are
implied in a president's overall veto power. However, the concept
has never been tested.
   Such a notion, Edwards said in an interview, comes from ``chit
chat in conservative circles'' and has little constitutional
legitimacy.
   ``We are looking for a vehicle that might be a suitable test
case, but at this point we don't have one,'' Fitzwater said, adding
that it was anticipated such a move would provoke a court challenge.
   Were Bush to cast such a veto, Edwards said, ``a majority of the
members of the Judiciary Committee'' would promptly take him to
court.
   However, Edwards conceded the issue could remain in limbo for
years until it makes its way to the Supreme Court.
   ``Conservatives could have a field day,'' he said. ``They think
they could get several years of line-item vetoes.''
   Administration sources said it was unlikely the test case would
come soon because there is nothing before the president that is a
likely candidate.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said a
tentative target had been selected by White House counsel Boyden
Gray _ a provision once in the Interior Department appropriations
bill to ban a requirement that members of Congress keep a log of
contacts with lobbyists.
   However, the House stripped the provision from the bill before
the president could decide whether to exercise a line-item veto.
   White House officials are keeping a sharp eye out, however, for
another candidate. Sources said they are looking for a provision
that is unrelated to the main bill, and on which a veto would not
disrupt public policy or important services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891025-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PlantExplosion 2ndLd-Writethru a0789 10-25 0831</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plant Explosion, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0789,0852</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phillips Officials Survey Damages, Deaths at Explosion Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix editor's note: SUBS grafs 4-5, `Company
officials...', with three grafs to UPDATE with Phillips officials in Oklahoma
saying total 23 missing or dead, sted 24, but unable to explain discrepancy.
Picks up 6th graf, `Fires that...'. ^LaserPhoto HT3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACYZK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emergency crews searched the charred,
twisted rubble of a plastics plant Tuesday looking for victims of
fiery explosions that hurled wreckage miles away. At least two
people were killed, 22 presumed dead and 124 injured.
   ``There's just nothing left,'' Harris County Sheriff Johnny
Klevenhagen said after venturing into the still-smoldering plant
No. 5 at the Phillips Petroleum Co. complex.
   Officials located but could not remove the body of a second
victim Tuesday, partly buried in mounds of concrete and steel
beams. They said it would take heavy equipment to fully search the
ruins. One body was found Monday.
   Company officials in Pasadena said late Tuesday that the 22
missing workers were presumed dead.
   ``Any employee in that wreckage probably didn't survive,'' said
Jere Smith, director of public relations for Phillips.
   Later Tuesday, officials at the company's Bartlesville, Okla.,
headquarters said 19 Phillips employees were either dead or missing
and four contract workers were missing _ for a total of 23.
Spokesman Bill Wertz could not explain the discrepancy in the
victim totals.
   Fires that followed the blasts and were fueled by highly
flammable chemicals had been contained in small areas. Only a thin
column of smoke rose from the plant Tuesday, 24 hours after the
first explosions, which shattered windows three miles away and were
felt 25 miles away.
   Some entire buildings inside the chemical plant complex had
disappeared, Klevenhagen said, and elsewhere pipes and metal
framework were broken and dangling.
   ``It is devastated,'' Klevenhagen said. ``Major, major damage.
It's going to take extremely heavy equipment to remove the debris.
   ``The problem we're finding is that there are areas of the plant
we just can't get to. We're going to have to bring in a bulldozer
to make a road.''
   Klevenhagen and a crew of firefighters, safety inspectors and a
medical examiner made the first foray into the ruins at the complex
outside Houston.
   Frantic relatives gathered and scanned lists of known survivors
Monday night. Many continued their vigil outside the plant Tuesday.
   Mary De La Vergne, 38, found the name of her husband, Cipriana
Rodriguez, 43, on the list of missing workers.
   ``I had just taken him lunch,'' said Ms. De La Vergne. ``I heard
the explosion when I was going back home.''
   ``I can only keep on hoping,'' she said, collapsing into tears.
   Of the 124 people reported injured, 35 remained hospitalized
Tuesday, with six in critical condition. Dr. Paul Pepe, Houston's
emergency medical director, said the patient in the worst condition
was a woman with first- and second-degree burns over half her body.
   The plant, which produced 4.5 million pounds a day of
polyethylene plastic used in everything from milk jugs to grocery
sacks, erupted in a series of explosions that began just after 1
p.m. Monday, sending debris flying as far as six miles.
   The fire raged into the evening Monday, fueled by plastics and
by ethylene and isobutane gases, which are both used to make
plastics. By Tuesday it had been contained in small, controlled
areas.
   ``We don't feel there is any danger of further explosions,''
said Smith. ``We're past that.''
   As many as 400 firefighters battled the blaze. Water had to
pumped from a sewage treatment plant and the nearby Houston Ship
Channel after the explosions knocked out water service to the area.
   Officials arranged Tuesday to move hundreds of employees' cars
that were damaged in the parking lot and hampered cleanup efforts.
   More than 900 people work in three shifts at the plant, built in
1948 on an 800-acre site, said Dave Dryden, spokesman at Phillips
headquarters in Bartlesville, Okla. Workers whose jobs were
affected by the explosion will continue to be paid, Smith said, but
some may be laid off later.
   Officials didn't immediately know what caused the explosion.
   Phillips environmental director Bill Stoltz said a seal blew out
on an ethylene loop reactor, in which chemical reactions take place
to create polyethylene out of ethylene, a component of natural gas.
   The seal break released hydrocarbon vapor which ignited.
   ``There are 100 ways that could occur. We don't know how the
ignition occurred,'' Phillips President Glenn Cox said.
   The ethylene is fed to the plant through a pipeline from Sweeny,
about 75 miles southwest of the plant in this town of 100,000
people. The pipeline was shut down after the blast.
   Inspectors from the Environmental Protection Agency and the
Occupational Safety and Health Administration joined Phillips'
emergency response team in assessing damages.
   Robert Benz, plastic resins manager at the plant, said there was
no immediate damage estimate. ``It'll be a big number,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
