<DOCNO> AP891025-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0144EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-BudgetMath     10-25 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Budget Math,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Time is Money in Budget-Balancing Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush excused his lateness for an
award ceremony for math teachers by joking he was busy ``trying to
solve a few quadratic equations.'' He said the exercise was
``somewhat more difficult than balancing the budget.''
   Having pretty much given up on the notion of balancing the
budget any time soon, administration officials are trying to juggle
a slew of budget-policy equations to gloss over a continuing
impasse with Congress.
   Bush told the math and science teachers gathered in the Rose
Garden on Tuesday that he gets much of his scientific understanding
from the comic strips.
   He cited a Gary Larson cartoon ``where, after detailed
calculations, Einstein discovers that time is actually money.''
   Time was money, in fact, in the federal response to the
California earthquake.
   Last week's devastating quake gave rise to weekend speculation
that the administration was considering some form of tax surcharge
or increase _ most likely in the gasoline tax _ to help pay for a
federal relief effort expected to cost U.S. taxpayers around $3
billion.
   After all, that's a big chunk, and where was the money to come
from in an already overburdened federal budget?
   The tax speculation was fueled by Bush's own repeated failure to
rule out a tax increase when asked by reporters about the prospects
during his tour of the San Francisco Bay area's earthquake damage.
   However, it turned out that Bush _ once again _ could stick with
the ``no new taxes'' vow of the 1988 campaign.
   A quirk in the nation's budget laws allowed administration and
congressional officials to ``find'' money for quake relief without
having to face the issue of raising taxes.
   Congress' inability to agree on a deficit-reduction package for
the fiscal year that began Oct. 1 resulted in across-the-board cuts
of $16.1 billion under the Gramm-Rudman budget balancing law.
   But those cuts took effect Oct. 16 _ the day before the
earthquake _ and there is no mechanism for further automatic budget
reductions for another year.
   Thus, the Gramm-Rudman law ``is not applicable in this case,''
presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater declared. ``It's a
whole other ball game,'' he said.
   Budget Director Richard Darman and congressional budgeters are
finding other equations that, like Larson's Einstein, turn time, or
at least delay, into money.
   For instance, by not counting the cost of the government's
bailout of savings and loan institutions as part of the deficit,
the ``real'' degree of red ink is understated.
   And, the deficit is further made to look less menacing by
another accounting gimmick involving Social Security funds.
   The current surplus in the Social Security Trust Fund _ a
surplus that will vanish once baby-boom generation workers get to
retirement age around the turn of the century _ is being used to
help finance the deficit.
   The law requires money in the fund to be used to buy government
securities, which in turn are largely used to finance the deficit.
Not only are Social Security receipts being used to help retire the
national debt, but the fact that there's a surplus in the account
makes the deficit in other programs look smaller _ on paper.
   The ``real'' current budget deficit, discounting the Social
Security surplus and putting back in the costs of the S&amp;L bailout
and other programs now exempt, is closer to $250 billion than the
$116.2 billion projected by the OMB.
   Meanwhile, Bush doesn't have much to say these days about the
``flexible freeze'' he talked about during his campaign.
   But, he told the math and science teachers: ``I had a friend who
was so smart once that he knew how to convert meters to gallons. In
his head.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891025-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Soviet-Afghan     10-25 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Afghan,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Invasion a `Mistake,' but Soviet Aid Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years and 1.5 million Afghan lives ago,
the Soviet Union invaded Afghanistan. This week, Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze called it a mistake.
   But Shevardnadze gave no indication that the Kremlin was
withdrawing its military support to the government created by the
Soviet invasion.
   The current Afghan government ``was put in place as a result of
the intervention that he now says was a contravention of moral
norms,'' said Barnett R. Rubin, a specialist on Afghanistan at the
Washington-based Institute for Peace.
   In a speech to the Supreme Soviet on Monday, Shevardnadze
admitted the 1979 invasion of Afghanistan ``ignored universal human
values'' and involved ``gross violations of our own laws.''
   One-third of Afghanistan's pre-war population of 14 million has
fled the country since the invasion, and about 70 percent of the
nation's cities, villages and agricultural land have been
destroyed, according to administration estimates.
   It is unusual but not unprecedented for the foreign minister of
a superpower to acknowledge that a previous administration erred in
wreaking such devastation on another country.
   Cyrus R. Vance, in confirmation hearings before the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee before he became President Carter's
secretary of state in 1977, said the U.S. intervention in Vietnam
was wrong.
   ``In the light of hindsight, I believe it was a mistake to have
intervened in Vietnam,'' Vance testified, pledging ``not to
mislead'' Congress as Carter's predecessors had done in waging war
in Indochina.
   Carter continued the detente of his Republican predecessors, but
rapprochement with Moscow fell apart when the Red Army invaded
Afghanistan in December 1979.
   Carter canceled U.S. participation in the 1980 Summer Olympic
Games in Moscow, embargoed the sale of U.S. grain to the Soviet
Union and began to aid Afghan guerrillas.
   Despite Vance's capitulation, the United States still has not
granted diplomatic recognition to Vietnam's communist government,
14 years after the fall of the U.S.-backed government in Saigon.
Nor could Vance restore the lives of the 900,000 Vietnamese and
60,000 Americans who died in the conflict.
   And his statements did not mark a permanent change in U.S.
policy. President Reagan made it clear he did not share Vance's
opposition to military intervention abroad, as he armed Nicaragua's
Contra guerrillas, invaded Grenada and bombed the headquarters of
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi.
   Vance accepted blame, whereas Shevardnadze did not. Vance had
been an architect of the U.S. war in Vietnam, serving as Army
secretary and undersecretary of defense in the Kennedy and Johnson
administrations.
   Shevardnadze, in his speech, stressed that when the Red Army
invaded Afghanistan in December 1979, he and the current Soviet
leader, Mikhail S. Gorbachev, were non-voting members of the ruling
Communist Party Politburo.
   ``I found out about what had happened from radio and newspaper
reports. A decision that had very serious consequences for our
country was made behind the back of the party and the people. We
were confronted with a fait accompli,'' Shevardnadze said.
   A private American specialist on Afghanistan, Selig Harrison of
the Carnegie Endowment for Peace in Washington, said that during a
trip to Moscow in April he was told that Gorbachev was an early
opponent of the Afghan invasion, but there is little direct
evidence of that.
   ``There was substantial disagreement from the beginning,''
Harrison said. Gorbachev, who in 1979 was the Politburo member in
charge of agriculture, ``expressed objections to the diversion of
funds to the war that had been programmed for agriculture,''
Harrison said.
   Since the Red Army withdrew in February, Soviet military aid to
the Afghan government headed by President Najibullah has been
estimated at $250 million to $300 million a month by U.S.
government analysts, and at up to $400 million a month by Rep. Don
Ritter, R-Pa., a harsh critic of the Kremlin.
   By contrast, the United States has been sending an estimated
$500 million a year in military aid to mujahedeen guerrillas of
Afghanistan.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said, ``We
welcome the Soviet admission and encourage them to take the next
logical step to correct the Soviet mistake: Transfer of power from
the illegitimate (Najibullah) regime to a government acceptable to
all the Afghan people.''
</TEXT>
