<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0143EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ZeroTolerance     10-25 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zero Tolerance,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Zero Tolerance' Anti-Drug Program Relaxed Further</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is again easing the ``zero
tolerance'' anti-drug policy _ which required immediate seizure of
illegal drug users' cars and boats _ to let some people pay a fine
and go on their way.
   ``Our goal and intent is still user accountability,'' said
Customs Service senior special agent Ed Callahan, who oversees the
program along with the Coast Guard.
   The changes are intended to ``streamline the program, make it
more effective, more equitable,'' he said Tuesday.
   Officials hope the new guidelines will save time and money now
spent on seizing cars, trucks and boats at the borders or in U.S.
territorial limits because small amounts of illegal drugs are found
inside.
   This is the third easing in the zero tolerance program since it
began March 21, 1988, with then-Customs Commissioner William von
Raab declaring: ``There will be no mercy.''
   Under the original rules, a driver heading across the border
into the United States with a small amount of marijuana in his car
could be stopped and his auto seized by the government. If he
wanted to get the car back immediately, he would have to pay the
full value of the car plus any fines, said Customs Service
spokesman Dennis Shimkoski.
   The new guidelines were signed Oct. 18 by Acting Customs
Commissioner Michael Lane, but they were effective Oct. 11.
   The limits of drugs for which the new rules apply are an ounce
of marijuana or hashish, a gram of cocaine, heroin or
methamphetamine, one-tenth of a gram of PCP and 500 micrograms of
LSD, Callahan said.
   Under the new rules, Callahan said, the car still could be
seized by federal agents under certain circumstances, such as if
the driver were impaired by the drug found in the car. More likely,
the driver simply would be charged with a failure to report that he
was bringing marijuana into the country.
   That violation required a penalty of $5,000 to $10,000, but the
Customs Service has reduced that by 90 percent, he said.
   ``Realizing that that is not proportionate to the violation, the
penalty would be $500 for the first offense, $1,000 for the second
offense,'' Callahan said.
   ``If you pay that penalty at the time of the incident, you get
in your car and drive away,'' he said. ``If you refuse to pay the
penalty, the automobile will be seized, just as it was in the past,
because we have made an offer of a mitigated penalty, which you
have rejected.''
   But forget putting the fine on Visa or MasterCharge. The Customs
Service doesn't take plastic, only cash, a cashier's check or some
other negotiable instrument, he said.
   If the car's owner had loaned the auto to someone else who was
carrying a small amount of an illegal drug, the federal agent would
decide on a case-by-case basis what would happen to the car,
Callahan said.
   Since the zero tolerance program began, Customs has seized 8,076
personal vehicles such as cars, pickup trucks and motorcycles, 452
commercial-type trucks, 190 boats and 13 aircraft, Shimkoski said.
About 75 percent of the total value has been returned to its
owners, excluding penalties.
   The new guidelines also change the policy for boats found with
the user-amounts of drugs on board. Under the new guidelines, the
owners of all boats with such drugs on board will be issued a
summons requiring them to report to Customs in 15 to 30 days for
handling of their case, Callahan said.
   The government in February exempted fishing boats heading to or
from fishing grounds from immediate seizure. Other boats, however,
were subject to seizure, requiring the Coast Guard to bring the
boats to shore, keep them safe and take in the owners.
   Under the first revision in the policy, made in May 1988,
Customs or Coast Guard authorities who found small amounts of drugs
on boats more than 12 miles offshore would seize the boats only if
they appeared to be transporting drugs into the country.
   The change was prompted by an outcry that erupted when the
Atlantis II, owned by the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution of
Massachusetts, the $2.5 million yacht Ark Royal and the Monkey
Business _ the pleasure boat that former presidential candidate
Gary Hart sailed on with model Donna Rice _ were seized when small
quantities of drugs were discovered on board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
