<FIRST>r w PM-MilitaryConstruction     10-25 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Military Construction,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget for Overseas Bases Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional negotiators who say the United
States is shouldering a disproportionate share of the worldwide
defense burden approved an $8.5 billion military construction bill
that cuts President Bush's budget for bases overseas.
   ``We've seen the peak for military construction spending,'' said
Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., chairman of the Senate Appropriations
subcommittee on military construction.
   Thwarted in earlier efforts to reduce troop levels overseas,
members of the House and Senate targeted money used for such items
as barracks, munitions centers and storage facilities at military
installations worldwide.
   Specifically, negotiators approved an $85.5 million cut from the
$86.3 million Bush requested for South Korea. Several members of
Congress have called for reductions in the 43,000 U.S. personnel
stationed in South Korea _ an arrangement that costs the federal
government $2.6 billion a year.
   The House is expected to act Thursday or Friday on the
legislation, which members of the House and Senate Appropriations
subcommittees on military construction approved by voice vote
Tuesday.
   The bill, covering the fiscal year that began Oct. 1, provides
$500 million less than this year's level for military construction
but about $500 million more than Bush requested.
   Sasser, discussing the Senate version of the bill last month,
said the ``best way to make our defense dollar go further is to
secure a more equitable burden sharing from our allies.''
   Lawmakers agreed to cut all $40.8 million Bush requested for the
Philippines, basing the decision on upcoming negotiations on a new
treaty to replace the Military Bases Agreement.
   The U.S.-Philippines pact under which the United States leases
Clark Air Base and Subic Bay Naval Base will expire in September
1991. Talks are expected to begin in December, and Vice President
Dan Quayle said last month he was hopeful a ``mutually acceptable
agreement will provide for a longtime stay by the Unites States.''
   However, opposition to the U.S. presence is strong. Quayle's
visit to the Philippines was marked by demonstrations. Hours before
the vice president arrived, two American civilians were killed near
a U.S. base.
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino has refused to say whether
she favors keeping the U.S. bases, but she is expected to discuss
the issue when she visits Washington next month.
   Senate negotiators also accepted the House plan to allocate $500
million to close 86 military facilities in the United States, scale
back five others and change the mission at 54 other installations.
Bush had requested $500 million.
</TEXT>
