<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-Europe     10-25 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Europe,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush: No Turning the Clock Back in East Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New East German leader Egon Krenz ``can't turn
the clock back'' to prevent major changes and the possibility of
German reunification, President Bush says.
   In an interview in today's editions of The New York Times, Bush
characterized the changes as ``too inexorable'' to halt.
   The president also struck back at congressional critics of his
aid program for Eastern Europe, saying he's tired of complaints
from ``people who found Poland on the globe about three weeks ago.''
   Bush said changes taking place in Eastern Europe are
``absolutely extraordinary, but I'm not going to be stampeded into
overreacting to any of this.''
   He also said he does not share ``the concern that some European
countries have about a reunified Germany because I think Germany's
commitment to and recognition of the importance of the alliance is
unshakable.
   ``And I don't see Germany, in order to get reunification, going
off onto what some are concerned about, and that is a neutralist
path that puts them at odds, or potentially at odds, with their
NATO partners.''
   During a visit to Eastern Europe in July, Bush proposed a
three-year, $149 million aid package for Poland and Hungary to
encourage fledgling economic and political reforms. Since then,
under pressure from Capitol Hill, he has raised the value of his
aid proposal to about $450 million.
   Last week, the Democratic-controlled House _ with strong backing
from Republicans _ approved a three-year, $837 million aid package
for the two countries.
   Bush also has been stung by the rhetoric of Democratic leaders,
who have denounced the president's policy as ``timid.''
   In the Times interview, Bush said: ``Democrats on Capitol Hill
have been calling me `timid.' I have other, better words, like
`cautious,' `diplomatic,' `prudent.'''
</TEXT>
