<FIRST>r w PM-Abramsvs.Crowe     10-25 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abrams vs. Crowe,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Spat Between Two Former Officials: In This Corner...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One side effect of the U.S. inability to
dislodge Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega is a highly unusual
public spat between two influential former officials over who is to
blame for the Panama policy failure.
   The finger-pointing, mudslinging and mutual recriminations
carried out recently in prominent newspapers are a departure from
the normal practice of policymakers who disagree. Such disputes
usually are kept private, but the feelings on the Panama situation
run deeply.
   In one corner in this conflict is the Reagan administration's
top diplomat for Latin America, Elliott Abrams, and in the other is
the recently retired chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm.
William J. Crowe Jr. They have decided to take the gloves off.
   The hawkish Abrams, 41, quit government service in January. The
more dovish Crowe, 64, joined the military six years before Abrams
was born.
   Both have impressive educational backgrounds and relish
intellectual combat. But beyond that, the similarities between them
are few. Aside from their political differences, Abrams is a
relative bantam while Crowe is a 6-foot-tall, 200-pounder.
   Their dispute over Panama boils down to how far the United
States should have gone last year in its efforts to remove Noriega,
a question that has been revived following the failed coup attempt
against Noriega three weeks ago.
   Abrams fired the first salvo against Crowe two days after the
abortive coup attempt, complaining in a New York Times column that
Crowe and the joint chiefs used ``adamant pressure'' to reject
proposals for ``vigorous action'' against Noriega last year.
   These and other allegations prompted Crowe to rebut in a letter
to the Times that Abrams was both ``naive and reckless'' in his
advocacy of the use of military force in Panama.
   Crowe suggested that such attitudes are not uncommon among
``young political appointees who have never served in uniform.''
   In a telephone interview this week, Abrams rejected Crowe's
suggestion that Abrams was alone in the push for a more pugnacious
stand against Noriega.
   ``They were not my positions, they were the State
Department's,'' he said. As for the notion that reckless military
action is often the option favored by those who have never seen
active duty, Abrams replied that a military move in Panama was
urged by his boss, a well-known Marine combat veteran, former
Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Crowe did not return a reporter's phone call this week but said
in his letter to the Times that Abrams was wrong from the start
about Panama.
   Abrams, Crowe wrote, offered assurances that the mere threat of
economic sanctions against Panama would oust Noriega.
   ``He then argued with great confidence that actually imposing
sanctions would bring the general to his knees in two weeks. We
tried that and it didn't work either,'' Crowe wrote.
   Abrams denied that he suggested that economic sanctions would
ever be sufficient to bring down Noriega.
   He also suggested that Crowe attempted to influence public
opinion with newspaper leaks designed to discredit the options
Abrams was advocating on behalf of the State Department.
   In a country that adheres to the principle of civilian
supremacy, Abrams said, such activity by a uniformed officer is
``pernicious.''
   Crowe, meanwhile, told The New York Times this week that Abrams
had been ``bad-mouthing me all over town, saying, `Isn't it sort of
weird that the J.C.S. are wimps,' and things like that.
   ``I was getting a little bit tired of Elliott. Now that I'm free
to talk, I felt I should throw down the gauntlet,'' Crowe said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
