<FIRST>r w PM-Yellowstone-Timber     10-25 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yellowstone-Timber,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Park Service Director Passes Environmentalists' First Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists are giving National Park
Service Director James Ridenour high marks for refusing to allow a
lumber company to haul timber from national forests through
Yellowstone Park.
   ``I think the park service is to be commended,'' Michael Scott
of the Wilderness Society said Tuesday. ``It did the right thing.''
   Ridenour rejected a U.S. Forest Service argument that an
economic emergency justified the route.
   ``It would have set a very serious precedent,'' Scott said,
contending that private owners would have made similar requests if
the forest service had prevailed.
   Ridenour denied the request on the advice of lawyers who said it
violated federal regulations that prohibit commercial transport
across park roadways, said park service spokesman George Berklacy.
   Ridenour, Berklacy said, was concerned that the plan to move
about 20,000 truckloads of logs through the park would have adverse
impact on important grizzly bear, elk and bison habitats as well as
roadways.
   The forest service sold the timber from national forests
bordering Yellowstone that were partially burned during colossal
fires that swept through the park last year.
   Doug Crandall, manager of Brand-S Lumber Co. in Livingston,
Mont., which bought the wood, said the longer the partially burned
wood remained in the forest, the less value it would have.
   ``In a couple of years, no one will buy it,'' he said.
   However, park service lawyers said the need to sell the logs
quickly didn't constitute an emergency, Berklacy said.
   Ridenour made his decision Monday after meeting Friday with
Yellowstone Superintendent Robert Barbee, national parks lawyer
David Watts and the associate director for park operations, Jack
Morehead, Berklacy said.
   ``The forest service was not leaning on us,'' Berklacy said,
adding that there is an alternative route the lumber company may
use.
</TEXT>
