<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-KennedyCenter     10-25 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kennedy Center,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chief Reported in Trouble With Board</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Board meeting scheduled for noon EDT; lead prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of trustees for the John F. Kennedy
Center for the Performing Arts is moving to possibly reduce the
powers of its chairman and chief executive, sources say.
   The sources said Tuesday night the 45-member board, in a meeting
scheduled for today, may consider changes in the center's bylaws to
ease Ralph Davidson out of some of his responsibilities as the
day-to-day administrator of the cultural center.
   Davidson is reported to have been the source of friction between
some trustees in recent months.
   The sources noted that the bylaws provide for a president, a
position vacant since the center opened in 1971 as the nation's
only official memorial to President John F. Kennedy.
   The Washington Post reported today that 28 trustees said they
don't want to renew Davidson's contract, which expires in January
1991. Some told Davidson they wanted to negotiate an earlier end to
his tenure, the newspaper said.
   Davidson, a former Time Inc. executive, was hired in February
1988 to succeed Broadway producer Roger L. Stevens, the first
chairman. Stevens officially retired in August of this year after a
long transition.
   Reports of Davidson's difficulties surfaced after the board's
last meeting three months ago. One Kennedy Center source, who spoke
on condition of anonymity, said Davidson had come to believe
differences over the future of the center were intractable. The
source didn't detail the differences.
   The newspaper said differences concerned personality clashes and
other matters, not the artistic health of the center.
   Among the matters cited were Davidson's reported failure to
attend important parties, how to pay for an upcoming trip to the
Soviet Union by the National Symphony Orchestra and Davidson being
unreachable by British producer Duncan Weldon, most likely losing
the chance to mount Weldon's productions of Shakespeare's ``Richard
II'' and ``Richard III.''
   Harry McPherson, general counsel to the center, declined to
comment on the report. The newspaper said Davidson declined to
comment.
   The white marble building on the north bank of the Potomac River
houses six theaters and concert stages and provides much of the
cultural activity of the nation's capital.
   The president of the United States appoints 30 of the 45
trustees for 10-year terms; 15 members serve ex-officio,
representing Congress, government agencies and advisory bodies.
</TEXT>
