<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     10-25 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Extends Design Work on ATF Fighter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon is granting a six-month extension
for early design work on the Advanced Tactical Fighter, a program
criticized by House lawmakers.
   While Pentagon and Air Force officials said they were unable to
determine an exact cost for the delay, one report put it between
$250 million and $500 million.
   The ATF is slated to succeed the Air Force F-15 and the Navy
F-14D Tomcat fighter.
   Two design teams are competing to build the aircraft. Northrop
and McDonnell Douglas are building a prototype known as YF-23 while
Lockheed, Boeing and General Dynamics are constructing a prototype
known as the YF-22.
   With the additional six-month delay, full-scale development of
the plane is not expected to begin before mid-1991.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Gramm Adds to Speculation He May Seek Presidency in 1996</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Phil Gramm says he's
considering a race for the White House in 1996.
   ``I don't think that anybody who ever runs for city council
didn't ultimately think about running for president,'' Gramm, a
conservative first-term senator from Texas up for re-election next
year, said Tuesday.
   ``I have great ambitions to serve America and to do things that
I believe important to the working men and women of the country,''
said Gramm, who was first elected to Congress as a Democrat. He
later resigned from the House, switched parties and was elected to
his House seat in a special election.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Report Says 11 Percent of Young People's Deaths Caused by Guns</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government report showing guns cause 11
percent of young people's deaths underscores the need to lower
teen-age homicide rates, especially among blacks, Health Secretary
Louis Sullivan says.
   Since 1968, homicide has been the leading cause of death for
black males age 15 to 19. From 1984 to 1987, the rate for that
group jumped 53 percent _ to 60 deaths per 100,000, according to a
report released Tuesday.
   Firearms are responsible for about eight in 10 of these deaths,
the report said.
   The report, ``Firearm Mortality Among Children and Youth,'' was
released in conjunction with the premiere of a television
documentary on youth homicide, produced by the Department of Health
and Human Services. The program is being offered to stations
nationwide.
   ``Just as we have controlled so many childhood diseases, we must
now mount an equally aggressive campaign to rid our children's
lives of the causes and tools of injury and violence,'' Sullivan
said in a statement.
   The National Center for Health Statistics counted 3,392
firearm-related deaths among children age 1 to 19 in 1987 _ about
11 percent of all childhood deaths.
</TEXT>
