<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0302EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Brazil-Mudslide     10-25 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Mudslide,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illegal Landfill Collapses, Buries Shantytown</HEAD>
<UNK>By STAN LEHMAN ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An illegal man-made hill collapsed and
buried a shantytown under tons of mud, killing at least three
people and injuring dozens, rescue officials said. Many more were
feared dead.
   ``A wall of earth blanketed the area,'' said Francisco Tenorio
de Albuquerque, a fire official. ``We've rescued a few people, but
there are countless others under the mud.''
   The disaster occurred Tuesday in the Nova Republica slum in
southern Sao Paulo when the 100-foot-high hill of dirt excavated
from construction sites, located illegally near the slum, gave way
and smothered 56 wood and brick shacks, de Albuquerque said.
   Officials said they did not know exactly how many people were
buried in the mudslide. But survivors at the scene said about 400
people lived in the slum neighborhood.
   Geraldo Jacob of the Public Works Department said some houses
were buried under at least 45 feet of dirt.
   ``We heard a loud roar and the ground shook and we ran for the
door,'' Maria dos Prazeres, a survivor, said in a television
interview. ``We just had time to move before the walls came
crashing down on us.''
   Firemen and civil rescue crews arrived shortly after the
disaster and began pulling out victims, de Albuquerque said. The
helmeted workers, aided by residents, dug through layers of reddish
mud with axes, shovels, hoes and their bare hands.
   ``My house was destroyed and I haven't anywhere to go, but thank
God my family and I are still alive,'' said Jose Onofre, 49, a
mechanic who was returning home from a laundromat when the hill
collapsed.
   The injured were treated at a makeshift emergency medical tent.
Survivors were sheltered temporarily in nearby schools and
churches, de Albuquerque said.
   The dirt, about 400,000 cubic yards of it, was illegally dumped
near the shantytowns, Jacob said, adding that the developer
responsible had been fined several times.
   ``It will take at least one week before the full extent of the
tragedy is known,'' Jacob said.
   De Albuquerque said darkness and the remote location made rescue
operations slow and difficult.
</TEXT>
