<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0308EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-YellowstoneQuakes     10-25 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yellowstone Quakes,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Swarm Recorded in Yellowstone Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A swarm of 40 earthquakes struck the
Yellowstone National Park area, but only two were strong enough to
be felt, geologists said.
   The quakes began at 1:16 p.m. MDT Tuesday and were recorded
during the next nine hours, said Walter Nagy, who monitors
Yellowstone seismic activity for the University of Utah Seismograph
Stations.
   The quakes included two of magnitude 3.5 on the Richter scale of
ground movement, at 9:35 p.m. and 9:36 p.m. These were large enough
to be felt locally, he said.
   The quakes were six miles north of West Yellowstone, Mont.,
along the western boundary of the park.
   They struck within five miles of an extensive swarm sequence in
1985, which included 28 quakes of magnitude 3.5 or greater, Nagy
said.
   He said Tuesday's quakes were at the eastern end of the rupture
zone of the magnitude 7.5 Hebgen quake on Aug. 17, 1959.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area; a 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake,
capable of widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable
of tremendous damage.
   The Oct. 17 San Francisco Bay area quake measured 7.1 on the
Richter scale.
</TEXT>
