<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Dance     10-25 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dance,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joffrey Opens With `Two-a-Day'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Joffrey Ballet season at the City Center
opened with what was intended to be a salute to vaudeville. But the
$650,000, 40-minute entertainment isn't ballet, and it isn't a
thoroughgoing giggle to watch, either.
   ``The Pantages and the Palace Present Two-a-Day'' was seen
Tuesday night at the start of a season that runs through Nov. 19.
   After Paul Taylor's ``Arden Court,'' in which dancers looked
bright and sparkling, Gerald Arpino's duet ``Sea Shadow'' and the
New York premiere of ``Two-a-Day,'' a ``Roaring '20s'' supper ball
was held at Roseland.
   This was appropriate since some of ``Two-a-Day'' looked more
like a glitzy production of ``The Boy Friend'' _ the 1954 musical
about the '20s _ than like vaudeville.
   Arpino was inspired to create ``Two-a-Day'' by theaters which
alternated movies and live stage shows. He began with a color film
recreating the ending of the first ``A Star Is Born.'' Then,
presumably, the audience saw the dance part of the live show.
   The program explained who inspired each of eight scenes. Sally
Rand is named for the first, ``Les Plumes.'' With 15 women running
around waving big pink and white fans, it looked more as though
Busby Berkeley was its inspiration.
   There isn't much dancing in ``Two-a-Day,'' but there are a lot
of men carrying women aloft and a lot of just running around the
stage. Six men with top hats and canes were listed as tapdancing.
They did a few novelty steps and one expertly twirled his cane like
a baton.
   In more extreme novelty, Kathryn Ginden wafted about two long
pieces of silk with her arms and poles she held in her hands.
   Bathing beauties in middy tops and shorts formed a kick line.
   A Persian couple seemed like a chance for a dance, but mostly
Tom Mossbrucker carried Julie Janus over his head.
   Six couples spoofing Spanish dancing was close to camp; it was
the liveliest scene and probably the best.
   A girl with bobbed hair arrived from above, seated on a moon,
amid swooning men and was carried around by them before departing
skyward. The mild finale was meant to be a group Charleston.
   Most of the music was composed by Rebekah Harkness.
``Two-a-Day'' was commissioned by David H. Murdock to honor the
office of the president. It was underwritten by Murdock and the
Harkness Foundation for Dance. The premiere was Oct. 10 at Kennedy
Center in Washington.
   We wouldn't really want to see ``Two-a-Day'' again. Maybe there
should have been a couple of comics and a trained dog.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
