<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Edge Down In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
Wednesday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange also
fell.
   The dollar ended at 141.55 yen, down 0.55 yen from Tuesday's
close of 142.10 yen. It opened at 141.57 yen and moved between
141.40 yen and 141.79 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 84.15 points, or 0.24
percent, erasing its 71.90-point gain during the morning session of
trading. It had shed 58.97 points Tuesday.
   Dealers said the index started falling as investors began taking
profits from the early gains, while others stepped off to the
sidelines to wait and see how the New York market performs on
Wednesday.
   In currency dealings, the dollar in Tokyo started lower
following a similar downswing in New York overnight as American
investors sold the currency largely influenced by an 80-point
overnight plunge in the Dow Jones industrial average of 30 issues
on Wall Street, traders said.
   The dollar in New York ended at 141.56 yen Tuesday, down from
141.90 yen the previous day.
   Many Japanese market players expect the dollar to fall further,
due to a recent downtrend in U.S. interest rates, said a trader
with a major Japanese commercial bank, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
