<SECOND>PM-Britain-IRA,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>One of Guildford Four Says Police Harassed Him After Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of four people freed from prison last week
after a court ruled they were wrongly convicted of a 1974 Irish
Republican Army bombing says police harassed him at gunpoint in
Belfast after his release.
   Legislators Jeremy Corbyn and Chris Mullin of Britain's
opposition Labor Party said today they will question Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's government in Parliament about Gerard Conlon's
allegation.
   A unidentified spokesman for the Conlon family was quoted by the
British domestic news agency Press Association as saying Conlon,
35, was badly shaken after police in Belfast stopped a taxi in
which he and family members were traveling Tuesday.
   Police checked the identity papers of the people in the taxi,
the report said, then searched Conlon, a Belfast Roman Catholic, at
gunpoint.
   ``Guns were pointed at him and one ... officer turned and
shouted to a group of others, `This is Conlon,''' the report said.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern Ireland's predominantly
Protestant police force, said in a statement that if Conlon made an
official complaint, it would be investigated.
   Conlon earlier told reporters: ``After 15 years (in prison),
haven't they done enough to me and my family?''
   Searches by armed police are commonplace in Northern Ireland but
critics allege they are sometimes carried out to harass members of
the minority Catholic community.
   Conlon returned to Belfast after Thursday's ruling in London by
Lord Lane, the country's second-ranking judge, that he and the
other three members of the so-called Guildford Four were wrongly
convicted.
   The four _ Conlon, Patrick Armstrong, Paul Hill, and Carole
Richardson _ were serving life sentences for an Irish Republican
Army bombing at a tavern at Guildford southwest of London on Oct.
5, 1974, that killed five people. They were arrested shortly after
the bombing and tried and convicted in 1975.
   Lane quashed the convictions after a prolonged campaign, ruling
that police officers probably lied to get the four convictions. He
also reversed the convictions of Armstrong and Hill for an IRA
bombing at a tavern in the London suburb of Woolwich on Nov. 6,
1974. Two people died in that blast.
   The government has ordered an inquiry into alleged police
misconduct.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to drive the British out of
Northern Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant province
with the mainly Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
