<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Prophet     10-25 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Prophet,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Off-Beat Quake Prediction Gets County Geologist Sidelined</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leode, 3rd graf, cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Berkland moonlights as an earthquake
prophet, using theories based on lost pets and lunar tides, but it
may have cost him his job as geologist for the Santa Clara County
Planning Department.
   Berkland complained Tuesday that he got a ``bad rap'' after he
predicted the deadly 7.1-magnitude quake that killed dozens,
injured thousands and caused more than $7.1 billion in damage.
   Berkland's boss, Planning Director Leode Franklin, said she put
him on administrative leave because his reported claims of another
major quake in the Bay area in November were ``generating
unwarranted fear.''
   Berkland, 59, contends he predicted nothing more than a 3.5- to
5.5-magnitude quake between Nov. 11 and Nov. 18.
   ``This is a fantastic situation when I get accused of something
I didn't do,'' Berkland said in a telephone interview from his San
Jose area home.
   The geologist said he has been predicting temblors for 15 years
by studying tides, the movement of the sun and the moon and the
disoriented behavior of dogs, cats, birds and other animals
immediately before an earthquake.
   He said one clue is the large number of lost animal
advertisements printed in papers a week or two before an earthquake.
   Berkland theorizes that animals are far more sensitive than
people to changes in magnetic fields known to occur before quakes,
and when they get disoriented they lose their sense of direction.
   Berkland said his unorthodox methods have generated ridicule
over the years. He got wide attention after the Oct. 17 quake
because he'd said four days earlier that a quake measuring up to 6
on the Richter scale was about to hit.
   Ms. Franklin said Berkland was hired by the county to assess
geologic conditions for land use approvals in unincorporated areas.
   ``My real concern is the public as a whole sees him as a county
official,'' she said, adding that his hobby has interfered with
legitimate geologic assessments.
   If Santa Clara County wants information on potential quakes, Ms.
Franklin said it will rely on the state Office of Emergency
Services and the U.S. Geologic Survey. On Tuesday, the USGS said
there was a 50-50 chance of a major aftershock by Christmas.
   The USGS based its prediction on statistical data from other
quakes in the area and on geologists' observations of the San
Andreas fault. The agency has disputed Berkland's methods.
   Bill Bakun of the USGS said people ``can do just as well by
flipping a coin and be as successful as Jim Berkland'' in
forecasting temblors.
   Berkland claimed that he's been right on 240 of the 300 quakes
he has predicted during the past 15 years.
</TEXT>
