<FIRST>r a PM-PanamaCoup-Survivor     10-25 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama Coup-Survivor,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officer Involved in Coup on Noriega Speaks About the Failure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI LAKES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disorganized coup in Panama was
muddled by confusion and mixed feelings among officers about the
leader they sought to overthrow, said the highest-ranking survivor
of the attempt.
   Capt. Javier Licona escaped the killings and arrests that
followed the collapse of the Oct. 3 coup because he had been sent
to Fort Clayton during the operation to ask why U.S. troops hadn't
cut off roads or buzzed airports to block loyalists of Panamanian
leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   When the coup began to crumble, Licona remained at Fort Clayton,
the U.S. base in Panama, and eventually was flown with other
refugees to the United States.
   Licona, 36, talked to reporters Tuesday for the first time since
the failed coup. He had declined to speak publicly while he
arranged for relatives to join him and was interviewed by U.S.
officials.
   Licona said the coup's leader, Maj. Moises Giroldi, told him
U.S. support was promised at a secret meeting the night of Oct. 1.
   ``But when I arrived (at Fort Clayton) General Cisneros knew
nothing of the support they were supposed to give us,'' Licona
said. Maj. Gen. Marc Cisneros is the top U.S. Army official in
Panama.
   After a 20-minute phone call with someone, Cisneros gave the
order to block the roads, Licona said.
   ``Panamanian military planes had already left to transport in
the troops to support General Noriega. It was too late,'' Licona
said.
   Having seized Noriega during the coup attempt, Giroldi seemed
unsure about what to do with him, Licona said.
   ``He remained under Noriega's influence ... He had been very
loyal to the general,'' Licona said. Giroldi wanted Noriega to
leave power peacefully, but said he could remain in Panama, Licona
said.
   Licona said Giroldi failed to make a clear agreement with Maj.
Federico Oleochea, leader of the strongest unit in the capital,
Battalion 2000.
   ``He told me he was sure Major Oleochea would support us the
moment he asked. But he never spoke wwith him concretely about what
he wanted. I never trusted Oleochea,'' he said.
   Oleochea eventually joined Noriega in crushing the coup, Licona
said. Giroldi was slain.
</TEXT>
