<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0428EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     10-25 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minimal Damage to Shuttle During Galileo Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers prepared Atlantis
for a weekend piggyback ride on a jet to Florida after finding the
shuttle sustained very little damage to its heat-shield tiles
during its latest space flight.
   ``Everything's going smooth. We're on schedule to depart on
Saturday morning,'' said Lisa Malone, spokeswoman for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   Atlantis today sat inside a 100-foot-tall steel structure named
the ``mate-demate device'' as workers prepared to mount it atop a
modified Boeing 747 jumbo jet for the return to Kennedy Space
Center.
   Plans now call for the jet to carry the shuttle to Kelly Air
Force Base, near San Antonio for an overnight stop. But there was a
remote possibility the entire trip would be completed Saturday,
said Conrad Nagel, Atlantis processing director.
   Atlantis landed at this Mojave Desert military base Monday
following a five-day flight during which astronauts released the
Galileo spacecraft from the shuttle's cargo bay for a looping
six-year voyage to Jupiter.
   Initial inspection showed only 25 nicks caused by debris that
hit the tiles. Most can be repaired and only six tiles will need to
be replaced, Cindy Lodge, tile manager for the shuttle, said
Tuesday.
   No tiles were lost, she said.
   Inspection of Atlantis' brakes showed they looked ``really
good,'' while the shuttle's tires displayed only ``normal
scuffing,'' Nagel said.
   The mission was Atlantis' fifth, and was the sixth flight for
any shuttle since the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion that destroyed
Challenger and killed its seven crew members.
   The next flight of Atlantis, scheduled for Feb. 10, probably
will be delayed by up to six days because of the six-day delay in
launching the shuttle on the just-completed flight, Nagel said.
   Atlantis is scheduled to perform a classified Defense Department
mission in February.
   Two other shuttle flights are planned for this year.
   Discovery is scheduled for a Nov. 20 launch on a classified
Pentagon mission.
   Columbia, scheduled for launch on a 10-day mission Dec. 20, will
place a Navy communications satellite in orbit, then attempt to
retrieve the $15 million Long Duration Exposure Facility satellite,
which will fall into Earth's atmosphere in February unless it is
plucked from its decaying orbit.
   The satellite contains experiments related to the proposed
``Star Wars'' system to defend the United States against incoming
warheads. The experiments were meant to determine how materials
that might be used in a Star Wars system will fare in the hostile
environment of space.
   The satellite, launched by Challenger in 1984, also contains
millions of tomato seeds, which will be planted on Earth to learn
how weightlessness affects the subsequent growth of the seeds.
</TEXT>
