<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0430EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MineExplosion     10-25 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mine Explosion,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Methane Levels High in Mine, Inspector Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISONVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four of the 10 men killed in an
explosion at a western Kentucky mine were pulled from an area where
dangerous methane levels had been detected four days earlier, a
state official said.
   But the official, testifying Tuesday at a hearing on the Sept.
13 explosion, said the high concentration of the gas alone would
not account for the blast, which caused the worst U.S. mine
disaster since 1984.
   Interviews with workers at the William Station Mine indicated
that tests showed the air in one part of the mine was 6 percent
methane on Sept. 9, said the official, state mining inspector Billy
Smith.
   Methane is considered explosive at levels of 5 percent to 15
percent.
   Workers hung additional fireproof curtains and tightened
existing curtains to allow more air to flow into the mine and
decrease the high methane level. They also assigned a person to
monitor the methane level while they worked in the area, he said.
   ``From what I can find out, they warned oncoming crews they had
detected methane,'' Smith said.
   State investigators are considering several possible causes for
the accumulation of methane, including water that blocked the
mine's primary ventilation system and the absence of a regulator,
or curtain, to control the flow of air through the mine.
   Workers were not required to use the regulator, since mining in
the section had been completed on Sept. 6, and the four workers who
died in the area of high methane concentration were dismantling a
longwall mining machine, Smith said.
   The six other miners were working in another section.
   The explosion may have been sparked by torches believed to have
been in use before the explosion, or by rock falls that may have
caused electric cables to spark, officials said.
   Ron Siler, president of Pyro Mining Co., said officials did not
learn of the high methane level until after the explosion.
   Attorneys for widows of miners killed in the blast questioned
state and company officials knew about a partition that was removed
about 15 minutes before the explosion.
   Federal investigators have said tearing down the barrier may
have altered the air flow in the mine, allowing the explosive
methane gas to accumulate.
   Smith testified, however, that the partition was about 5,400
feet away from the explosion area and was unlikely to have affected
the level of methane in the blast area.
   Methane gas is given off as coal is mined. Smith said any
accumulation of the gas usually clears out of an area within two
days after mining ceases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
