<DOCNO> AP891025-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0453EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--LandlordDiscrimination     10-25 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Landlord Discrimination,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landlord to Pay Fine While He Appeals Living-In-Sin Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of discrimination for
denying housing to an unmarried couple will grudgingly pay a $700
fine with $1 contributions from supporters while he waits for a
ruling on his appeal, his lawyer said.
   The donations for Layle French came from around the country,
said the attorney, James Anderson.
   French, 33, was fined $1,048 on June 7 by an administrative law
judge who said French violated the state's anti-discrimination law
when he reneged on an agreement to rent his former house to Sue
Parsons.
   Parsons planned to live in the house with her fiance. French
later decided it would be against his religion to rent to an
unmarried couple.
   Anderson said French willingly paid the $348 portion of the fine
to reimburse Parsons for having to change her plans. But he
appealed the $700 civil penalty to the state Court of Appeals.
