<SECOND>PM-Toddler Rescued,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toddler Rescued From Busy Street, Police Arrest Parents, Babysitter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police rescued a 17-month-old child
found tottering in the middle of a busy street and charged his
parents and babysitter with child neglect.
   Edward Crawford was not injured when Detective Thomas Jackson
spotted the toddler Tuesday morning.
   Edward's older brother, Sam Baker, 4, also had wandered away and
was found later a block away in another busy area, authorities said.
   James Crawford and Melinda Baker were charged with child neglect
and were being held in jail Tuesday night under $500 bonds.
   The babysitter, Melanie Lashbrook, was charged with child
neglect and released on bond. She also was wanted on contempt
charges for not showing up in court on a prostitution citation.
   Lashbrook was sleeping with a third child, 2-month-old Joshua
Crawford, when the two older boys wandered away, said Youth
Guidance Officer Regenia Blanton.
   ``We were called out on a lost child and when we arrived we
realized a child had been found in the middle of Shelby Street,''
Blanton said.
   After the children were safe, police pounded on Lashbrook's
apartment door and woke her up, police said.
   The three children have been placed in the custody of the state
Department of Human Services.
   The parents came from Olean, N.Y., several weeks ago to visit
friends here, Blanton said. When their car broke down, they were
forced to stay with the friends, who live in Lashbrook's building,
until they could raise enough money to fix their car.
</TEXT>
