<FIRST>r i PM-Ghana-Firing     10-25 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ghana-Firing,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader Fires Only Female Member Of Ruling Council</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Ghana, Flight Lt.
Jerry Rawlings, has dismissed the only woman on the country's
ruling Provisional National Defense Council, state radio said.
   The report Tuesday on Accra Radio, monitored here, said Rawlings
fired Mrs. Aanaa Enin ``on the grounds of continued acts of
disrespect against members of the public and officials as well as
other conduct incompatible with revolutionary humility.'' No other
details were available.
   With Mrs. Aanaa the council had nine members. There was no word
on whether she would be replaced.
   Rawlings took power in a coup Dec. 31, 1981, set up the
Provisional National Defense Council and banned political parties.
    Last month Rawlings relieved Lt. Gen. Arnold Quainoo as head of
the West African nation's military, taking personal command.
Quainoo kept his position on the ruling council.
   Earlier this month Rawlings' government announced that several
military officers were being questioned in connection with an
investigation into conduct that could threaten state security.
   In 1957, Ghana became the first British colony in Africa to gain
   independence. The three civilian and four military governments
that preceded Rawlings' ended in coups.
