<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0619EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Earns-Media     10-25 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Media,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Down at Times Mirror, Up at Knight-Ridder, Washington Post, Lin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Longer version ran BC on financial wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Times Mirror Co. said that its third-quarter earnings fell 13.5
percent from a year earlier, while Knight-Ridder Inc., Washington
Post Co. and LIN Broadcasting Corp. reported earnings increases.
   Knight-Ridder reported Tuesday that its third-quarter earnings
rose 18.2 percent, Washington Post reported a 17.7 percent increase
and LIN Broadcasting a 19.4 percent rise.
   Times Mirror, the Los Angeles-based media and information
company, said earnings fell to $70.1 million, or 54 cents a share,
in the three months ended Oct. 1 from $81 million, or 62 cents a
share, a year earlier.
   But the 1988 earnings included a $26.5 million one-time gain on
the sale of timberland assets.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 7.2 percent to $873.9 million from
$814.8 million a year earlier.
   ``Softness in advertising volume, primarily at our Eastern
newspapers, continues to adversely affect newspaper publishing
revenues and operating profits despite improved results at the Los
Angeles Times,'' said Robert F. Erburu, Times Mirror chairman and
chief executive.
   Times Mirror also publishes Newsday, New York Newsday, the
Baltimore Sun newspapers, The Hartford Courant, The Morning Call in
Allentown, Pa., The (Stamford, Conn.) Advocate and Greenwich
(Conn.) Time.
   Erburu said strong results at the company's cable television and
professional publishing companies and improvement in broadcast
television partly offset the decline in newspapers.
   Knight-Ridder, the newspaper and business information company
based in Miami, said it earned $37.8 million, or 72 cents a share,
in the three months ended Sept. 30, compared with $32 million, or
57 cents a share, a year ago.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 7.5 percent to $541 million from
$503.1 million a year earlier.
   The operating profit at the newspaper division rose 19.5 percent
to $78.4 million, while the business information services division
had an operating profit of $2.5 million, up about fivefold from a
year earlier.
   Robert F. Singleton, chief financial officer, attributed the
earnings gain to ``softer newsprint prices, strong cost controls, a
lower effective tax rate and fewer shares outstanding.''
   The latest results also included a $4.2 million gain on the sale
of TV stations KTVY in Oklahoma City and WJRT in Flint, Mich.
   Knight-Ridder owns 29 daily newspapers including The Miami
Herald, The Philadelphia Inquirer, the Detroit Free Press and San
Jose Mercury News.
   For the first nine months, Knight-Ridder earned $185.2 million,
or $3.53 a share, up 67 percent from $110.8 million, or $1.94 a
share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month revenue rose 9.9 percent to $1.66 billion from $1.51
billion a year earlier.
   Washington Post Co., publisher of The Washington Post and
Newsweek magazine, said it earned $44.8 million, or $3.50 a share,
in the third quarter, up from $38.1 million, or $2.96 a share, a
year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 5.2 percent to $346.3 million from
$329.4 million a year earlier.
   For the first nine months, Washington Post earned $146.8
million, or $11.44 a share, down 36.6 percent from $232.2 million,
or $18.04 per share, a year earlier.
   LIN Broadcasting, a cellular telelphone, television and
specialty publishing concern based in New York, said earnings rose
to $24.6 million, or 46 cents per share, in the quarter compared
with $20.6 million, or 39 cents a share, a year ago.
</TEXT>
