<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0640EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths     10-25 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths,0665</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0526 to restore AP logo to Winters obit. A
separate for PMs moved on Barrett as a0519. ^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Edward Barrett</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward Ware Barrett, the founder of the Columbia
Journalism Review and a leading figure in American journalism, died
Monday after a long illness. He was 79.
   Barrett worked briefly for CBS before joining Newsweek as a
researcher-writer in 1933. He became Washington correspondent,
national editor and associate editor for Newsweek, staying there
until joining the war effort in 1942 as chief of what became the
Office of Strategic Services.
   He went back to Newsweek from 1946 to 1950 before returning to
government service as assistant secretary of state. In 1956, he
took over as dean of the university's Graduate School of Journalism.
   Barrett founded the Columbia Journalism Review in 1962, creating
the first national magazine devoted to journalistic criticism. He
was its publisher and editorial chairman from 1975 through 1982,
when he became publisher emeritus.
   He is survived by his wife of 50 years, Mason, and two
daughters, Margo, of New York City, and Lisa, of Burlington, Vt.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Carl Wise</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl T. Wise, former associate editor of
the editorial board at The News Journal papers, died Saturday of
heart disease. He was 89.
   Wise began his career by wrapping newspapers at the Sunday Star,
and in 1914 was a copy and errand boy for The Morning News. In
1930, he became a copy editor at The Morning News, and was named
city editor in 1933.
   Wise was named news editor of the Journal Every-Evening in 1943.
The newspaper later became the Evening Journal. He was appointed to
the editorial staff as associate editor of the News Journal papers
in 1954. Wise retired in 1961.
   He is survived by his wife, Anna Mickley Wise; two daughters,
Elise W. Snowberger of Louisville, Ky., and Anne W. Kappel of
Wilmington; five grandchildren; and a great-granddaughter.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Schumann</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John J. Schumann, the founder of a
newspaper and a radio station, died Monday after a sudden illness.
He was 91.
   No details of his illness were released.
   On Feb. 21, 1926, Schumann launched the first weekly issue of
The Vero Beach Journal. A year later, the Vero Beach Journal bought
the town's other newspaper, The Vero Press. The two papers merged
to become The Vero Beach Press-Journal, a twice-weekly paper which
published its first edition in 1927.
   He was chairman of the Press-Journal for more than 60 years.
   Schumann was a founding director and served as president of the
Indian River Federal Savings and Loan Co. He also was a founding
director of Westside Bank, Beach Bank and Sebastian River Bank.
During his career, Schumann also served as a director of the Indian
River Citrus Bank.
   In 1932-33, Schumann served on the Vero Beach City Council. He
also launched WTTB, Indian River County's first radio station.
   He is survived by his wife, Ruth; his son; a sister, Margaret
Fuller, of Glendale, Ca.; five grandchildren; and eight
great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Roland Winters</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roland Winters, an actor whose film roles
included Charlie Chan, died of a stroke Sunday at the Actors' Fund
Nursing Home. He was 84.
   He appeared in six films as the Confucius-quoting Chinese
detective, succeeding Warner Oland and Sidney Toler.
   Winters appeared in more than 80 movies and performed in several
Broadway plays.
</TEXT>
