<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0654EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Election     10-25 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Election,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Soviet Votes to Deny Communists Guaranteed Seats in Pa2liament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other top
Communists would have to campaign for their parliamentary seats in
local districts in 1994, much as the British prime minister does,
if the legislature gets its way.
   The constitutional change throwing all seats in parliament up
for popular election was approved by the Supreme Soviet Tuesday in
a 254-to-85 vote. However, it must be confirmed by the
legislature's parent body, the Congress of People's Deputies, which
meets at the end of the year.
   The change, part of a package of constitutional amendments
approved Tuesday, denies the Communist Party and other special
interests their guaranteed seats.
   Last year's political reform allocated 100 seats to the
Communist Party, which filled them by allowing the leadership to
select just 100 candidates.
   That allowed Gorbachev and most of the ruling Politburo to be
seated in Congress without facing a public vote of confidence.
   The Supreme Soviet, the 542-member full-time legislature, did
not require Gorbachev to mount a national campaign to win
re-election to the presidency, although some deputies had suggested
a direct election. That post will continue to be filled by the
Congress from among its members.
   The decision by no means restricts the Communist Party from
running candidates for geographical seats. Currently, 80 percent of
the 2,250 deputies are Communist Party members.
   Last year's political reform gave Soviet voters their first real
selection of candidates. But the election system was complex and
many people complained that the process was undemocratic and
favored the status quo.
   Two-thirds of the 2,250 deputies in the Congress were elected
from geographical districts. The other one-third were elected by
social organizations, and the reform package promised 100 seats
each to the Communist Party, the official trade unions and
cooperative organizations.
   The package allocated 75 seats each to the Komsomol (Communist
Youth League), to creative unions and to groups of women, academics
and veterans.
   The last 75 were split among smaller groups, with one seat even
going to an association of stamp collectors.
   Progressives complained that the system violated the principle
of one person, one vote. They said members of these organizations
had the opportunity to vote in each group as well as in their
geographical district.
   In practice, key reform groups such as the Baltic people's
fronts and groups of new private business cooperatives were shut
out of the privileged group in favor of long-standing agricultural
cooperatives and organizations controlled by the Communist Party.
   In one case, however, the prestigious Academy of Sciences capped
a stormy series of elections by choosing a slate of reformers that
included human rights activist Andrei Sakharov.
   The Supreme Soviet also decided Monday to allow the republics of
the Soviet Union to make their own decisions on whether their
presidents will be elected directly by the public or by their
legislatures.
   Although the Congress is supposed to handle final approval of
constitutional amendments, the legislators speeded up their vote
because a number of the republics are scheduled to adopt new
election laws this week that depend on the national amendments, the
official Tass news agency said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
