<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0751EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-FreewayReinforcements     10-25 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Freeway Reinforcements,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engineer Said Bridge Columns Didn't Need to be Strengthened</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior California transportation
engineer told a seismic workshop four years ago there was no need
to strengthen freeway columns until future earthquakes proved them
vulnerable, state documents show.
   Ray J. Zelinski, head of the freeway retrofitting program for
the state Department of Transportation, said the strengthening
wasn't necessary because the state's project to tie roadbeds
together with steel cables provided enough stability in an
earthquake, according to the documents released Monday by the
department.
   Some structural engineers have criticized California's
transportation department for not strengthening the columns on
Oakland's double-decked Nimitz Freeway, which collapsed during the
Oct. 17 earthquake, killing more than three dozen people. The
freeway's roadbeds were tied together.
   The cause of the collapse is still undetermined, however.
   ``It should be noted,'' Zelinski said in a paper delivered at
the 1985 workshop in New Zealand, ``that column retrofits have been
avoided by designing restraining features in a manner which
circumvents collapse due to column damage.
   ``Review of behavior of retrofitted bridges during earthquakes
will determine whether features will need improvement and whether
columns need to be considered for retrofitting,'' he said.
   Zelinski has been ordered by state transportation officials and
attorneys not to comment on his earlier remarks.
   However, James E. Roberts, chief of Caltrans' structures
division, said Zelinski still believes the roadbed tie-down system
should be enough to prevent failures, although the freeway's
collapse ``shakes his faith a little.''
   Roberts said he thought the tie-down project has been highly
effective.
   The state's program to strengthen columns through retrofitting
also may have been delayed in part because Zelinski and other
engineers did not believe it was necessary, said Roberts. ``That
tells you about why we haven't seen the need to move ... faster.''
   Also Tuesday, a former state bridge designer charged that the
Nimitz Freeway, which opened in 1957, was not built to the highest
standards of the time.
   Jim See, who is now the public works director for the city of
Pleasant Hill, said the freeway's columns were not sufficiently
reinforced with horizontal steel supports.
   Roberts said his staff is investigating See's allegations.
</TEXT>
