<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0803EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SatanicVerses     10-25 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Satanic Verses,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Author Denies Claim He Misled His Publisher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Salman Rushdie denied a newspaper's claim
that he misled his publisher about the likely impact his novel
``The Satanic Verses'' would have on the Moslem world.
   In a letter published today in The Independent, Rushdie accuses
the daily of telling a ``blatant untruth'' in a profile it
published Saturday of Peter Mayer, head of Viking Penguin
publishers.
   Rushdie has been in hiding for eight months since the late
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini called on Moslems to kill him for
allegedly blaspheming their faith.
   The threat also extends to Rushdie's publishers, and The
Independent's profile said Mayer ``has been forced to spend weeks
slipping through shadows.''
   It said that when Mayer first read the book, he ``missed the
religious time bomb ticking inside its covers.''
   ``Rushdie was asked twice, once before Penguin bought the book
and again afterward, what the now notorious Mahound chapter was
supposed to mean,'' The Independent wrote.
   ``He seemed curiously reluctant to explain. `Don't worry,' he
said at one point. `It's not terribly important to the plot.'''
   In his letter, Rushdie wrote: ``This passage is a lie. As
Penguin editorial staff in London and New York know, I discussed
the background to `The Satanic Verses' fully, answering all
questions.''
   He said he had ``failed to anticipate the distortions and
falsifications to which my novel was subsequently subjected.'' But
he insisted it was ludicrous to suggest he had dismissed some 75
pages of the novel as unimportant to the plot.
   ``The implication that I deceived Viking Penguin is wholly
unjustified, and, in the present circumstances, injurious.
Character assassination is also a sort of murder,'' Rushdie wrote.
   ``I am acutely conscious of Peter Mayer's present anguish ... as
I'm sure he is of mine,'' he wrote.
   Rushdie also took issue with the newspaper's suggestion that
since he had ``nothing to lose'' he was pressuring Penguin to
produce a paperback version of ``The Satanic Verses,'' despite the
danger that this would further inflame Moslem hostility.
   ``I'd like to think that your readers found the description of
my present situation ... more than a little distasteful,'' he wrote.
   The letter was dated Oct. 23 and gave no indication of where it
was written.
</TEXT>
