<FIRST>r a PM-TielessTeacher     10-25 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tieless Teacher,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teacher Suspended Over Tie Dispute Not Sure He'll Go Back to Teaching</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tod in 3rd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By T.J. SIMONEAUX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school teacher suspended for
refusing to wear a tie says he may not accept his job back despite
a judge's order that he be reinstated.
   ``I won't go back until I get something in writing that says,
`You're welcome to walk into the building,''' said Bill Webb
following a ruling Tuesday that his constitutional rights were
violated by a dress code banning denim for teachers and requiring
male teachers to wear ties.
   Kanawha County Circuit Judge Tod Kaufman ordered Webb reinstated
with back pay and court costs.
   Webb, 46, a math teacher at Point Pleasant High for 20 years,
was fired Dec. 21 after being suspended three times for refusing to
follow the dress code.
   A lawyer for the school board says an appeal of Kaufman's ruling
is virtually certain, and Webb says that would take months. So for
now, Webb says he will continue working at his Gallipolis, Ohio,
farm and auto repair shop.
   ``Knowing the people of Mason County the way I do, they'll take
the next eight months to appeal it, and we won't know anything
until June or July,'' he said.
   Diane Johnson, an assistant Mason County prosecutor acting as
the school board's attorney, says she'll ask Kaufman for a stay of
his order until the appeal is settled. She said she doesn't plan to
file for the stay until after the board's Nov. 6 meeting.
   She said, however, that if Webb shows up for work, the board
will file for a stay immediately.
   Johnson also said the dress code, which was revised to delete
the tie requirement, remains in effect.
   Webb contended that his apparel, usually jeans and a cotton work
shirt, caused no problems until Superintendent Charles Chambers
issued the dress code.
   In his ruling, Kaufman said Webb had been praised as an
``excellent teacher'' who had good rapport with his students and
said his dress had caused no problems.
   ``This dress code involves constitutional considerations which
include the right of the individual teacher to dress as he or she
chooses so long as no disruptive or distracting effects occur which
are detrimental to the educational process,'' the judge wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
