<DOCNO> AP891025-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0947EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-People-Midler     10-25 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Midler,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bette Midler's Attorney Claims Ford Deliberately Copied Singer For
Ad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for Bette Midler told a federal
jury that Ford Motor Co. was wrong to use a sound-alike version of
one of her hits for a car commercial after the entertainer declined
to sing it herself.
   ``They made the commercial anyway,'' said Peter Laird during his
opening statement Tuesday at the civil trial in U.S. District
Court. ``They deliberately imitated Bette Midler's voice.''
   Miss Midler is suing Ford and the Young &amp; Rubicam advertising
agency for $10 million over a 1986 television commercial for
Mercury Sable automobiles.
   The lawsuit contends the use of a sound-alike voice to recreate
a variation of Miss Midler's 1972 hit ``Do Ya Wanna Dance'' was
unfair competition and infringement of the right to publicity.
   Robert M. Callagy, an attorney for Young &amp; Rubicam, admitted
that the commercial imitated Miss Midler but he denied any
wrongdoing under federal copyright laws.
   ``We had the right to imitate the Midler sound recording,''
Callagy said. ``It was consistent with the law.''
   Young &amp; Rubicam hired one of Miss Midler's former backup singers
to perform the song after Miss Midler's manager turned down an
offer for her to do the ad.
   Howard Privett, an attorney for Ford, said the automaker was not
involved in making the commercial and only approved it for airing.
   Miss Midler, whose recent films include ``Beaches'' and
``Outrageous Fortune,''was not in court Tuesday but was expected to
testify later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
