<HEAD>UNDATED: and blue.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 23
   Sun-Sentinal, Fort Lauderdale, Fla., on flag burning:
   The Senate's rejection of a constitutional amendment that would
have made burning the U.S. flag illegal has set the stage for
another round in the acrimonious battle over protection for the
national colors. ...
   Before the Supreme Court overturned the Texas statute, 48 states
had laws prohibiting flag burning.
   That is a ringing expression of the public will. Whatever
courage the issue takes, Congress and the president should
rememeber there has been no call for political bluster.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 20
   The Garden City (Kan.) Telegram on flag burning:
   If you haven't heard the news yet, the Senate failed ... to pass
a constitutional amendment to ban burning of the American flag.
   President Bush has indicated he will allow the bill (banning
flag burning) to become law without his signature.
   Now Washington can quit playing Trivial Pursuit and turn its
attention to more serious matters.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 24
   Delaware County Daily Times, Primos, Pa., on Oliver North's
pension:
   Ollie North's corps of heavyweight pals continue to toil on
behalf of the convicted felon.
   Their latest effort involves the $23,000-a-year pension North
earned for 20 years of military service.
   The Navy stripped North of the pension after he was convicted
and sentenced to probation in July for his role in the Reagan
administration's secret scheme to arm the Contras.
   Now some lawmakers are vowing to get the ex-Marine his pension.
They justify their action by saying Congress never intended that
its anti-shredding law deprive North of his pension.
   The Senate is scheduled to vote Nov. 3 on a bill to exempt North
from the penalty imposed after his conviction on three felonies. ...
   Sen. Orrin Hatch already has the solution: Give North special
treatment.
   Said the Utah Republican, ``Regardless of what happened in the
Iran-Contra affair, people have a difficult time understanding why
he is being denied the pension that he earned.''
   Sure he earned it, by giving 20 years of military service to his
country. But then he decided to shred some documents and in doing
so gave up any right he has to that money.
   Sorry, Ollie, you don't deserve the pension.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 19
   The Bulletin, Bend, Ore., on students and cultural ignorance:
   American college students ... have a high degree of cultural
ignorance. The cry already has gone up for American colleges to do
something about that. ...
   A majority of the (college seniors responding to a recent Gallup
Poll commisssioned by the National Endowment for the Humanities)
were unable to say who was president at the time of the Korean War.
Only 58 percent knew that the Civil War was fought sometime between
1850 and 1900.
   Lynne V. Cheney, chairwoman of the National Endowment for the
Humanities, used the poll results to call for a mandatory 50-hour
college curriculum which would cover five areas of knowledge. ...
   But a good part of the pressure is being put on the wrong
institutions. Students arrive in college having had 12 or more
years of formal schooling. What the test results show is that they
are being cheated in their elementary and high schools, not that
the colleges have failed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 19
   The Joplin (Mo.) Globe on foreign investment:
   Congress has set its cap to stifle foreign investment, which if
happens would be a gross miscarriage of lawmaking.
   The legislative move doubtless has been spurred by a surge of
foreign investment in the United States in recent years, causing
people to worry about American dependence on other countries.
   Such concerns are unwarranted for a couple reasons.
   One, foreign investment is not nearly as extensive as popularly
thought.
   Two, foreign investment brings to the U.S. economy significant
advantages.
   Frankly, Americans don't or can't (because of taxes) save enough
to cover the government's massive deficits. So the United States
needs investments from abroad to continue economic growth and
sustained vitality.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 23
   The Dallas Morning News on the CIA:
   Should the Central Intelligence Agency be given the authority to
become involved in coups that result in the assassination of
foreign leaders? ...
   The Bush administration seems bent on rescinding a 1976 order
issued by President Gerald Ford barring U.S. involvement in
assassinations. ... Bush is entering a mine field. ...
   Weakening the Ford directive would be a virtual invitation to
the CIA to strike out on adventures that may ultimately be
counter-productive. The temptation to assist in the elimination of
despised foreign leaders would be great, but does the executive
branch really want to get into the business of playing God? ...
   It may be reasonably asked if CIA involvement in foreign
assassinations might not result in foreign agents showing less
restraint against U.S. political figures here. ...
   The United States should promote democracy by promoting
democracy. That means giving encouragement to the opponents of
dictatorships, teaching them about the principles of our system of
government and helping promote the conditions under which democracy
thrives. ...
   But under no circumstances short of outright war are the
interests of democracy promoted by dialing CIA for murder.
</TEXT>
