<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   10-25 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0847</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: for murder.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 20
   The Seattle Times on East Germany:
   In a season of extraordinary events in Eastern Europe, the
removal of Erich Honecker from power in East Germany must rank
among the most dazzling and perplexing.
   The man whose communist principles were steeled by a decade in a
Nazi prison, the man who supervised construction of the Berlin
Wall, is the same leader who had the wit 18 years ago to renew
political and financial ties with West Germany.
   Honecker, 77, was deposed in favor of his younger protege, Egon
Krenz, 52, who is credited with the same dogged commitment to
hard-line ideology.
   A startling conclusion that may be slow to form in the West is
that Honecker was removed not for his failure to crush a nascent
pro-democracy movement, but for dragging his feet on economic
reforms. ...
   Honecker, who outlasted the Nazis, could not keep pace with his
country's desire for political and economic reform.
   If Krenz is no more responsive, he may not last, either.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 21
   The State, Columbia, S.C., on East Germany and Hungary:
   (Egon) Krenz has made it clear that the Communist Party (in East
Germany) will maintain its leading role and will not share power
with any other political element. In truth, there's no organization
to share it with right now.
   East Germany has not allowed an independent movement like
Poland's Solidarity to emerge, and there is no reform element
within the party as there is in Hungary. But the pressures building
up in the country will create outlets, and ... Krenz had better
have the flexibility to deal with (them).
   While the leaders were changing in East Berlin, the party was
changing in Budapest. Hungary's Communist Party took the
unprecedented step of declaring itself politically bankrupt and
recasting itself as the Socialist Party. Then Parliament abandoned
one-party rule by allowing parties to freely form and compete in
elections scheduled for next year.
   The Communist label proved to be poison when Poland allowed free
elections earlier this year. Just how complete this reformation is
is not yet apparent. The new party elected the former Communist
Party chairman as its president, but the reformers seem to have the
upper hand. ...
   As we watch these events, we should remember that Moscow will
probably tolerate more deviation in Hungary and Poland than in East
Germany, which it considers the centerpiece of its empire. East
German dissenters might do well to keep that in mind, too.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 18
   The Gloucester County Times, Woodbury, N.J., on communism:
   More than 52,000 East Germans, eager to escape their communist
``paradise,'' have pushed into West Germany since Sept. 10.
   In other developments showing that people are growing more
restive under communist oppression, formerly independent countries
brought under control of the Union of Socialist Republics, such as
the Baltic states of Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, are eager to
throw off the reins of the Russian-dominated federation.
   In Hungary, a historic Communist Party congress overwhelmingly
approved scrapping the 70-year-old party. ...
   We in the United States are well aware of the shortcomings of
political democracy and economic free enterprise. But our system
has proved far superior to communism and other
government-controlled economies.
   Those who have experienced firsthand ... the denial of rights
and economic failure of communism ... long to share our way of life.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 23
   Vicksburg (Miss.) Evening Post on coca growing:
   Years before crack became the scourge of America, Bolivian
peasants grew coca plants. Some of the leaves were sent aboard to
be processed into illegal cocaine, but mounds of them wound up in
the marketplaces of La Paz.
   The highlands Indians were in the habit of chewing the leaves to
help numb their hunger and the piercing cold.
   The presidents of Bolivia, Peru and Colombia surely must
understand that many Indians view coca as a medicinal plant that
helps them survive their harsh environment. Now, with demand for
cocaine and crack soaring in the United States and Europe, the
peasants have come to see it as an export crop that helps ease
their pain with money.
   The peasants, who find themselves whipsawed between drug
outlaws, guerrillas and the government, need a substitute for their
coca cultivation.
   The presidents of the three drug-troubled Andean countries
decided at their meeting to invite President Bush to meet with them
within 90 days. We hope he goes with some concrete ideas for wooing
the coca-growing peasants away from the drug traffickers and
left-wing guerrillas.
   The possibilities include targeting U.S. agricultural assistance
to the remote regions where coca is now grown. The peasants need
help in modernizing their herding and growing practices. The United
States could provide farm equipment and loans for growing legal
crops.
   Easing trade barriers into the United States for legal
agricultural exports from the coca-growing areas may also help.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
