<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1014EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     10-25 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Invites Legislators to Sell Him on Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon's Christian leader, Gen. Michel
Aoun, has invited Christian and Moslem lawmakers to a meeting to
discuss their plan for ending the country's 14-year-old civil war,
a newspaper said today.
   Aoun has criticized the plan for not setting a deadline for the
withdrawal of Syrian troops from Lebanon but was quoted as telling
Paris' Le Figaro newspaper that he has not completely rejected it.
   Sources said Lebanese Christian legislators, who agreed to the
accord in Saudi Arabia on Sunday, feared Aoun would have them
arrested if they returned to Beirut. Aoun said he would guarantee
their safety.
   ``I have not said a categoric `no' to the accord,'' Le Figaro
quoted Aoun as saying from his compound at Baabda, near Beirut.
   ``On the contrary, I accept all the institutional reforms.
Whether they are good or bad, I won't interfere. It's an affair
between Lebanese,'' Aoun said.
   The 63 Lebanese legislators, evenly divided among Moslems and
Maronite Christians, met in Taif, Saudi Arabia for three weeks to
come up with a plan to end the war.
   The changes they approved Sunday would shift political control
from the Christian minority to the Moslem majority. On Monday, the
committee issued a document calling on Parliament to meet no later
than Nov. 7 in Lebanon to ratify the reforms and elect a president.
   Aoun invited the legislators, even those he considers traitors,
to a meeting.
   ``The text of Taif hasn't been ratified yet. If they are
convincing, maybe I would be in agreement with them,'' Aoun was
quoted as saying. He also said he would accept a new president
``even if they decide the president should no longer be a
Maronite.''
   Aoun, who declared a ``war of liberation'' in March to drive the
40,000 Syrian troops from the country, found fault with the accord
for not setting a date for a Syrian withdrawal.
   ``It's a vague redeployment, then, two years after the
installation of new institutions, a retreat. How much time is all
this going to take?,'' Le Figaro quoted him as saying.
   Aoun also said he would not run for the presidency, Le Figaro
reported.
   In Paris, popular Maronite Parliament deputy Raymond Edde became
the first politician to announce publicly he would be a candidate.
   Edde, who has been living in self-imposed exile in France
following attempts to assassinate him in Lebanon, said he would
remain in Paris and not travel to Beirut for the election.
   Also today, rival Shiite Moslem militias clashed in a brief
firefight in Syrian-policed south Beirut. Police said one person
was killed and two were wounded.
   The clash pitted gunmen of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God, against fighters of the mainstream Shiite Amal
militia.
   A police spokesman said the 30-minute clash with automatic
rifles broke out over ``traffic priority'' between a member of
Hezbollah and an Amal militiaman in a narrow alley of south Beirut.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891025-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1017EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MobWitness     10-25 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mob Witness,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Calls for Investigation Into Coddled Protected Witness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mob witness whose protective custody
is under investigation ``played court'' with his family in a
judge's chambers while they lived in an apartment in a police
station, his wife says.
   Mayor Joseph R. Paolino Jr. on Tuesday announced an internal
investigation of the Police Department over the custody of Peter
Gilbert, a three-time murderer who was a key witness in two trials
of alleged organized crime figures.
   It will be at least the third investigation of the confessed
murderer, who died of a heart attack in June 1988 while on his way
to an unsupervised skydiving trip in Connecticut. He had been
expected to testify against other alleged organized crime figures.
   Packages containing 9 grams of cocaine were found in Gilbert's
parachute bag. Later investigations showed that while in police
custody, Gilbert was paid at least $98,000, took other trips,
charged meals and liquor to the state and bought bullets and
jewelry at taxpayers' expense.
   Paolino, who said he didn't know Gilbert was in department
custody, ordered the probe because of the ``outrageous
revelations'' of recent weeks, including reports that a police
officer was videotaped joking with Gilbert about the free ride they
were getting.
   In the 30 months Gilbert, 43, was in police custody, he was kept
at a police station apartment with his wife, Debra, and some of his
seven children, then transferred in January 1988 to a safe house
while he served a 10-year sentence for murder.
   Mrs. Gilbert told WPRI-TV in an interview broadcast Tuesday that
while the family lived in the apartment at the police station ``the
policeman would stand in the hall and Peter and I would go skating,
and our daughter had a little three-wheeler and would be skating
all over. ...
   ``We went into the (municipal) judge's chambers and played
court, and we had fun,'' she said.
   The apartment formerly had been a matron's living quarters.
   The Providence Journal-Bulletin reported Saturday that Mrs.
Gilbert had a videotape of a police officer joking with her
husband. Mrs. Gilbert told the newspaper the tape shows Detective
Steven Cross with his arm around her husband's shoulders saying,
``The criminal justice system has been good to us, Peter, huh?''
   Cross, who was recently transferred from the detective division
to the auto squad, which investigates stolen cars, was not in the
office for comment Tuesday, said Police Officer Bob Lauro. Cross
told WPRI-TV that his comment was ``play acting'' to make Gilbert
feel at home.
   WPRI-TV broadcast footage Tuesday that it said was taken as
Gilbert cavorted with his police keepers at a Florida motel pool.
The station said it obtained the footage from Mrs. Gilbert.
   The film showed the incident with Cross and pictures the station
said Gilbert took of a new van, one of several vehicles he
apparently bought with a $20,000 credit union loan obtained while
under police protection.
   Gilbert also videotaped a police officer sleeping in a poolside
lounge chair while he was supposed to be guarding the witness.
``Hard time, tough duty,'' Gilbert said on the tape as he laughed.
   The sleeping officer has since committed suicide, WPRI said.
   Gov. Edward D. DiPrete announced a state police investigation of
the Gilbert case last week at the recommendation of the U.S.
attorney.
</TEXT>
