<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1023EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Romania     10-25 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romanian Leader Castigates Reforms in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian leader Nicolae Ceausescu has
condemned reforms by some of his Soviet bloc neighbors, telling a
Communist Party plenum in Bucharest that they represent an
abandonment of socialism.
   Ceausescu, who has ruled for 24 years, also accused unnamed
``imperialist circles'' of trying to destroy world communism, the
official Agerpres news agency reported today.
   The two-day plenum debating ideological questions began one day
earlier than scheduled. Observers speculated that the early opening
may have been prompted by unease over Monday's mass commemoration
in Hungary of its 1956 anti-communist uprising.
   More than 100,000 people gathered for the officially condoned
rallies in Budapest, which were broadcast nationally by Hungarian
television and could be watched by many of Romania's
1.7-million-member Hungarian minority.
   Ceausescu rules over an old-style communist state clinging to
tough economic policies that have produced the Soviet bloc's worst
food and energy shortages. He criticized Hungary and Poland by name
in a speech last week for their market-oriented economic reforms.
   Poland has the East bloc's first non-communist government and
Hungary this week declared itself a democracy. Hungary's Communist
Party even changed its name.
   The Romanian party plenum, also called to discuss better food
supplies for its hard-pressed people, is the last such meeting
prior to a party congress scheduled for Nov. 20-25. The congress
formally is the highest decision-making body of the Communist Party.
   ``Steps are taken in some (Soviet bloc) countries that weaken
the positions of socialism and open the way to the reinstatement of
capitalism in various forms,'' Agerpres, monitored in Vienna,
quoted Ceausescu as telling the plenum Tuesday.
   ``Some openly declare that they want to take various capitalist
countries for a model,'' Ceausescu said. ``It is hard to
understand, though, that socialism can be developed and improved by
taking as a model the capitalist system divided into classes of
oppressors and oppressed.''
   Although he named no countries, Ceausescu clearly targeted
Hungary, Poland and the Soviet Union, as he spoke of economic
reforms that would ``open the path to the lowering of the people's
living standard.''
   ``Facts in some socialist countries that switch to the `market
economy,' (such as) mounting inflation and profiteering ... spell
danger to the very development of the socialist society,''
Ceausescu said.
   In his address, Ceausescu made clear that Romania will stick to
the centralized economy that has brought it widespread food
shortages and have left many Romanian houses cold and streets dark
in the past four winters.
   He warned that ``the imperialist circles' actions against
communism ... are a great danger for detente and cooperation.
   ``If they continue they will inevitably lead to an even more
drastic deterioration of the world situation,'' Ceausescu said
without elaboration.
   Romanian exiles abroad listening to his speech broadcast by
Radio Bucharest noted that Ceausescu stuttered and raised his voice
several times throughout the two-hour, frequently emotional, speech.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
