<FIRST>u i PM-NATO 1stLd-Writethru a0544 10-25 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0544,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Chiefs Wrap Up Nuclear Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Cheney urging caution, new
quote; Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Wrapping up ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILAMOURA, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO defense ministers today welcomed
Soviet promises to cut its powerful military forces but urged the
Kremlin to do more to slash its tactical nuclear weapons.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and other ministers of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization also applauded in their final
statement Moscow's pledge to remove a disputed radar station in
Siberia.
   Cheney cautioned that the Soviet Union remains a powerful
military force and said ``there is great uncertainty about how
events will unfold in the Soviet Union.''
   Wrapping up two days of nuclear strategy talks on the southern
Portuguese coast, the officials said they ``looked forward to the
prompt and full implementation of this commitment.''
   After the meeting, Cheney was to fly to London for talks with
British officials on the European leg of a three-week foreign tour.
   In the final statement, the ministers said they ``were
encouraged by the changes underway in the Soviet Union and some of
its allies.''
   ``Nevertheless, we recognized the continuing capability of the
forces of the Warsaw Pact for offensive military action,'' it said.
   It expressed concern about ``substantial capabilities'' in
Moscow's space program and its nuclear modernization program.
   ``We welcomed the announced Warsaw Pact unilateral force
reductions and looked forward to their full implementation,'' the
statement said.
   However, the ministers said the cuts ``would have little effect
on the Warsaw Pact's nuclear capability and, in particular, on
their continuing massive superiority in short-range nuclear missile
systems.''
   ``We therefore called again on the Soviet Union to reduce
unilaterally its short-range missile systems to current NATO
levels,'' the statement said.
   The ministers' agenda was somewhat overshadowed by Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze's unusually candid speech on
Monday.
   He told the Soviet legislature that the Krasnoyarsk radar
station violated the 1972 U.S.-Soviet Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty
and said it would be removed. The facility stood in the way of
further arms treaties, he said.
   ``It was an acknowledgement of what the United States has
maintained for a long time,'' said a senior U.S. official, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   ``We obviously applaud this recognition'' and the pledge to
dismantle the installation, he said.
   West German Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg called
Shevardnadze's speech ``remarkable'' and ``a true sign of glasnost
(openness).''
   ``The fact that he stands up and says straight out that
Krasnoyarsk was a violation of the (ABM treaty) is a whole new
language,'' he told reporters.
   Shevardnadze said the decision to take down the giant,
phased-array radar had been criticized internally. But, he said,
``We are saving the ABM treaty and opening the way to the
conclusion of a treaty on strategic weapons.''
   The United States has argued the ABM treaty prohibited the
deployment of large radar stations, capable of giving early
warnings of missile attacks anywhere except on the periphery of
U.S. or Soviet territory. The Krasnoyarsk radar is deep within
Soviet Siberia.
   In his speech, Shevardnadze also called for dissolving NATO and
the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   Not surprisingly, the NATO officials did not share his vision of
an end to the Western allliance.
   ``I can assure you, we're not thinking of disbanding NATO,''
Stoltenberg said.
   All 16 NATO nations, except France, attended the meeting. France
does not belong to the alliance's integrated military structure.
Iceland, which has no armed forces, has observer status.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
