<SECOND>PM-Plant Explosion-Effects, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0503,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fatal Explosion Could Spark Economic Plunge in Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Plant Explosion, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf bgn: `The blasts...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   to CORRECT number presumed
dead to 23, sted 25, and missing to 21, sted 23.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fatal explosions that ripped through
a plastics plant also may send shock waves through the industry,
driving up plastics prices worldwide, analysts said.
   Analysts said if the Phillips Petroleum Co. plant is destroyed
or shut down for a while, manufacturers of plastic products like
milk jugs and grocery bags could be scrambling for plastic at
higher prices.
   ``If the whole thing goes down, there are going to be shortages
all over the place,'' said analyst Bill Kuhlke of DeWitt &amp; Co., a
Houston-based chemical consulting company.
   The blasts at the plant killed as many as 23 workers and injured
124. Two bodies have been recovered and up to 21 others are missing
and presumed dead.
   Phillips, which supplies up to 19 percent of a common plastic
base, has been leading several companies building factories along
Texas' Gulf Coast. Company officials said Phillips supplies about a
third of the world's plastics and its polyethylene plant No. 5
represented a large chunk of their production power.
   Phillips spokesman Dave Dryden of the company's Bartlesville,
Okla., headquarters said the effects of losing the plant were
unclear.
   ``We're very early in the assessment,'' Dryden said.
   Phillips bought the 800-acre Pasadena plant in 1948, and turned
it into a huge complex employing more than 900 people. It produces
more than 2 billion pounds of plastics per year, three-quarters of
it polyethylene.
   ``The damage we know of was primarily to the polyethylene
plant,'' Dryden said. The plant was scheduled to increase
production 15 percent in 1990.
   He said Phillips has another plant at the complex that makes 500
million pounds of polypropylene annually, which is used carpet
fibers and films. And another part produces K-Resin for plastic
water bottles and rigid, but flexible plastic cups like the ones
used on airlines. That production was to increase production by 50
percent in 1990.
   Consultant Earl Simpson with Bonner &amp; Moore Associates said he
had brushed off talk of a polyethylene price increase the industry
hoped to see Nov. 1, but the Phillips explosion may allow a rise of
about 3 cents per pound. Product in storage will only last about
five weeks, he said.
</TEXT>
