<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     10-25 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>20 Police and Soldiers Arrested For Atrocities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 20 policemen and soldiers
were arrested on charges of rape, attempted extortion and other
crimes during the struggle with Sinhalese extremists, officials
said today.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne said several military officers
were among those arrested in the past month. Lt. Gen. Hamilton
Wanasinghe, the army commander, said if the arrested are found
guilty ``they will be dealt with most severely.''
   Wijeratne said among those arrested were five policemen in a
Colombo suburb on charges of raping a young Sinhalese woman they
detained for questioning after claiming she belonged to the
People's Liberation Front, a radical Sinhalese group.
   Police arrested four army lieutenants who allegedly posed as
front members and tried to extort money from a wealthy businessman
in the town of Wellawatte just south of Colombo, said Wijeratne,
who is also deputy defense minister.
   The officials commented after The Sun, an independent newspaper,
voiced concern about an increase in the number of serious crimes
blamed on police.
   At least 5,000 people have been killed in the Sinhalese
heartland of central and southern Sri Lanka since July 1987, when
the government signed an Indian-brokered accord designed to end an
insurgency by Tamil militants in northeastern Sri Lanka.
   The government has blamed most of the deaths on the front, which
has assassinated fellow Sinhalese who serve or back the government.
However, human rights activists, opposition politicians and
religious leaders say government forces and pro-government
vigilante groups are responsible for many killings.
   The People's Liberation Front accuses the government of selling
out the rights of the mainly Buddhist Sinhalese majority by making
too many concessions to the Tamil minority. Tamils, who are mostly
Hindus, account for 18 percent and say they are discriminated
against.
   Tamil guerrillas launched a series of massacres of Sinhalese
civilians. Those attacks, plus the ensuing war pitting the
guerrillas against Sri Lankan soldiers and later Indian
peacekeepers, have claimed 11,000 lives since the Tamil separatist
insurrection began in 1983.
</TEXT>
