<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0515,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Hears Change of Venue Arguments in Trial of Miami Police Officer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with today's court action, raise
first reference to defense attorney, picks up at 9th graf pvs bgng, `Jurors
are...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Witnesses called by attorneys for a white police
officer charged with manslaughter in the shooting of a black
motorcyclist testified today about past racial disturbances in the
city.
   However, Circuit Judge Joseph Farina restricted evidence about
plans for quelling any violence that might stem from the officer's
trial.
   The judge and attorneys for both sides agreed Tuesday that riots
were likely if Officer William Lozano were acquitted.
   Lozano's attorney, Roy Black, who wants the trial moved from
Dade County, did succeed today in admitting a Metro-Dade police
contingency plan into evidence, although Farina ordered it sealed
for now.
   Also introduced was a poster from the ``Overtown Comrades'' that
the defense described as an inflammatory and offered as proof of
efforts to whip up anger over the trial in the black community.
   Lozano is charged with two counts of manslaughter in the deaths
of motorcyclist Clement Lloyd, 23, and passenger Allan Blanchard,
24.
   Their deaths touched off three days of racial disturbances in
January.
   Farina, who will rule on Black's motion for change of venue
after hearing more testimony and arguments today, said Tuesday he
didn't need to hear lengthy testimony about the possibility of
violence.
   ``There very well may be post-trial difficulties,'' said Farina.
``But we don't need individuals testifying to that.''
   One person was killed, 11 others were wounded by gunfire and 13
buildings were burned in the rioting after Lloyd was shot while
being chased by police. Blanchard was fatally injured when the
motorcycle crashed.
   The defense attorney had subpoenaed scores of witnesses and
wanted to enter newspaper clippings, videotapes and other documents
into evidence to show that public agencies were preparing for more
violence.
   ``Jurors are going to think if they find my client guilty, there
is not going to be a riot, but if they find not guilty, there is
going to be a riot,'' Black said. ``It's unfair for ordinary people
to have that much responsibility on their shoulders.''
   But Farina threw out most of the subpoenas and limited the riot
testimony during the change of venue hearing to police reports from
four previous racial disturbances in the 1980s, all of which
resulted after a jury found a policeman was innocent of shooting a
black man.
   The judge and attorneys decided Monday to seat a large jury pool
just before the change of venue motions so the panel could be
ordered to avoid reading or listening to testimony on the motions.
   Prosecutors sought to quash Black's subpoenas, but did not
dispute the threat of violence in case of acquittal.
   ``There is a degree of probability that a riot will occur,''
said Roy Wood, an assistant Dade County attorney.
   Police have acknowledged contingency plans for a post-trial
riot, including the purchase of 700 gas masks, arrangements for use
of two armored vehicles and the possible use of the Orange Bowl to
house those arrested during any disturbances.
   Farina said careful questioning of potential jurors should
determine whether their deliberations will be affected by the
chance of possible riots.
   ``I have no doubts that there are a number of individuals in
this community who will accept that responsibilty, as difficult as
it may be,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
