<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0582 10-25 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0582,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Discusses Lebanese Peace Prospects in Phone Calls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Mitterrand in lead and 4th graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush discussed the prospects for
peace in Lebanon in telephone calls with Pope John Paul II,
President Francois Mitterrand of France and King Fahd of Saudi
Arabia, the White House said today.
   Bush on Monday congratulated Fahd and the Arab League for
arranging talks in Taif, Saudi Arabia, that led to a breakthrough
agreement among Lebanese parliamentarians on a new national charter
for governing the torn country.
   Bush expressed the hope that the parliamentarians' work `` would
be a step in the direction of Lebanese reform,'' said Marlin
Fitzwater, the White House spokesman.
   The president also called Mitterrand to discuss the situation in
Lebanon, and on Tuesday he called the pope, who has made repeated
efforts to promote a peaceful settlement in the 14-year civil war
between Lebanon's Christian and Moslem factions.
   Fahd was one of three Arab leaders designated by the Arab League
last spring to press for constitutional reforms in Lebanon to end
the strife there. The Saudis are urging Lebanon's Parliament to
convene in Beirut Nov. 7 to elect a new speaker, approve political
reforms and elect a new president.
   Sixty-two Lebanese politicians fashioned the proposed charter in
three weeks of negotiations at Taif.
   Fitzwater said Bush was also on the phone Monday with West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl ``to discuss events in Germany,
particularly after the resignation of (Communist party chief Erich)
Honecker and the selection of a new leader of East Germany.''
   Bush, in an interview published Wednesday in The New York Times,
said he was not worried about the possibility of a reunified
Germany heading off onto ``a neutralist path that puts them at
odds, or potentially at odds, with their NATO partners.''
