<FIRST>r a PM-CivilRightsSlaying     10-25 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Civil Rights Slaying,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson City Council Votes to Reopen Medgar Evers Murder Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: E C Foster is cq in 13th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEGHERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city council is asking the state and
county to reopen the murder case of civil rights leader Medgar
Evers more than a quarter-century afer he was gunned down.
   A council member said the move indicates how much attitudes have
changed.
   ``Hopefully, the district attorney will follow through to
correct an injustice of the past,'' Councilman Louis Armstrong said
Tuesday after the vote.
   ``The motive for introducing this resolution was to begin
healing a festering wound created by a subversion of justice by the
state Sovereignty Commission,'' Armstrong said of the now-defunct
segregation watchdog agency.
   ``I think it was incumbent upon the city council to protect the
rights of one of its citizens who was murdered by bigotry and
hatred.''
   The city council's vote came a day after The Clarion-Ledger, a
Jackson newspaper, reported that in 1964 investigators from the
sovereignty commission helped the defense screen prospective jurors
at the first of two trials of Byron De La Beckwith, who was charged
in Evers' death.
   Armstrong's resolution asked the state attorney general and
Hinds County district attorney to reopen the investigation and
prosecution in connection with the civil rights leader's June 12,
1963, slaying.
   A secretary in the office of District Attorney Ed Peters said he
would be out of town all week and and no one else could comment on
whether he would reopen the case. Jim Warren, a special assistant
to Attorney General Mike Moore, said the decision would be up to
Peters. ``We would, however, offer him any assistance, if he so
requests,'' Warren said.
   The council, which has a majority of white members, voted 4-2,
with one council member absent.
   Beckwith was tried twice in 1964 by all-white juries for the
murder of Evers, a NAACP field secretary who was gunned down in the
driveway of his Jackson home. Both trials ended in hung juries.
   Prosecutors said Beckwith's fingerprint was on a gun found in
bushes near the slaying, and witnesses placed his car near the
scene.
   Beckwith said his gun was stolen.
   Councilman E C Foster said Tuesday that he voted for the
resolution because he'd like to see the case solved.
   ``Primariy, it's clear that the murderer is still free, and so
if by reopening the investigation we can bring the murderer to
justice, then I think that's what should happen,'' he said.
   Councilman Derwood Boyles, who voted against the resolution,
said Monday, ``As far as I'm concerned, that comes under the
heading of the district attorney and the attorney general, and I
don't personally think I should be telling them what to do.
   ``I think if Mr. Evers was here, he'd tell us we have more
important things to do than that,'' said Boyles.
</TEXT>
