<FIRST>u i PM-Iraq-RebuiltCity 1stLd-Writethru   10-25 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iraq-Rebuilt City, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0591,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraqis Mark Rebuilding of War-Devastated Port</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with details of festivities in
Faw; picks up 6th graf: Before the...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people poured into
streets and parks of the capital today to celebrate reconstruction
of the southern port of Faw, which was almost destroyed during the
war with Iran.
   ``Faw has risen again, dressed in colorful clothes woven from
the eyelashes of our valiant men and built upon their sweat,''
President Saddam Hussein said in the televised speech.
   The government has spent millions of dollars to celebrate what
government newspapers called ``a miracle of construction, building
a new town in only 114 days.''
   Arriving in Baghdad to take part in the celebrations were
Jordan's King Hussein and presidents Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and Ali
Abdullah Saleh of North Yemen. Saudi Arabian Defense Minister
Prince Sultan delivered a congratulatory letter from King Fahd.
   Official celebrations in Faw were expected later in the week,
part of three days of festivities in Baghdad and the rebuilt city.
Faw lies 400 yards from Iranian outposts.
   Before the Persian Gulf war with Iran broke out in September
1980, Faw was a dusty oil terminal town with population of about
50,000. The Iranians captured the town in February 1986, but Iraqi
forces retook it in April 1988 in the first of a series of
offensives. Hostilities ended with a cease-fire in August 1988.
   Saddam thanked other Arab countries for taking part in the
celebrations and making donations for the rebuilding of the town.
   Schools and most government departments were closed as students
lined the main highway from the airport to downtown Baghdad, waving
pictures of the arriving Arab leaders and flags of their countries.
</TEXT>
