<FIRST>r a PM-MealProgramOuster     10-25 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Meal Program Ouster,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Director of Meal Program Once Hailed by Reagan Is Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials have ousted operators of a
program providing meals to the elderly that former President Reagan
once praised as a national model but later was accused of
mismanagement and poor service.
   The county Council on Aging ordered locks changed Tuesday at a
recreation center where it canceled the contract under which
Frances Freeman operated the South Park Area Council's meal program
for six years.
   On Thursday the Tucson Urban League will take over the remainder
of a $70,000 contract to feed 75 to 80 people a hot lunch each day,
said Marian Lupu, executive director of the Council on Aging.
   Ms. Freeman's group had the contract with the state- and
federally subsidized Council on Aging since 1983. She ran a
food-for-the-elderly program with local funds for 13 years before
that.
   Ms. Lupu said monitoring by the Council on Aging and an audit by
the state Department of Economic Security showed ``a great number
of irregularities in the way the program has been delivered to the
participants.''
   The Council on Aging accused Ms. Freeman's group of cutting meal
portions and mishandling sign-in sheets that are supposed to verify
that recipients get served, said Diana Edwards, a council program
monitor.
   In 1982, then-President Reagan pointed to Ms. Freeman's meals
program as an outstanding model of social service volunteerism at a
time of federal cuts in social programs.
   Ms. Edwards said her agency worked with Ms. Freeman's group
since 1983 trying to bring it into contract compliance. She said
that last year it lost the contract for home delivery of meals, in
May for transportation of about 25 people to the center and on
Tuesday for providing meals at the center.
   George Logan, assistant director for management review at the
Department of Economic Security in Phoenix, said the attorney
general's office would determine whether criminal charges should be
filed. He said, ``There is that potential; very definitely.''
   Margo Cowan, a community activist who identified herself as
secretary of the South Park Area Council, told The Associated Press
that she, Ms. Freeman and other officials of the group would have
no comment.
   But the Tucson Citizen quoted Ms. Freeman as saying she never
was told directly that Council on Aging funding was being cut off
and first heard about it Tuesday morning as she was on her way to
the center.
   Ms. Freeman said she plans to keep helping elderly people
without the funding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
