<FIRST>r a PM-BLARelease     10-25 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BLA Release,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Figure In 70s Racial Killings Is Paroled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of four Black Liberation Army
members who killed two white teen-agers in 1974 in an effort to set
off racial violence has been paroled from prison after serving 14{
years of a 199-year term.
   Brad Evans, 34, was freed Tuesday after he agreed to move to
DeKalb, Ill., where he will live with a brother and work in data
processing. He agreed not to return to Florida without permission
of the state Parole Commission, officials said. He is on parole
until 2173.
   Relatives of Stephen Orlando and Stephen Lamont Roberts, the two
teen-agers killed in random attacks that BLA members said were
launched to spark a racial war, vehemently opposed Evans' release.
   The Jacksonville BLA wasn't connected with a West Coast group of
the same name.
   Evans' last two attempts for parole were rejected because of
opposition from the victims' families and the judge in the case,
and the commission at one point pushed Evans' next parole review
date to 1999.
   But after Evans' family devised a plan for him to live in
Illinois, the commission agreed to free him.
   ``The majority of the commission was convinced that the Brad
Evans who went to prison in troubled times is not the Brad Evans
there now,'' said Guy Revell, chairman of the Florida Parole
Commission.
   After Orlando, 18, was shot and stabbed, the group sent a tape
to his mother, Marian Mallory, saying he had been ``tried, found
guilty and executed'' for political crimes against blacks.
   The group also sent tapes to television and radio stations
warning that ``more white devils will die.''
   Evans was convicted of second-degree murder in Orlando's death
and pleaded guilty to second-degree murder in Roberts' death.
   Jacob John Dougan, the leader of the group, whose death sentence
has been overturned twice, was resentenced to death for Orlando's
murder in 1987.
   Elwood Clark Barclay also was sentenced to die for Orlando's
murder, but the Florida Supreme Court reduced his sentence to life
in 1980.
   A fourth defendant, Dwayne Crittendon, was sentenced to 199
years. His parole hearing is set for August.
</TEXT>
