<SECOND>PM-Double Shooting, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0570,1015</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sirens Over Car Phone Lead Police to Victims of Abduction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS in 2nd graf that baby is two months premature, sted
one. INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf pvs bgng, `Stuart, 29, ...' to UPDATE
with quotes from news conference today. Pickup 12th graf, `Police have...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police scoured the city today for suspects in the
abduction and shootings of a pregnant woman and her husband, whose
mobile phone transmitted the sounds of sirens that directed
rescuers to them.
   The woman died of a head wound after doctors delivered her
two-months premature baby by Caesarean section. Relatives said they
were told there was little hope for the infant's survival. The
husband was in critical condition.
   Charles and Carol Stuart were abducted while leaving Brigham and
Women's Hospital, where they'd attended a birthing class Monday
night.
   Their abductor forced them to drive to the city's Mission Hill
district, then robbed and shot them.
   Stuart then used the car's cellular phone to call police, but
could not give his location. When he lost consciousness, operators
listened on the phone for the sirens of passing police cars.
   Mrs. Stuart's baby was delivered at the hospital she'd left
hours earlier. A hospital spokeswoman would say only that the baby
was alive but would not comment further.
   The couple had chosen Christopher as the baby's name because
doctors had said he would be born the day after Christmas, said
Rosemary Leone, aunt of the 33-year-old Mrs. Stuart.
   ``If you could only see how beautifully formed he is,'' she
said. ``He looked perfect. They told us to stroke his face because
they said he would need a lot of love.''
   ``She wanted this baby so badly. But they don't think there's
much hope for him,'' she said.
   ``She had what she always wanted. A good job, a husband, a
house, and soon a baby. And then one bastard came and took it all
away,'' said Mrs. Stuart's cousin, Cheryl Leone.
   Stuart, 29, general manager of a fur store in Boston's Back Bay,
remained in critical condition today with a gunshot wound to the
abdomen, a Boston City Hospital spokesman said.
   At a news conference today, Joseph Saia, deputy police
superintendent, said Stuart's condition had kept him from assisting
in the investigation.
   ``Hopefully he will recover and provide invaluable help to the
case,'' he said.
   Police have no suspects but Mayor Raymond Flynn said
fingerprints were found in the Stuarts' car, along with two
.38-caliber slugs.
   ``We now need people to come forward and provide whatever
information they have, whether they saw something or heard
something,'' Flynn said. ``Police officers will be combing the
(Mission Hill) public housing development and talking to everyone
and anyone.''
   The gunman apparently thought the Stuarts were police officers
after seeing the car phone, said Joseph Dunford, deputy police
superintendent. Before shooting the couple, according to Dunford,
the gunman said, ``I think you're five-o,'' slang for police.
   Stuart battled for himself and his wife in the minutes after
they were shot and left for dead, police said. But as he spoke to
police on his telephone, he faded in and out of consciousness while
his pregnant wife lay dying next to him.
   He cried in pain and confusion. Not knowing where he was, he
couldn't tell state police dispatcher Gary McLaughlin where to send
help.
   ``Oh man, it hurts and my wife has stopped gurgling, she's
stopped breathing,'' Stuart called out, according to a transcript
released Tuesday by police.
   Then there was silence.
   ``Chuck, can you hear me? Chuck, Chuck can you hear me, buddy,''
McLaughlin pleaded. ``Pick up the phone, Chuck. Chuck? Come on
Chuck, can you hear me, Chuck? Chuck, pick up the phone, I can hear
you breathing there Chuck, come on, buddy.''
   Still, nothing.
   McLaughlin instructed Stuart at one point to open his door or
window to see if he could identify some landmark, so that help
could find him.
   But Stuart only replied: ``I'm blanking out.''
   ``You can't blank out on me, I need you man. Chuck? Chuck?''
   In a desperate effort to home in on the car, police in cruisers
were told to flick their sirens off and on, one by one. McLaughlin
was able to tell which cruiser was near the Stuarts' car by
listening to the sirens coming over the phone.
   ``Get my wife out,'' Stuart told the officers who found him.
   The ambulance crew that cae to the aid of the Stuarts had been
riding with a camera crew from the CBS-TV series ``Rescue 911,''
which tells real-life stories about rescue operations.
   The crew videotaped Stuart regaining consciousness and talking
about the attack as paramedics worked on him en route to Boston
City Hospital, and was allowed into the emergency room, CBS
spokesman Mike Silver said in New York.
   The mayor asked that every available detective be put on the
case, said police spokeswoman Jill Reilly.
   At a news conference, Flynn was asked why the killing was
getting so much attention when shootings occur almost daily in
other distressed areas of the city.
   ``No matter whether it happens in Roxbury, Charlestown, Back Bay
or Beacon Hill, whatever area or color or ethnicity, it will be
handled in the same aggressive and fair way by the Boston Police
Department,'' he replied.
   Ted Kakas, an owner of the fur store where Stuart has worked for
eight years, said couple had just celebrated their fourth wedding
anniversary. The child was the couple's first.
   The couple, from suburban Reading, were mindful of the rise of
violence in the city, friends said.
   ``Chuck and I had talked about the number of shootings that had
gone on there,'' said fellow employee Peter Jaworski. ``It seemed
almost daily, the number of people getting shot.
   ``So many senseless things going on,'' Jaworski said, choking on
his words.
</TEXT>
