<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Drugs     10-25 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Drugs,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Countries Step Up Cooperation to Combat Drug-Trafficking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocaine-producing and consuming nations
wrapped up a two-day meeting Wednesday, agreeing to tighten their
dragnet on drug traffickers and encourage coca farmers to plant
other cash crops.
   Spain and other European countries that have seen a dramatic
expansion in the drug trade in recent years pledged greater
involvement.
   ``This meeting represents a great step forward in broad-based,
material support by the major European countries,'' said Acting
U.S. Assistant Attorney General Edward Dennis, adding: ``It would
not be helpful to elaborate on the specifics of material offered.''
   He said the group also agreed to work toward streamlining the
extradition process and establish a network of treaties ``that will
eliminate any hiding place in the world'' for drug traffickers.
   The meeting brought representatives of the 12-nation European
Economic Community, the United States and Colombia, Peru and
Bolivia together for the first time to discuss material and legal
methods to halt the flow of cocaine.
   In the past three years the amount of cocaine seized in the EEC
has tripled as drug traffickers turn from the United States in
search of new markets.
   An official said cocaine seizures in Spain last year represented
62 percent of the EEC total of about six tons, and that Italy is
another major point of entry into Europe.
   ``We feel that the recognition (by EEC countries) of our
situation represents a rather big step forward,'' said Armando
Lecaroz, Peru's special drug ambassador.
   Spanish Interior Minister Jose Luis Corcuera said the group
agreed on the importance of investigating and halting the
laundering of drug money and would look into ways to control the
export from EEC countries of chemicals used to transform coca leave
paste into cocaine.
   On Tuesday at the close of a Hispano-French summit in the
Spanish city of Valladolid, French President Francois Mitterrand
called for a crackdown on money-laundering and said banks ``will
have to open up their books and their accounts.''
   Most of the world's coca leaves are grown in the Andean
highlands of Peru and Bolivia. Most of the coca leave paste is
processed into cocaine and shipped to the rest of the world from
Colombia.
   Representatives of all three producer countries stressed the
importance of crop substitution programs to wean growers away from
coca as well as export incentives and financing to make substitute
crops commercially attractive.
   Participants agreed in a final communique to draw up and secure
funding for appropriate crop substitution programs.
   Spain's special drug coordinator Miguel Solans said concrete aid
in the form of vehicles, training of police and narcotics agents,
weapons and judicial protection programs would be negotiated
bilaterally.
</TEXT>
