<DOCNO> AP891025-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1343EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ResidentialExplosion 2ndLd-Writethru a05</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Residential Explosion, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0590,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Search for More Possible Victims, Clues to Cause of Blast</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with mayor touring area, saying no more deaths expected,
other details. DELETES outdated material throughout. No pickup. Bim Orrenmaa
in 5th graf is cq. Note town is pronounced Kahn'-ee-aht.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONNEAUT, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nine-block residential area was strewn
with smoldering debris today after a series of explosions destroyed
three homes, killing two people and injuring 13 others.
   ``It's like a war zone. There's a lot of damage,'' Conneaut
Mayor Lewis Shiley said after surveying the neighborhood.
   A dozen agents from the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms were to search the rubble later today for clues of the
explosion, Shiley said. The mayor said it was presumed there were
no more deaths. Officials earlier feared more victims might be in
the wreckage.
   ``It's pretty much out. There's still some smoldering,'' Chet
Arcaro, Conneaut building inspector, said of the fire that broke
out after the series of explosions about noon Tuesday.
   Fire Chief Bim Orrenmaa said officials were investigating the
possibility that the 20 minutes of explosions, of which the largest
occurred midway through the series, may have been caused by illegal
fireworks.
   ``I thought it was an earthquake,'' said Lori Punkar, who lives
three blocks away in this town of 13,000 people just west of the
Pennsylvania state line.
   ``This felt like someone hit the house,'' she said. ``Like a
semi hit the house. All the neighbors ran out in the street saying,
`What was it?'''
   W.A. West said the blast rocked his house two miles away. ``We
were eating lunch and it shook the floor. I had no idea what it
was.''
   Orrenmaa said he saw what appeared to be firecrackers strewn
around the house where the largest explosion occurred.
Investigators had not yet determined whether all of the explosions
occurred at the same house.
   The fire chief said the pattern of the blasts led him to suspect
illegal fireworks were involved and he summoned federal agents to
investigate.
   John Kingsolver, a special agent with the federal bureau's
Cleveland office, also said items that resembled firecracker tubes
had been spotted at one house. He said federal investigators were
warned of the possibility of more blasts while they examine the
debris.
   The county coroner's office tentatively identified the two dead
as people who lived in the area of the blast: Donald A. Rossi, 56,
and June Riddle, described as elderly.
   The only injured person to be hospitalized, Georgianna Rossi,
46, was listed in satisfactory condition this morning at Hamot
Medical Center in Erie, Pa., about 25 miles east of Conneaut. She
lived in the house where the largest explosion occurred.
   Twelve people were treated at Brown Memorial Hospital in
Conneaut and released, said hospital administrator George Whitney.
   Orrenmaa originally put the death toll at three, but later
revised it to two.
</TEXT>
