<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--BoatAccident     10-25 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Boat Accident,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>11 Hurt in River Accident Near Site of Marchioness Sinking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven people were slightly injured Wednesday when
a boat bumped into Southwark Bridge in the River Thames near the
site of a fatal accident involving a pleasure boat in August,
police said.
   The Thames Line vessel collided with a buttress of the bridge
after apparently suffering a steering failure, police said. The
dented boat was taken out of service and the government's Marine
Accident Branch launched an investigation.
   Thames Line said later the accident was caused by an engine
fault leading to a loss of power.
   None of the 30 passengers on board was seriously injured, the
company said. One was taken to a hospital and treated for a bruised
knee, and 10 others suffered minor bruises.
   On Aug. 20, 51 people were killed when the Marchioness, a
pleasure boat chartered for an overnight birthday party, sank near
Southwark Bridge in central London after colliding with the
Bowbelle, a sand-and-gravel dredger.
</TEXT>
