<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1347EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-American     10-25 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-American,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Turn Away American Accused of Selling Secrets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American facing charges of selling secrets to
the Soviet Union had applied for Soviet citizenship last month but
was denied, a government spokesman said Wednesday.
   Frank Nesbitt, who is accused of delivering unauthorized
information to Soviet agents, requested citizenship when he was in
Moscow as a tourist in September, said Foreign Ministry spokesman
Yuri Gremitskikh.
   He was turned down because of ``suspicion of connections with
the criminal underworld,'' Gremitskikh said. He did not elaborate.
   Nesbitt, 44, a former military communications officer, was
arrested in a McLean, Va. hotel earlier this month and ordered held
without bail Oct. 19. A federal grand jury will hear the
government's case against him.
   The FBI says Nesbitt received $2,000 for classified
communications intelligence information he gave the Soviets during
his 10-day stay in Moscow, and was promised up to $100,000 more for
future work.
   Nesbitt's lawyer, Gregory English, said last week his client
intended no harm to the United States. He said Nesbitt passed on
only information he believed to be unclassified and had proposed to
the FBI that he become a double agent.
   English also said Nesbitt ``wanted to have some excitement in
his life.''
</TEXT>
