<DOCNO> AP891025-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1356EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FloodInsurance     10-25 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flood Insurance,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>FEMA to Lower Flood Insurance Rates in Some Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency is
moving ahead with a program that will offer lower flood insurance
rates in communities that work harder to reduce risks of flood
damage, officials said Wednesday.
   Harold T. Duryee, head of FEMA's Federal Insurance
Administration, said the agency is setting a Dec. 15, 1990,
deadline for initial applications from communities seeking to
qualify for premium adjustments under the program, called the
Community Rating System.
   The first flood insurance rate cuts will take effect Oct. 1,
1991, in communities that qualify for them, he said.
   Duryee said the agency also is trying to simplify procedures
involved with the flood insurance program, noting criticism in some
communities that ``the program was so complex that people didn't
want to fuss with all that was necessary to get coverage.''
   Frank Reilly, the FIA's deputy administrator, said about 2,000
out of the nearly 18,000 communities now participating in the
National Flood Insurance Program will apply for premium reductions
under the new rating system.
   Currently, there are more than 2.1 million federal flood
insurance policies in force. Over the last 10 years, 350,000
insurance losses have been paid out for a total of $2.5 billion.
   An FIA summary of the Community Rating System said its goals are
to ``are to encourage, by the use of flood insurance premium
adjustments, community and state activities beyond those required
by the National Flood Insurance Program to reduce flood losses,
facilitate accurate insurance rating and promote the awareness of
flood insurance.''
   ``Not only does such a system properly reward those communities
that are doing more than the minimum to protect their residents
from flood losses, it will will encourage communities to initiate
new flood protection activities,'' the paper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891025-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1401EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NicaraguaFunds     10-25 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua Funds,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Contra Says American Money Used To Buy Votes, Causes Corruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A disgruntled former Contra leader lashed out
Wednesday at U.S. financing for the opposition political coalition
in Nicaragua, charging the money is going for vote-buying and will
cause ``corruption on a big scale.''
   Edgar Chamorro, who describes himself as the CIA-selected
director of Contra communications from 1982 to 1984, said the $9
million in National Endowment for Democracy funds equals $2 billion
in his poor, Central American country.
   The Bush administration last week received congressional
approval for the aid to help the coalition in its February
electoral fight against the leftist Sandinista government.
   ``The congressional vote for this form of intervention
represents an essential agreement between the Bush administration
and the Democrat-controlled Congress that the attempt to overturn
the Sandinista government by armed force has failed,'' he said at a
news conference.
   Congress cut off military aid to the Contra rebels in 1988. The
10,000 or so troops, most of whom are based in Honduras, receive
non-lethal aid.
   Chamorro also charged that presidential candidate Violeta
Chamorro, who is not related to him, received the nomination
because of vote-buying.
   ``People received money to get her elected,'' he said. ``I have
heard this directly from friends and witnesses.'' He offered no
other proof or testimony.
   Chamorro also charged that opposition leaders planned to use
more than $2.5 million in American funds for salaries, cars and
paid vacations.
   ``These are merely the current, overt funds,'' Chamorro said.
   An Agency for International Development official, speaking on
the condition of anonymity, said a draft budget had been presented
by the opposition coalition, but no decisions had been reached.
   ``It will be closely monitored,'' he said.
   Chamorro said the CIA still supplies the opposition working out
of Honduras and Costa Rica.
   He said Contra combatants continued ``carrying out armed
propaganda activities, murdering electoral officials and Sandinista
political activists and warning peasants against voting for the
Sandinistas.''
   Chamorro says he is a ``non-Sandinista Nicaraguan'' but faulted
the government only for not cracking down on the large sums of
money coming into the country for the elections, $2 million of
which goes to the government's electoral council.
   ``I think Nicaragua was wrong in accepting that money,'' he
said. ``This is corruption on a big scale.''
   Chamorro returned to live in Nicaragua in 1987 and he now heads
the Managua office of the Center for the Study of Democratic
Systems, a group he said will ``observe the observers'' in the
Nicaraguan elections. That organization is an offshoot of the New
York-based Institute for Media Analysis, made up mostly of
Americans opposed to the U.S. support for the Contra rebels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
