<FIRST>r a AM-School-Racism     10-25 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School-Racism,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Division Will Investigate Racism At Colorado High School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVERGREEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Civil Rights Division is
investigating incidents at a high school that prompted transfer
requests from a black teacher and three black students.
   Officials from the Civil Rights Division and other civil-rights
agencies plan to visit Evergreen High School next week, division
public information officer Judy Fester said Tuesday.
   Evergreen language arts teacher Joseph Knight submitted a
transfer request to the Jefferson County School District last
Friday after receiving an unsigned note containing a racist threat.
   The note ``was very physically threatening,'' Knight, 35, said
Tuesday. ``Life. Death. That sort of thing. ... I simply can't work
in fear, and I won't.''
   Knight is on paid administrative leave while his transfer
request is considered.
   Several weeks ago, three black students, the sons of Evergreen
residents Norm and Joan Burkett, withdrew from the school after
hearing that some students rigged a homecoming contest against them
because they are black. Their mother resigned as president of the
Parent Teachers Association.
   The students said that earlier racist graffiti and slurs against
blacks and Jews contributed to their decision to leave the school.
   Principal Byron Tucker said he believes the incidents are the
work of a handful of white supremacist students. He added that
there is growing anger among the school's 1,100 students, who
generally view publicity about the incidents as marring their
school's reputation.
   Parents in the mountain community west of Denver feel the same
way. ``I've been getting a lot of phone calls,'' said PTA President
Lynn Richardson. ``Parents are very upset and angry that Evergreen
is being labeled as racist.''
   Under Colorado's 1988 ethnic intimidation law, the note writer
could be charged with a misdemeanor. Jefferson County Sheriff's
Department spokesman Bob Deutsch said, however, that no police
report had been filed.
</TEXT>
