<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1404EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DelayedDiplomas     10-25 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Delayed Diplomas,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese-Americans Denied Diplomas in WWII Will Finally Graduate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen Japanese-Americans whose graduation
from high school was thwarted by World War II will receive diplomas
they earned 47 years ago.
   The students, who are scheduled to receive their diplomas
Saturday, were among those detained in the since-discredited
wartime policy of relocating Japanese-Americans to internment camps
as possible enemy sympathizers.
   ``Our rights were denied us all these years,'' said Hayao
Shishino, a retired cook who lives in Cerritos. ``We want to be on
the rolls of the Class of 1942.''
   Most of the high school seniors sent to internment camps went on
to receive diplomas from correspondence courses or at their 25th
anniversary class reunion in 1967. But Shishino and other former
students wanted diplomas dated 1942.
   He successfully appealed to Los Angeles school board member
Warren Furutani, whose mother-in-law was among the classmates
refused diplomas.
   ``The most important part of this episode is that it is a living
history lesson. We have an opportunity to go back and set the
record straight,'' Furutani said.
   Shishino helped set up the weekend ceremony, which 11 of the
former Los Angeles High School students are expected to attend. One
diploma will be awarded posthumously.
</TEXT>
