<FIRST>r a AM-SaxophoneCase     10-25 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saxophone Case,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted in Saxophone Kidnapping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been found guilty of holding an
expensive saxophone for ransom.
   A state court jury deliberated about three hours Tuesday before
finding Rickie Lee Cleland guilty of stealing local musician Joe
Thompson's tenor saxophone, valued at $10,000 to $12,000, and
demanding money for its return.
   Cleland, 38, of Helena, could face up to 20 years in prison
after being convicted of felony theft and intimidation. Sentencing
was set for Nov. 30.
   Cleland was accused of stealing the saxophone on June 25 while
Thompson's band was storing equipment after playing at a wedding
reception.
   Prosecutors said Cleland called Thompson a few days later, said
he had found the horn and asked what Thompson would pay to have it
back.
   They said Cleland rejected Thompson's offer of $250 and said he
would give him a day to raise more money _ then asked for $1,500.
   Thompson alerted police, who connected a tape recorder to his
phone in time for a June 29 call from Cleland.
   During that call, according to the tape, Cleland increased his
demand to $2,000 but later settled on $500.
   Cleland was arrested a few minutes later when he met Thompson to
make the exchange.
</TEXT>
