<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Poland     10-25 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Poland,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Agrees to Reschedule Polish Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Police, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan has signed an agreement to allow Poland to
extend its debt repayment schedule for about $396.5 million in
loans, the Foreign Ministry said Wednesday.
   A ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the agreement followed negotiations in Warsaw under arrangements
made by Poland's creditor nations, known as the Paris Club, in late
1987.
   He said Poland's debts to Japan, which had been due Dec. 31,
1988, included $336.6 million of export insurance paid by Japan to
cover Poland's failure to pay for its imports and $59.9 million in
loans extended by the Japan Export-Import Bank.
   Under an agreement, Poland will repay the debts and interest
over five years after a five-year grace period, the official said.
