<DOCNO> AP891025-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1450EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     10-25 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>North-South Talks Bog Down With Accusations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers from North Korea and South
Korea set aside their agenda Wednesday and traded accusations of
dictatorship and human rights abuses, casting doubt on any quick
breakthrough toward easing tension.
   Delegates from the two sides clashed when communist North Korea
opened the talks at this truce village by demanding South Korea
release three jailed dissidents and get all U.S. troops to withdraw.
   Chief South Korean delegate Chai Mun-shick responded by saying
North Korea should stop interfering in the south's internal affairs
and said the Pyongyang government ``must abandon dictatorial rule
and protect human rights.''
   The senior North Korean delegate, Chun Kum Chol, reacted
angrily: ``Your accusations are nonsense.''
   After reading prepared statements repeating their uncompromising
stands, both sides traded unusually hostile accusations for more
than three hours, but agreed to meet again Nov. 29.
   Wednesday's meeting, the first since December, was called to set
terms for a joint session of the two Koreas' legislatures to work
out various tension-easing measures on the peninsula, including a
non-aggression pact.
   The nations clashed over similar subjects at Red Cross, sports
and other talks earlier this month but their exchanges were not as
hostile as Wednesday.
   The chief North Korean delegate, Chun, argued that the three
jailed South Korean dissidents _ Christian pastor Moon Ik-hwan,
opposition lawmaker Suh Kyung-won and radical student Im Su-kyong _
were ``patriots who wanted reunification of the divided peninsula''
and demanded their immediate release.
   The three dissidents were arrested between April and August for
making illegal trips to North Korea, an enemy country.
   The Seoul government bans unauthorized visits to North Korea and
maintains dialogue on national unification must be carried on only
through official channels. The two Koreas do not allow their
citizens to visit each other or cross the heavily guarded border.
   The Korean peninsula was divided into the communist north and
the capitalist south in 1945 at the end of World War II and the two
nations remain bitter enemies after fighting a bloody war from
1950-53.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
