<FIRST>u w PM-US-Mideast 2nd-Writethru a0564 10-25 0905</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mideast, 2nd-Writethru, a0564,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Offers to Review Proposal for Israeli-Palestinian Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with Baker comments; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
Arens told. Editing to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III offered
today to review his proposal for talks between Israel and
Palestinian Arabs but said overhauling it could delay negotiations.
   ``We think the five points are reasonable. We think the five
points are clear,'' Baker told a White House news conference,
referring to the major provisions of the U.S. proposal.
   Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, in a letter to Baker
delivered Monday night, accepted the U.S. package in principle _
provided his government was assured the Palestine Liberation
Organization would be excluded and that the talks would deal
entirely with holding elections on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   ``I think that we want to do everything we can to try and move
things forward,'' Baker said. ``And therefore we will review the
suggested changes we have received.''
   However, he added, ``if we start making changes for one side we
will find ourselves in an extended negotiating session in terms of
making changes that might be requested. ... It would be much better
if both sides would accept the five points as a general framework
for moving forward and then let's get about the hard, nitty-gritty
business of sitting down face-to-face and deciding what the rules
are that would govern the conduct of elections.''
   Baker described his mood as realistic _ neither optimisic nor
pessimistic _ after reading Arens letter and talking to him Tuesday
on the telephone.
   But he went on to say: ``Over the last week or so many people
have wanted to, basically, write this effort off. They wanted to
declare it dead. The events of the last two or three days at least
indicate that the effort has life in it.''
   Arens told Baker in the letter delivered by Israeli Ambassador
Moshe Arad on Monday night that the PLO must be excluded and the
agenda limited to the mechanics of conducting elections among the
1.4 million Palestinians who live on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Baker had already offered assurances he was not trying to
pressure Israel into dealing with the PLO and that Israel would
have the right to determine beforehand if it was ``satisfied'' with
the Palestinian delegation.
   Arens asked Baker to harden those assurances, while Baker is
trying to persuade the PLO through Egyptian intermediaries to
permit Palestinians in the Israeli-held territories to engage in
negotiations with Israel.
   Without a green light from Yasser Arafat's organization, it is
extremely unlikely Palestinians will step forward. Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir, in a letter last week to Baker, said they
were being subjected to ``intimidation.''
   The PLO's Central Committee, meeting last week in Baghdad, Iraq,
insisted that only the PLO had the authority to represent
Palestinians and to select the delegation. But Margaret Tutwiler,
the State Department spokeswoman, said Tuesday that did not mean
the PLO had rejected Baker's initiative.
   Baker talked again to Arens on Tuesday, reaching him by
telephone in Brussels where the Israeli foreign minister is meeting
with Belgian and European Common Market officials as well as with a
group of Israeli ambassadors based in Europe.
   The contents of their conversation were not disclosed. But it
was learned Baker and Arens concluded they had a basis to keep
working together toward Shamir's goal of holding elections among
the Palestinians.
   Arens, in an interview broadcast today on Israel Radio, said,
however, he was ``adamant'' that the formula for talks with
Palestinians not deviate in any way from the Israeli government's
peace initiative.
   Baker also talked by telephone with Egyptian Foreign Minister
Esmat Abdel Meguid, who was in Cairo.
   Publicly, the State Department welcomed Arens' letter to Baker
and said through Ms. Tutwiler it ``reinforces what we believe _
that they are engaged and that they are working really hard to try
to bridge these gaps.''
   Shamir, while touring the Golan Heights, meanwhile, described
the recently stepped-up exchange with the Bush administration as
positive. ``I don't see any large gap between our views and the
proposals of the secretary of state,'' he told reporters. ``But
there are some differences.''
   Israel's Labor Party opposition stressed those differences. ``I
don't see anything in Baker's proposal that needs to be changed,''
said Shimon Peres, the Labor leader who is also finance minister.
   Shamir said Israel would agree to the Baker plan ``after the
changes we proposed are accepted.'' The prime minister added: ``In
a few days we will know if there is an agreement or not.''
   Only one of Baker's five points has been publicly acknowledged
by the State Department. It provides for a three-way meeting of
Israel, Egypt and the United States in Washington after Israel
meets with Palestinians but before the elections are held.
   The other provisions are that the Israeli-Palestinian talks be
held, that the elections are the focus, that Israel is to be
``satisfied'' with the Palestinian delegation's composition and
that Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak is free to consult any Middle
Eastern parties about the makeup of the delegation.
   Shamir's proposal is that Palestinians elected on the West Bank
and in Gaza would make arrangements with Israel for five years of
limited self-rule. After this trial run, Palestinians together with
Jordan and Egypt, would negotiate an overall settlement with Israel.
</TEXT>
