<FIRST>r a AM-Mother'sTestimony     10-25 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mother's Testimony,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Turns In Son On Bank Charge To Keep Him From Worse Trouble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman says she turned her son over to
the FBI to face a bank robbery charge so he wouldn't get into more
trouble.
   ``I'd rather see him in prison for a few years than see him
dead. That's why I turned him in. I thought I was doing the right
thing,'' Carolyn Hayes of Hattiesburg said Tuesday during a bond
hearing for her son, Gregory Molette.
   U.S. Magistrate John R. Countiss III noted that Molette had
convictions in 1983 and 1984 for sale of marijuana and ordered him
held without bond until his trial Jan. 8.
   ``He's a danger to the community because of his drug habits and
propensity for the sale of drugs,'' Countiss said.
   Hayes, 46, said her son ``didn't have any money. He would have
gone and stole and gotten in some deeper trouble.''
   Molette was indicted Oct. 6 in connection with the Sept. 5
holdup of a Unifirst Bank for Savings branch in Jackson.
Authorities said $3,910 was taken.
   ``He called me and asked for money and I told him I didn't have
it, which I didn't. I'm a widow lady,'' Hayes said.
   ``I told him I knew what he had done because I had seen it on
the TV myself,'' Hayes said. Local television stations showed a
photo taken by a bank surveillance camera.
   Molette, 24, took a bus to Michigan after he saw his picture on
television, FBI Agent Willie Covington said. FBI agents arrested
him Sept. 12 at a relative's home in Saginaw, Mich.
</TEXT>
