<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1509EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Democrats-Bush     10-25 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Bush,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simpson Says Democratic `Yapping Dogs' Out to Get Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republicans, stung by a drive by
Democrats to portray President Bush as timid, hesitant and weak,
described the critics Wednesday as ``yapping dogs'' determined to
``rule or ruin.''
   ``They're not interested in legislating,'' said Deputy
Republican Leader Alan Simpson, R-Wyo. ``They're just interested in
seeing just who can ram it to the other side.''
   But Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, replying to a remark
by Bush on Tuesday that he was tired of ``taking hits'' from
opponents, said the president has no reason to complain.
   The president doesn't mind criticizing others, but doesn't want
to be criticized himself, the Maine Democrat said.
   He said criticism of the adequacy of the president's proposals
for Poland and Hungary was entirely justified because ``what the
president proposed was inadequate.''
   Mitchell, House Speaker Tom Foley, D-Wash., and most other
Democratic leaders have opened an aggressive campaign in recent
weeks, repeatedly using such words as ``weak,'' and ``timid,'' and
``woefully inadequate'' to describe Bush's efforts on such issues
as aid for Eastern Europe and the war against drugs.
   On Tuesday, Mitchell ripped into Bush's drive to pass a capital
gains tax cut, accusing the administration of unfair tactics and
declaring: ``The capital gains tax has become the Holy Grail of
this administration.''
   Mitchell said the administration ``has cast aside any concern
for the deficit. It has cast aside any concern for the budget
process, it has now cast aside any concern for fairness and it has
cast aside any concern for relations with this Congress'' on the
capital gains issue.
   Simpson told the Senate that in making such statements, Mitchell
and Foley are reflecting ``heat from down below.''
   ``It's heat from people who really don't like to legislate; they
just like to rule or ruin,'' Simpson said.
   He said these ``young Turk'' Democrats were irritated with the
early tendency of both Mitchell and Foley to accomodate the
president and facilitate his programs.
   ``They have been saying, ``When are you going to stop that? When
are you going to hammer him? ``Get him. Forget the issues. Just get
him.'''
   Simpson said he is not blaming Mitchell or Foley but is
reserving his fire for those Democrats whom he said insisted on a
more aggressive strategy.
   ``I think they grind their teeth at night,'' Simpson said,
adding:
   ``They're not interested in legislating. They are just
interested in seeing just who can ram it to the other side. Out of
ambition ... They have a higher agenda and that's power ... And
Heaven forbid, some of them even lust for the presidency.''
   ``And so they rattle the cage,'' Simpson said.
   ``And they say things like, `the hesitancy presidency,' which is
a dazzling phrase somebody cabbaged up. `Timid.' That's another.''
   ``George Bush has been through all of that,'' Simpson said. ``In
eight years (as vice president) he was called ... a `wimp,'
`sycophant,' `lapdog.' ... Didn't faze him a bit.''
   ``So there won't be any response from George Bush at these
yapping dogs,'' Simpson said. ``And there are yapping dogs out
there.''
   Actually Bush did respond in an interview on Tuesday with The
New York Times.
   ``Democrats on Capitol Hill have been calling me `timid,' he
said. ``I have other, better words like `cautious,' `diplomatic,'
`prudent.'''
</TEXT>
