<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     10-25 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Urges Christian Legislators to Reject Peace Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Analysis, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Michel Aoun called on legislators
Wednesday to reject a peace plan they passed during a special
Parliament session in Saudi Arabia, and his hostility left him
politically isolated even in his Christian camp.
   Fearing Aoun's wrath might land them in jail, some Christian
legislators delayed their return to Beirut.
   Christian political, militia and religious leaders declared
cautious support for the accord. The main political alliance urged
Lebanese leaders to ``show flexibility in dealing with it.''
   Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir of the Maronite church was quoted in
radio interviews from Rome as supporting the plan, which would
shift political control from the Christian minority to the Moslem
majority but reserve the presidency for a Maronite.
   Aoun scorned it in a speech to young Christian demonstrators at
the war-battered remnants of the presidential palace east of Beirut.
   He repeated that he accepted the political reforms but rejected
the accord's lack of a deadline for the withdrawal of the 40,000
Syrian troops in Lebanon.
   ``No to the accord of capitulation! No to surrender!'' the
estimated 2,000 demonstrators chanted, waving posters of Aoun and
flags of Lebanon.
   Parliament approved the plan Sunday after 23 days of talks in
the Saudi resort of Taif. It is aimed at ending 14 years of civil
war.
   Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria _ assigned by the Arab League
to mediate the Lebanon crisis _ urged Parliament to convene by Nov.
7 in Beirut to formally approve it and elect a president.
   The White House said the Bush administration supports the accord.
   The Lebanese Front alliance of right-wing Christian groups
declared support for the plan, which was approved by 59 of the 62
lawmakers at Taif.
   The front's president, George Saadeh, voted for it. Saadeh heads
the Phalange Party, the main Christian political group in Lebanon.
   The Lebanese Front ``pleads with all officials and leaders to
show flexibility in dealing with initiatives to settle the Lebanese
crisis,'' a statement said.
   Saadeh and five deputies went to Rome to seek church backing for
the plan.
   Parliament deputy Raymond Edde, a Maronite Catholic like Aoun,
announced in Paris that he will run for president.
   Edde, who has been living in self-imposed exile following
repeated attempts to assassinate him in Lebanon, was the first
person to announce candidacy for the post.
   Lebanon has been without a president since Sept. 22, 1988, when
Amin Gemayel's term expired and Parliament was unable to decide on
a successor.
   Gemayel named Aoun head of an interim military Cabinet pending
election of a new president.
   Moslems rejected Aoun's appointment and swore allegiance to the
Cabinet of acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem.
   One senior official in the Phalange Party, speaking anonymously,
said Aoun felt abandoned by the plan because it does not fulfull
his goal of driving the Syrians out of the country.
   Syrian troops were deployed in 1976 under an Arab League mandate
to quell the civil war. Aoun said they violated the mandate by
siding with the Moslems in the war.
   ``The general rightfully feels he is left out in the cold. He is
the main loser as a result of the Taif accord and it looks like
he's not going to take it gracefully,'' said the official.
</TEXT>
