<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Arts     10-25 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Arts,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artists Rally For More Government Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of artists and their supporters staged a
National Arts Advocacy Day on Wednesday and warned that theaters,
museums and other institutions are being ``squeezed to death'' by
government cutbacks.
   Subsidized theater in Britain is ``as much under threat as the
Amazonian rain forests,'' said Richard Eyre, director of the Royal
National Theatre.
   The demonstrators rallied at the South Bank Arts Center, home of
the Royal Festival Hall and the National Theater, before heading to
the House of Commons to urge lawmakers to be more generous with
funding for the arts.
   John Bowis, a legislator for the governing Conservative Party,
said they would have to exert ``huge pressure'' because the arts
were of little interest to most members of Parliament, or MPs.
   ``The last time I initiated a debate on the arts there were
about 40 MPs present out of 650'' in the House of Commons, he said.
   Speakers accused the government of underestimating the value of
the arts to British life and as a revenue earner. More than 300
people attended the rally, organizers said.
   ``Britain has an artistic talent all round which is second to
none, but which is being squeezed to death,'' said Sir Peter
Maxwell Davies, the composer and conductor.
   Years of belt-tightening by arts organizations are being wasted
because of rising inflation, said Luke Rittner, the
government-appointed secretary-general of the Arts Council, which
distributes government arts subsidies. He pleaded for another $64
million of government aid over the next three years.
   Since Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservatives won power
in 1979, government financial support for the arts has fallen by 19
percent, said Simon Crine, director of the National Campaign for
the Arts, which organized the events.
   Total government spending this year on arts and libraries,
including the 19 national museums, is officially estimated at $1.3
billion, of which $707 million is for the arts alone.
   The Arts Council receives $245 million of that for drama, music,
opera, dance, movies and videos, touring companies and art
exhibitions.
   Local authorities spend a further $316 million and business
sponsorship amounts to $47 million.
   Arts organizers say the inflation rate of 7.6 percent has thrown
many ensembles and projects into crisis and the government's own
advisory body, the Museums and Galleries Commission, said in July
that inflation and wage increases have risen four times as much as
its grants.
   Britain's flagship arts center, the heavily subsidized Royal
Opera House, has a projected deficit this year of nearly $4
million; the Royal Shakespeare Company is more than $1.58 million
in the red and the National Theater, the financially strongest of
the trio, only balanced its books this year by drawing on reserves.
   The British Museum faces the first deficit in its 236-year
history, about $1.58 million, largely because funding has failed to
match civil service pay hikes, said Sir David Wilson, its director.
   Subsidized theater in Britain is ``as much under threat as the
Amazonian rain forests,'' said Richard Eyre, director of the Royal
National Theatre.
   Peter Palumbo, the millionaire real estate developer and
chairman of the Arts Council, said last week that Britons should
abandon the outdated perception of the arts as a recreational
pastime for amateurs.
   The arts are a major industry, employing 500,000 people and with
an annual revenue of $19 billion, he said.
</TEXT>
