<FIRST>r w AM-Industry-Ozone 1stLd-Writethru a0657 10-25 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Industry-Ozone, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Group Plays Down Ozone Pollution</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs reaction from environmental group after 3rd
graf pvs, picking up 4th graf pvs, Congress is ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ozone pollution reported in some cities
last year was caused mostly by unusually hot weather, not dirtier
air, an industry-supported analysis said Wednesday.
   ``The environmental community would have you believe we are in
an ozone crisis, but that is not the case,'' said William D. Fay,
administrator of the Clean Air Working Group.
   With the exceptions of Los Angeles, Houston and sometimes New
York ``our cities are facing neither an ozone crisis nor an
intractable ozone problem,'' said Fay.
   Dr. Michael Oppenheimer of the Environmental Defense Fund
disagreed, however, contending that ``most of the eastern United
States has too much ozone.''
   Emissions and weather are the factors that affect pollution,
said Oppenheimer. Emissions have been increasing with the improving
economy, he said. And while 1988 was an unusual year, if climate
warming does occur as some scientisis fear, that would increase
future pollution levels.
   Congress is considering legislation which would tighten
emissions standards for automobiles, businesses and industry, and
last summer's increased smog levels have been cited in debates over
that measure.
   Several cities did record dramatic increases in the number of
times their air quality failed to meet federal standards last year.
   But Kay H. Jones of the Seattle research firm Roy F. Weston
Inc., said his analysis of ozone readings in more than 70 major
cities shows that 1988 was an aberration.
   For much of the nation, the summer of 1988 was the hottest since
the Dust Bowl years of the 1930s, and the excessive heat generated
more ozone in large cities, Jones said.
   Ozone, a highly reactive form of oxygen, is a major constituent
of urban smog. Heat speeds the chemical reactions which form ozone.
   Conditions returned to nearly normal this past summer, Jones
said. For example, he said, Atlanta exceeded ozone standards for 19
days in 1988 and only once in 1989. For other cities the excessive
days included Baltimore, 34 in 1988 and 2 in 1989, Chicago, 27 in
1988 and 3 in 1989; New York, 39 in 1988 and 12 in 1989 and
Washington, 30 in 1988 n London Metal Exchange warehouse
stocks and a pending strike vote at Exxon Corp. mines in Chile.
   ``Strikes and shutdowns that had been supporting prices for a
while back are settled and copper is not in such tight supply,''
said Demler.
   Copper settled 35 to 45 cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in October at $1.15 a pound.
   Also on the Comex, the steadier stock market and stronger dollar
sent gold and silver futures slightly lower.
   ``It's been a pretty dead metals market lately, with not much
major news to generate any sudden shifts,'' said Diane Meagher of
Deak International Inc. in Chicago.
   Gold settled $1 to $1.10 lower, with the contract for delivery
in October at $369.10 a troy ounce; and silver was 3.4 cents to 3.5
cents lower, with October at $5.114 a troy ounce.
   Oil futures prices were mostly higher in very light trading on
the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Futures were supported by a false rumor during the day that an
earthquake had hit Alaska, said Mike Rothman, senior oil anaylst
for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.
   He also said traders were discounting the 6.304 million barrels
of crude oil listed in Tuesday's American Petroleum Institute
inventory report.
   ``They believe stocks were depleted by the effects of Hurricane
Jerry and there will be off-setting figures in next week's
report,'' said Rothman.
   Crude futures settled 10 cents lower to 23 cents higher, with
the contract for delivery in November at $18.83 a barrel; heating
oil was .20 cent lower to .05 cent higher, with November at 58.44
cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .05 cent to .61 cent
higher, with November at 53.40 a gallon.
   Futures prices for corn and soybeans climbed higher, but wheat
prices sagged on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   This week's light trading continued for a third day, with little
outside news of any major consequence for the futures markets, said
Susan Leighty, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Lack of export demand and beneficial rains for both the South
American and U.S. winter crop were depressing wheat prices, Ms.
Leighty said.
   Supporting futures prices was new Soviet interest in the
agricultural markets, as the Soviet Union purchased 50,000 metric
tons of Argentine meal and 350,000 metric tons of corn from
Yugoslavia since Tuesday, said Victor Lespinasse, a floor trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents to 6\ cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in December at $4.05{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2\
cents higher, with December at $2.42\ a bushel; oats were } cent to
1\ cents lower, with December at $1.46 a bushel; and soybeans were
3 cents to 6 cents higher, with November at $5.66 a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, livestock and pork prices
were mostly higher.
   ``We had a late rally in the final 20 minutes, mostly on
commission house buying,'' said Chicago analyst Phil Stanley of DEC
Futures Inc.
   Lighter supplies of cattle, but not so light for hogs were
affecting prices, Stanley said.
   Cattle settled .02 cent lower to .03 cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in December at 75.20 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .03 cent lower to .30 cent higher, with October at
83.05 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent lower to .27 cent
higher, with December at 47.80 cents a pound; and forzen pork
bellies were .20 cent to .55 cent higher with February at 53.32
cents a pound.
   The stock-index futures traded on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange followed the New York Stock Exchange to lower ground.
   The contract for December delivery of stocks tracked by the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled 1.85 points lower at 344.65.
Each point is worth $500.
