<DOCNO> AP891025-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1928EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CapitalGains     10-25 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital Gains,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Presses for Senate Vote on Capital Gains Tax Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush forcefully pressed for a clear
shot at a Senate vote on a lower capital gains tax in a meeting
Wednesday with Senate Democrats, but was told his chances were
slim, participants said.
   The lawmakers said after a White House meeting that they told
Bush his only realistic hope was to support a compromise package
that included other items as well.
   While balking at the notion of delaying action on such a measure
until next year, Bush expressed willingness to discuss a compromise
package, said the senators.
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said when he proposed that the capital
gains change be linked with a higher minimum wage, White House
Chief of Staff John Sununu ``put a pad in front of me and said,
`Write it out.'''
   Harkin was one of eight Democrats invited to the White House by
Bush as the president continued to lobby Democrats for a
straightforward vote on the capital gains proposal.
   The White House is seeking Senate approval of a provision passed
by the House that would lower the tax on capital gains _ profits
from the sale of real estate, stocks and other assets _ to 19.6
percent for two years, from the current maximum rate of 33 percent.
   But the Senate Democratic leadership has resisted scheduling a
simple vote on the measure, and the White House in the past few
days has stepped up its lobbying campaign.
   ``If the administration continues to push for an up-and-down
vote on capital gains to the exclusion of everything else, that's
just not going to happen,'' Harkin said.
   Senators who met with Bush said the president was repeatedly
told there was little likelihood he would get a vote on a separate
capital gains tax bill this year.
   The blunt assessment was more substantial in that it came from a
group of Democrats who in the past had supported either a capital
gains tax cut, or some form of capital gains incentives.
   Bush met with Harkin and Sens. Brock Adams of Washington, Max
Baucus of Montana, Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, Wyche Fowler
Jr. of Georgia, John Glenn of Ohio, John F. Kerry of Massachusetts
and Timothy E. Wirth of Colorado.
   Participants said that, in addition to the capital gains
proposal, the final package might include a Democratic-sponsored
plan to expand coverage of Individual Retirement Accounts as well
as legislation to deal with the minimum wage and child care.
   ``It's clear that most people feel they've got to resolve this
in some sort of sensible way that involves compromises on both
sides,'' Kerry told reporters.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president was agreeable to
``possible compromises'' on the proposal, but did not suggest what
form such a package might take.
   ``We are working to pick up new votes all the time,'' he said.
   However, it seemed unlikely Bush picked up any in Wednesday's
session.
   ``The president presented his position very forcefully,'' Glenn
said.
   Participants said Bush opened Wednesday's meeting by denying
that he was seeking to make the issue a ``Holy Grail,'' as Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, had asserted on Tuesday.
   The House attached the capital gains cut to broader
deficit-reduction bill which is now in a House-Senate conference
committee.
   The Senate version does not contain the cut. Democrats have
threatened to filibuster if the conference committee produces a
compromise version containing the capital gains provision.
   It would take 60 votes to shut off such a filibuster, votes
Republicans do not appear to have.
   Negotiators from the Senate and House began the efforts
Wednesday to work out a compromise between the different
deficit-reduction bills passed by the two chambers but made little
headway.
</TEXT>
