<FIRST>r i AM-India-Clashes     10-25 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Clashes,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seventeen Die in Moslem-Hindu Clashes, Reports Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobs dragged passengers from a train and
killed four of them in eastern Bihar state, bringing to 17 the
number of deaths blamed on fighting Wednesday between Moslems and
Hindus, news reports said.
   United News of India said all the deaths were in Bhagalpur, a
remote city of 300,000 where four people died in sectarian violence
on Tuesday.
   The area has been plagued by looting and arson and the news
agency said troops were dispatched to the region on Wednesday to
keep order. It said they were given orders to shoot lawbreakers on
sight.
   United News said that mobs attacked an express train near
Bhagalpur, dragged passengers from the car and killed four. Mobs
also attacked a local train and wounded six, it said.
   The religions of the victims in the latest clashes were not
known.
   A state government official in Patna, Bihar's capital, said
police found only nine bodies of people killed in clashes
Wednesday. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
25 policemen were wounded.
   Bhagalpur, on the Ganges River that is sacred to Hindus, is
about 110 miles east of Patna and about 220 miles northwest of
Calcutta.
   The deaths brought to 41 the number of people killed in
Hindu-Moslem clashes since Sunday in four villages across Bihar
state, one of the poorest and most violent in India.
   Some of clashes coincided with processions by Hindu militants
who are collecting bricks to build a temple at Ayodhya, in
neighboring Uttar Pradesh state, where Hindus and Moslems both lay
claim to the same religious site.
   Moslems make up 11 percent of India's 880 million people. Hindus
comprise 82 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
