<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-FirefighterHero     10-25 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Firefighter Hero,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighter Ignores Gas And Flames To Free Woman From Marina Apartment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighter Gerry Shannon, who rescued a
woman 12 years ago only to have her die, grabbed the woman pinned
in her blazing Marina apartment and held on like man in a grudge
match with death.
   The 19-year veteran firefighter found Sherra Cox lying in the
dust and blackness, trapped under a door and doorframe when two
upper floors of her apartment building collapsed during the Oct. 17
earthquake.
   ``When somebody holds your hand and you're a few feet away, I
doubt I'll ever feel that again. I felt like I knew her and I
couldn't go no matter what was happening,'' said Shannon, 44.
   When he heard someone was trapped, he found an opening in the
rubble of a sidewall. Throwing off his coat and helmet, he crawled
inside the dark two-foot hole lighting his way with a flashlight.
   Cox, 55, had dislodged an iron pole and was banging it with her
one free arm.
   ``I am here,'' she called to Shannon, who crawled toward the
voice.
   Outside, firefighters and spectators, who smelled the gas
enveloping the building and saw flames igniting, yelled for Sannnon
to leave.
   ``It got real bright and hot when the building across the street
fell. I saw her eyes got wide. I heard someone stick his head in
and yell to get out. She just squeezed hard and said, `Please don't
leave me,'' he said.
   The struggle brought back memories of 12 years ago when Shannon
was off-duty and pulled a woman from an apartment fire, but she
died shortly after of smoke inhalation.
   ``What I've thought the most about is when I heard everybody
tell me to get out. ... I knew the building was on fire, and it
felt like we were both done for but I couldn't leave her,'' he said.
   But Shannon needed equipment or both could die.
   He crawled outside, and Capt. Robert Boudoures handed him a
chainsaw. Shannon went back and began to cut the timbers. After
more than an hour, Shannon cut Cox free.
   Another rescue worker shoved in a stretcher and helped pull Cox
out.
   Cox was taken to San Francisco General Hospital where she
underwent seven hours of surgery for a dislocated, fractured hip
and cracked pelvis. She was in fair to good condition Wednesday.
   ``I saw her yesterday in the hospital. She's doing great. She's
a real tough gal,'' said Shannon.
</TEXT>
