<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-EarthquakePairs     10-25 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Earthquake Pairs,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Past Earthquakes In Pairs Might Mean Quake Now Likely In Oakland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earthquakes on one side of San Francisco Bay
have been matched within three years by similar-sized quakes on the
other side, raising the possibility that another might now be due
in Oakland, researchers say.
   An earthquake that hit Oakland's side of the bay in 1836 was
followed by a quake on the San Francisco side in 1838, and an
earthquake that hit the San Francisco peninsula in 1865 was
followed by an Oakland quake three years later. All the earthquakes
had magnitudes of 6.3 to 7.0.
   The 1865 earthquake occurred near the Loma Prieta area of the
San Francisco peninsula, where the Oct. 17 earthquake occurred,
according to a report to appear Friday in Science magazine.
   An Oakland quake similar in size on the Richter scale to the
Oct. 17 earthquake would cause far more damage, said Allan Lindh of
the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park, Calif. ``As horrible as
this one is, it's just nothing compared to when we get an
earthquake this size in the urban areas (in and near Oakland),'' he
told Science.
   Lindh could not be reached Wednesday.
   Lindh, William Ellsworth and their colleagues in Menlo Park
report that the 70 years leading up to the big San Francisco
earthquake of 1906 were marked by numerous earthquakes, and that
activity was sharply reduced after the big quake.
   In a telephone interview, Lynn Sykes, a seismologist at the
Lamont-Doherty Geological Observatory of Columbia University in
Palisades, N.Y., said there are reasons to believe the two sides of
the bay are seismologically linked.
   Just as there was activity in the Oakland area before the 1906
earthquake, there was activity there before the Oct. 17 quake,
Sykes said.
   ``There were a number of magnitude 5 to magnitude 6 earthquakes
in the East Bay starting around 1973,'' he said. ``I would say in
both instances, the stress or pressures in the Earth were building
up,'' he said.
   The question now is: Did the Oct. 17 quake relieve pressures
that had been building in the East Bay? Or did it increase
pressures there, making a matching quake likely?
   ``It's too soon toth graf ``The deaths ...''; ADDS 3
grafs with Baker reaction.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-PLO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians killed three fellow Arabs in the
occupied territories on Wednesday, including a woman accused of
subverting the Palestinian revolt by dealing in prostitution.
   As police found the body of one victim in an abandoned car,
masked youths appeared on a nearby hill and shouted ``Allahu
akbar!'' _ Arabic for ``God is great!''
   In Tel Aviv, judges sentenced a West Bank Palestinian to life in
prison plus 20 years after he pleaded guilty to murdering an
Israeli construction worker and trying to careen a crowded public
bus into a steep ravine last month.
   Also Wednesday, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said U.S. Middle
East peace proposals must be changed to more closely reflect
Israel's own initiative before they can be accepted by the
government.
   Arens wants the United States to exclude Cairo as the site for a
preliminary Israel-Palestinian meeting and to change language
suggesting Palestinians from outside the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip may take part, an Israeli official said.
   In the Gaza Strip, police found the body of an accused
collaborator, Fayez Mohammed Sahlawi, 29, in the trunk of a car
parked north of his home village of Beit Hanoun. They said an
initial investigation indicated he was shot to death. Masked youths
fled the scene after shouting their war cry.
   In the Mughazi refugee camp in Gaza, masked youths stabbed and
beat to death Fayza Abdul Salam, 50, Arab reporters said. She was
accused of dealing in prostitution.
   In the West Bank, eight masked men kidnapped Salah Abu al-Wafa,
38, from his house in the northern town of Jenin on Tuesday, axed
him to death and dumped his body near his house, town residents
told reporters.
   The residents said al-Wafa was accused of working with the
Israeli intelligence agents and dealing in drugs.
   The army spokesman's office confirmed the deaths of both Ms.
Salam and al-Wafa.
   The deaths raised to 135 the number of Palestinians killed by
fellow Arabs as suspected collaborators, or as drug dealers or
prostitutes, during the 22-month Palestinian uprising against
Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In Tel Aviv, a district court sentenced 26-year-old Ahmed
Shukry, of Ramallah, to life plus 20 years after he pleaded guilty
Wednesday to one count of murder and 51 counts of attempted murder.
   Shukry's second sentence would start should he be granted
parole, which is possible after 20 years under a life sentence in
Israel, meaning he faced at least 40 years in prison.
   Shukry was convicted of murdering Michael Eshtener, 38, at a Tel
Aviv building site Sept. 7 and of stabbing an Israeli bus driver
two days later in an attempt to force a bus off the Jerusalem-Tel
Aviv highway into a ravine.
   Shukry's attempt occurred near the spot where a Palestinian
forced a bus on the same route off a cliff on July 6, killing 16
Jews, including a U.S. tourist and two Canadians.
   ``In the occupied territories (Arab) children are being killed
every day,'' army radio quoted Shukry as telling the court. ``I
wanted to kill Jewish children.''
   At least 603 Palestinians have been killed by Israeli soldiers
or civilians in the uprising. According to the Israeli Information
Center for Human Rights, more than 120 of those killed were under
age 16. Forty Israelis have also died in the violence.
   The foreign minister, interviewed by government-run radio,
disputed a report by the Israeli Embassy in Washington that he
already had agreed in principle to a five-point peace plan of U.S.
Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   ``We are working in order to ensure that the formula presented
by the secretary of state will be the same as the government's
decision, the government's initiative,'' Arens told the radio from
Brussels, where he is attending a meeting.
   The Israeli peace initiative calls for elections in the occupied
lands to select Palestinians to open talks with Israel on limited
autonomy. It rules out any role for the PLO, which Israel considers
a terrorist organization.
   Israeli officials have opposed Cairo as a venue for preliminary
talks because they believe Egypt is trying to act as an
intermediary for the PLO.
   In Washington, Baker said the suggested changes will be reviewed
but cautioned: ``If we start making changes for one side, we will
find ourselves in an extended negotiating session in terms of
making changes that might be requested.
   ``It would be much better if both sides would accept the five
points as a general framework for moving forward,'' he said.
   A Foreign Ministry official said he could not comment until he
saw a text of Baker's remarks.
</TEXT>
