<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1612EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Greenspan-Fed     10-25 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greenspan-Fed,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenspan Defends Independent Federal Reserve</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan on
Wednesday defended his agency's political independence and warned
that proposals to make the central bank more accountable to
Congress and the administration could hamper its fight against
inflation.
   Greenspan was the lead-off witnesses as Congress launched its
first major review in more than a decade of the operations of the
Federal Reserve and its chairman, often called the second most
powerful man in the country because of the Fed's power over
interest rates.
   Greenspan said he opposed a bill sponsored by Reps. Lee
Hamilton, D-Ind., and Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., that they say would
make the central bank's deliberations less secretive and more
accountable to the public.
   The Hamilton-Dorgan bill would require the Fed's top
policy-making body, the Federal Open Market Committee, to meet with
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and other Bush administration
officials at regular intervals.
   The bill would also require immediate release of decisions made
by the FOMC and it would change the term of the Fed chairman so
that an incoming president would be able to appoint a new chairman
sooner after taking office.
   Greenspan rejected all of these proposals, contending they
increased the risks that the Fed would set interest rates in
response to political pressures rather than on judgments about what
was best for the long-run health of the economy.
   ``The Federal Reserve must take actions that, while sometimes
unpopular in the short-run, are in the long-run best interests of
the country,'' Greenspan said, adding the Fed's 75-year history of
independence had ``served the country well.''
   While voicing strong opposition to the Hamilton-Dorgan bill,
Greenspan did endorse a separate resolution sponsored by Rep.
Stephen Neal, D-N.C., that would write into law a requirement that
the Fed eliminate inflation and give the central bank five years to
reach that goal.
   Terming Neal's measure a ``laudable'' effort to clarify the
Fed's mandate, Greenspan warned that wringing inflation out of the
economy over the next five years would have short-term costs in
terms of slower growth. He termed the 1994 deadline achievable and
said it could be accomplished without plunging the country into a
recession.
   Consumer prices, after spurting up sharply early in the year,
are now rising at an annual rate of 4.4 percent, very close to the
rate of inflation over the past several years.
   Neal's measure does not include any penalties if the Fed fails
to meet the five-year deadline for eliminating inflation, but Neal
argued that the resolution would clarify existing law, which
directs the Fed to pursue the sometimes conflicting goals of
promoting employment, stable prices and moderate long-term interest
rates.
   In his appearance before Congress, Greenspan sought to play down
reports of a major rift between the Fed and the Bush administration
over interest rates. The administration has been pushing the Fed to
lower rates in an effort to spur economic growth and lower the
international exchange rate of the dollar.
   Greenspan said that he and the administration ``have differences
on occasions'' but that what was being interpreted as major
disputes were in reality only disagreements concerning ``relatively
minor issues of tactics.''
   Both the Neal measure and the Hamilton-Dorgan proposal are given
slight chance of getting through Congress because of opposition in
the Senate, where key members of the Senate Banking Committee have
given the Fed high marks and said they see no reason to make
changes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
