<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2008EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Immigration     10-25 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Immigration,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Votes to Defer Deporting Chinese, Salvadorans and Nicaraguans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday voted 258-162 to
protect thousands of illegal aliens who fled conflict in their
homelands by deferring their deportation to China, El Salvador and
Nicaragua.
   ``It will create humanitarian relief for three categories of
individuals who are here in the United States and for whom there is
no will to send them back,'' said Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn.
   The bill, which now goes to the Senate, would suspend for three
years deportation of Chinese, Salvadorans and Nicaraguans who
register within nine months.
   It would stop short of granting political asylum or permanent
resident status, but would provide temporary protection to perhaps
750,000 exiles.
   It also would establish a system for extending such temporary
status to citizens of additional countries beset by armed conflict
and natural disaster.
   The measure is designed to furnish shelter to those who have
fled civil war in Central America and face government persecution
as a result of the student democracy demonstrations in China.
   Proponents said 70,000 Salvadorans and 30,000 Nicaraguan
civilians have been killed in civil wars in their countries over
the last decade and that 10,000 participants in the Chinese
democracy demonstrations have been jailed.
   They scoffed at complaints that the measure would create an
exception that would undermine existing immigration law.
   Critics said it was a mistake to combine relief measures for the
Central Americans and the Chinese. They said the measure would
merely provide Central Americans hungry for American jobs with a
foot in the door.
   ``What we are going to do is grant a permanent status not to
people who came here for any political reason but for people who
came here for an economic reason to take jobs away from American
workers,'' said Rep. Bob Walker, R-Pa.
   Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass., a supporter of the measure, retorted
that the AFL-CIO and a number of large labor unions have endorsed
the measure. ``So evidently they aren't afraid,'' he told the House.
   Rep. Helen Bentley, R-Md., cited estimates that the price tag on
operation of the measure could reach $260 million over two years.
``I can tell you that my constituents will not abide by it,'' she
declared.
   Rep. Hamilton Fish, R-N.Y., said that illegal aliens who have
fled the three countries already are in the United States. ``I
think its in our interest to have Nicaraguans and Salvadorans
living in the open rather than maintaining an underground
existence,'' he said.
   ``This bill is the right thing to do,'' Rep. Bill Richardson,
D-N.M., told the House. He urged help for those ``uprooted for
political reasons, who have been escaping tragedy.''
</TEXT>
