<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     10-25 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruling Party Holds First Plenum Since Soviet Withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling party on Wednesday opened
its first plenum since the Soviet troop withdrawal and promoted to
the Central Committee several leading figures who opposed Moscow's
intervention in the Afghan war.
   Several rockets slammed into Kabul, killing six people.
   Four members of one family were killed when a missile crashed
through their house and exploded. Women stood in the courtyard of
the house wailing in mourning.
   Another rocket landed in the hills behind Kabul.
   The plenum was held amid tight security in deteriorating
government buildings in downtown Kabul. It elected 19 new full
members and one alternate to the policy-making Central Committee of
the ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan, a government
spokesman said. Two new members were also appointed to the
Politburo, the highest policy-making body in the country.
   A tank manned by several soldiers stood at one end of the street
near the meeting place. Dozens of troops patrolled the streets
nearby.
   The party changes were intended to unite the party and increase
support from the military, diplomats and an Afghan government
source said.
   President Najib addressed the meeting and said the party was
ready to unite with all ``progressive'' groups to achieve peace in
Afghanistan. It was the first full party meeting since October 1988.
   The Soviet-backed government is in the middle of a civil war
against U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas. Although fighting appears
stalemated, the rebels control much of the countryside.
   Among the new Central Committee members are Karim Misaq and
Abdul Ghorbandi, both leading members of the ruling party's Khalq
faction, which opposed the Soviet military intervention in 1979.
   The intervention brought Khalq's opponent, the Parcham faction,
to power.
   The two factions have been bitter enemies since the 1960s.
Traditionally, Khalq, which means ``masses,'' had much support in
the military and Parcham, meaning ``flag,'' was popular among
intellectuals. Neither can claim much popular support.
   The Khalq group has long been critical of Moscow's military
presence in Afghanistan and blames Afghanistan's current plight on
the policies of the Parcham.
   Since the last Soviet troops withdrew in February, the party's
Parcham leadership, especially Najib, has sought to blunt such
criticism by bringing Khalq members into government.
   ``These moves are necessary to show the rebels that our ranks
are united,'' said a government official, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``We are showing that we have a strong party.''
   The official said the Parcham group was also bringing Khalq
people into the Central Commtttee because they need military
support. The Khalq group has strong military backing. It was the
military that put the Khalq faction in power in April 1978 when
officers loyal Khalq staged a Communist coup.
   Soviet forces intervened in December 1979 to replace that
government with another, then stayed to help fight the guerrillas.
   Also appointed to the Central Committee were the secretaries of
several provincial party committees.
   Afghan guerrillas said they have scored more victories against
government forces in the past two weeks than at any time since the
Soviet troops left.
   Najibullah Lefrey, information minister in the rebels'
government-in-exile, made the claim in a news conference in
Islamabad, Pakistan. The guerrillas are based in Pakistan.
   This month, the guerrillas stopped a major army convoy that was
heading south from Kabul to supply troops defending Khost, an
eastern garrison town 90 miles away that has been under siege since
August.
   Lefrey said the air force then tried to drop supplies to Khost
by parachute but that many landed in guerrilla-controlled areas
nearby.
  
</TEXT>
