<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Soviet     10-25 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Soviet,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Meets Communist Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze said Wednesday his country is determined to maintain
friendly relations with Poland's Communists and with the
non-Communists leading the government.
   ``I think it is an interesting period and obviously this
situation deserves introducing some corrections,'' the chief Soviet
diplomat said when asked about the current state of Soviet-Polish
relations.
   ``First of all we have to rebuild the mechanisms of economic
relations and increase the effectiveness of our cooperation,'' he
said, without elaborating.
   A joint communique said both sides agreed mutual problems should
be solved on the basis of the principles of freedom of choice and
non-intervention in internal affairs.
   Shevardnadze is the highest-ranking Soviet official to visit
Poland since the election to prime minister Aug. 24 of Tadeusz
Mazowiecki, the East bloc's first non-communist prime minister.
After meeting with him Tuesday, Shevardnadze announced Mazowiecki
will visit Moscow next month.
   Shevardnadze demonstrated Moscow's apparent openness to Polish
pluralism Wednesday when he invited Adam Michnik, a top Solidarity
editor and former political prisoner, to join him for part of a
session with Communist Party leader Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski.
   Afterward, Shevardnadze declared he is willing to meet with
``every party, with anybody.''
   Michnik, editor in chief of the pro-Solidarity Gazeta Wyborcza
daily and one of Poland's keenest observers of Soviet affairs, was
the only journalist ushered into the Central Committee conference
room. They talked for about 10 minutes before Shevardnadze came out
and spoke with other reporters.
   The Soviet government has said it views the radical changes in
Poland as internal political matters. Shevardnadze said the Soviet
Union is determined to maintain friendly relations with the new
Solidarity-led coalition government as well as with Poland's
Communist Party.
   Speaking of ``blanks spots'' in Polish-Soviet history, such as
the massacre of Polish soldiers on Soviet soil during World War II,
Shevardnadze said they would be cleared up.
   ``We want only the truth. It is needed by our two nations and is
in the interest of friendship,'' he said.
   The joint communique said both sides had ``confirmed the will to
explain some problems and history of Polish-Soviet relations.
Quickening of these works is in the interest of both sides.''
   The most important is the massacre of nearly 4,500 Polish
officers at the Katyn Forest in World War II. A Polish commission
has traced responsibility to Soviet secret police, but there has
been no response from the Soviets.
   Asked what the limits to Soviet tolerance of changes in Poland
are, Shevardnadze said, ``We don't set up order in other countries.
Would you want it to be so?''
   The meeting with Rakowski was followed by a meeting with
President Wojciech Jaruzelski, a Communist. They embraced warmly
and posed for photographers before beginning private discussions.
   During talks with new Foreign Minister Krzysztof Skubiszewski on
Tuesday, Shevardnadze pledged that the Soviet Union will maintain
crucial deliveries of oil and raw materials to Poland, its largest
economic partner in the East bloc.
   Moscow provides nearly 85 percent of Poland's crude oil, 65
percent of its processed petroleum products, and 72 percent of its
iron ore.
   Shevardnadze told the official PAP news agency his country is
interested in an intensification of economic relations with Poland.
``Cooperation is simply necessary because the Soviet and Polish
economies are complimentary to each other in many spheres,'' he
said.
   Shevardnadze said trade with Poland represents about 10 percent
of his country's total foreign trade, while the Soviet Union
receives about one-third of Polish trade.
   Both countries are in the midst of economic crisis, but the new
Polish government has made a firm commitment to introduce a market
economy and is seeking to renegotiate its contacts with its East
bloc trading partners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
