<FIRST>r w AM-US-Korea     10-25 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Korea,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea To Announce Controversial Jet Deal in November</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea plans to purchase 120 U.S. jet
fighters under a co-production agreement that one senator predicts
will spark a ``bitter brawl'' between Congress and the
administration, officials said Wednesday.
   South Korean Defense Minister Lee Sang Hoon has informed Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney that the Seoul government will announce its
choice between two U.S. fighters early next month, said Pentagon
sources.
   Cheney was told of the decision during a courtesy call at the
Pentagon last week, said the sources, who spoke on condition of not
being identified by name.
   Lee was in Washington during the visit of South Korean President
Roh Tae Woo.
   The South Koreans will choose between the F@A-18 Hornet, built
by the McDonnell Douglas Corp., or the F-16 Falcon built by General
Dynamics Corp., in order to modernize their fleet of aging F-5
fighters.
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., an opponent of the co-production plan,
said through an aide on Wednesday that the deal could be worth $1.8
billion to $3 billion.
   The aide said Dixon foresees a ``bitter, bitter brawl'' between
Congress and the Bush administration over the plan and contends it
will cost U.S. jobs and harm American aerospace and aviation
industries.
   The senator plans to offer a resolution in the Senate to express
disapproval of the deal ``as soon as it is official,'' said the
aide, who asked not to be identified by name.
   The Koreans proposed to buy 12 fighters off-the-shelf from U.S.
manufacturers, assemble 36 from U.S.-supplied kits and then build
72 on their own, an arrangement that has been accepted by U.S.
negotiators.
   Pentagon spokesman Navy Lt. Cmdr. Edward Lundquist confirmed
that U.S. and Korean negotiators ``have agreed to a 12-36-72 mix.''
   Lundquist said 12 aircraft will be fully built in the United
States, 36 will be assembled in South Korea from imported parts and
72 planes will be built in South Korea under the licensed
co-production agreement.
   ``A significant portion of the co-produced aircraft will be
produced in the United States ... At least 70 percent of the
program's value will be spent in the United States,'' he said.
   During a visit to the Pentagon in July, Lee said the decision on
the purchase of the 120 fighters was to be announced in September.
   Cheney said after that July session that he preferred the
Koreans purchase the planes ready-made by U.S. manufacturers, but
added that the final agreement would ``probably be some blend'' of
outright purchase and co-production.
   The defense secretary added that he was pleased the Koreans had
decided to purchase U.S. planes over those of other nations.
</TEXT>
