<DOCNO> AP891025-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1643EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Nicaragua     10-25 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aministration Complains to Moscow About Arms Shipped to Salvadoran
Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration complained to Moscow
on Wednesday that Nicaragua is still shipping Soviet-bloc arms to
Salvadoran rebels, despite repeated Soviet and Nicaraguan denials.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, citing the seizure of a
truckload of weapons on the Nicaraguan-Hondran border, called the
continued shipments ``a major problem.''
   ``We've had an extended dialogue with the Soviet Union about the
importance of using their influence to stop that kind of
activity,'' Baker said.
   At the same time, President Bush extended for another six months
a U.S. trade embargo against Nicaragua first imposed by President
Reagan in mid-1985.
   In a statement announcing the renewal of the sanctions, Bush
said the Central American nation continues to pose ``an unusual and
extraordinary threat to national security and foreign policy of the
United States.''
   Bush must report to Congress twice a year on the status of the
embargo and on U.S.-Nicaraguan relations.
   The developments came as Bush prepared for a visit to Costa
Rica, where he and 17 other heads of state _ including Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega _ will join in festivities marking 100
years of Costa Rican democracy.
   Baker, briefing reporters on Bush's trip, said the president
would not meet with Ortega during the two-day visit that begins
Friday.
   He cited continued clandestine shipments by Oretga's Sandinista
government of East-bloc arms to leftist Salvadoran rebels as one
reason why a Bush-Ortega meeting would be ``inappropriate''
   ``Nicaragua clearly continues to ship arms'' to the
anti-government rebels, Baker said.
   ``It is a major problem that we have called to the attention of
the Soviet Union, and called to their attention as recently as
today,'' Baker said.
   Asked whether the apparent continued shipments undermine Soviet
credibility, Baker said: ``It is a major stumbling block.''
   The Soviets have denied any knowledge of the shipments.
   The Honduran military last Wednesday seized what officials
called a record shipment of weapons being sent from Nicaragua
through Hondurus to rebels in El Salvador.
   The State Department says the captured weaponry includes 20 AKM
assault rifles, with 13 of Soviet manufacture. The remainder were
made in other Soviet-bloc countries.
   The cargo also reportedly included more than 300 rifle grenades,
800 mortar shells, large quantities of Soviet-made hand grenades,
50 other assault weapons or machine guns, large quantities of
ammunition, explosives and military radios, according to the State
Department. Much of the equipment was wrapped in Nicaraguan
newspapers.
   Also included with the weapons were instruction booklets with
``FMLN'' on the cover, the letters of the Spanish-language name of
the Salvadoran ``liberation'' effort.
   Salvadoran government officials have told the State Department
that the truck was registered in the name of a ``known FMLN front
group,'' U.S. officials said.
   ``At the very least, the government of Nicaragua is not doing
what they are telling the Soviet Union, based on what the Soviet
Union tells us,'' Baker told reporters.
   Noting that Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze had
recently visited Nicaragua, Baker said: ``It would appear to me the
Nicaraguans are telling them one thing and doing something else,''
Baker said.
   The Bush administration wants to see Ortega's government voted
out of office in the election next Feb. 25, and contends that
election preparations unfairly benefit the ruling Sandinistas.
   Bush, in his six-month report to Congress on the status of the
Nicaragua embargo, said ``the trade sanctions are an essential
element of our policy that seeks a democratic outcome in Nicaragua
by diplomatic means.''
   The embargo bars imports from Nicaragua and bans U.S. exports to
that country except to support the Contra rebels fighting the
leftist Sandinista government. It also prohibits Nicaraguan
aircraft or boats from entering the United States.
</TEXT>
