<FIRST>r i AM-SFQuake-Japan     10-25 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Japan,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baseball Group Donating $100,000 to California Quake Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japan Professional Baseball Association said
Wednesday it is donating $100,000 from proceeds from Japan's
version of the World Series to victims of the earthquake in
California.
   In its announcement, the association noted that former President
Ronald Reagan, now visiting Japan, had thrown out the ceremonial
first pitch at Game 3 of the Japan Series on Tuesday.
   As Reagan entered the field, a public address system announcer
asked the audience to make donations to U.S. quake victims ``in
order to promote U.S.-Japanese relations.''
   In the best-of-seven Japan Series, the Pacific League champion
Kintetsu Buffaloes led the Central League champion Yomiuri Giants
three games to one after the Giants' 5-0 victory Wednesday.
   Many people in Japan, which also is subject to devastating
earthquakes, received their first word of the California disaster
as they tuned in to watch a live satellite broadcast of Game 3 of
the World Series from San Francisco on Oct. 17.
</TEXT>
