<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HomeSales     10-25 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>September Home Sales Hit Highest Level This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes, responding to lower
interest rates, climbed 4.3 percent in September to the highest
level this year, a real estate trade group said Wednesday.
   The National Association of Realtors said existing single-family
homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.63
million units last month following a 4.5 percent sales increase in
August.
   Analysts credited lower mortgage rates for the back-to-back
monthly increases in sales, with the lower rates meaning families
that had been priced out of the market when rates were rising
earlier in the year can now afford homes.
   At the end of last week, fixed-rate mortgages had dipped back
below 10 percent, averaging 9.92 percent, according to a weekly
survey conducted by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. Last
spring, mortgage rates hit a peak of 11.22 percent, reflecting a
year-long effort on the part of the Federal Reserve to push rates
higher in an effort to dampen inflationary pressures.
   With signs that inflation was easing, the Fed has relented and
has been nudging rates lower in response to signs of sluggish
economic growth.
   ``Many people who were forced to put off trading up or entering
the market earlier this year are making their move now,'' said Ira
Gribin, president of the Realtors association. ``With mortgage
rates lower during the second half of the year than the first, the
market is reaching a broader income range of buyers.''
   The national median price for an existing single-family home
fell from August to September by $1,400 to $93,400. The median, or
mid-point, price was still 5.5 percent higher than it was a year
ago.
   Analysts attributed the one-month price drop in large part to
the fact that the market in September shifts away from larger
families to smaller households buying smaller homes.
   Regionally, the sales advance was paced by a 12.7 percent
increase in the West, where homes were sold at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 620,000 units in September.
   Sales were up 3.7 percent in the South to an annual rate of 1.40
million units, while sales rose 1 percent in the Midwest to an
annual rate of 990,000 units.
   Sales were unchanged in the Northeast at 590,000 units. This is
down 9.2 percent from a year ago. Home sales in the Northeast have
been in a slump this year because surging home costs have priced
many buyers out of the market.
   But John Tuccillo, chief economist for the Realtors, said that
sales in the Northeast have come back slightly from a low-point
reached in June and appear to be stabilizing at the current sales
pace.
   ``Housing markets appear to be firming up across the board. We
expect that the lower mortgage rates this fall will keep boosting
sales in the moderate-price range,'' Tuccillo said.
   The most expensive housing market in September was the
Northeast, where a median-priced home went for $144,800, followed
by the West at $144,300. The median sales price in the South was
$84,200 while the Midwest offered the cheapest housing with a
median price of $71,800 in September.
   The national sales pace of 3.63 million units was the fastest
clip since homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
3.92 million units last December.
</TEXT>
