<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1651EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-MarinaSchool     10-25 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Marina School,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students And Homeless Sharing Schoolgrounds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixth-graders and street people shared
quarters Wednesday as the upscale Marina Middle School reopened for
classes even though a Red Cross shelter for 175 earthquake victims
remained in the gym and cafeteria.
   On a sunny morning, students played basketball in the yard while
a few feet away scruffy-looking street people walked between
temporary metal barricades to breakfast. One man washed his hair
using canned water. There was no contact between the mismatched
schoolmates.
   Red Cross officials estimated about half the homeless were
displaced residents of the affluent area, while the other half
permanently lived on the streets.
   Some of the fresh-faced students were upset that the homeless
were still in the building more than a week after the Oct. 17
quake, even though security is heavy and segregation nearly total.
   ``It might be disturbing the students,'' said student Kevin Wong
as he headed into classes.
   A student who wouldn't give his name said some children feel
they have sacrificed enough by giving up a week of classes so the
victims could be housed.
   With the cafeteria turned over to the homeless, students have to
bring bag lunches. Wednesday morning the cafeteria featured an
obscenity-filled screaming match between two street people, who had
to be separated by security guards. Outside in the yard lay a
bundle of filthy clothes.
   ``It's sort of wierd,'' said one girl, who school officials
would not allow to give her name. ``We can't get to the gym.''
   But administrators said they were happy to help.
   ``These are people who need the help,'' said Assistant Principal
Norm Sui. ``Things are going fine.''
   He estimated 90 percent of the 950 students were back in
classes, in grades six, seven and eight.
   The school stay was a trip back in time for retired army nurse
Mabel Doss, whose nearby apartment was heavily damaged by the quake.
   ``It's amazing how much you've grown when you come back to sit
in these little seats,'' Ms. Doss said as she ate a breakfast of a
banana, orange slices and a turnover.
   ``This is better food than I've been eating,'' said Rick
Marshall, who said he normally lives on the street.
   ``I think there's a spirit that exists in the gymnasium here,''
he said. ``There's a lot of emotional support and hugging.''
   Red Cross officials say the shelter will remain open as long as
people need it.
</TEXT>
