<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1659EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CoalStrike     10-25 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Labor Secretary Named Mediator for Coal Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Labor Secretary W.J. Usery Jr. on
Wednesday stepped into the fray between the Pittston Co. and 1,700
striking miners as the government's super mediator, saying he hopes
to provide ``different ideas, different everything'' to bring an
end to the 7-month-old walkout.
   Usery, tapped by current Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole to
intervene in the three-state strike, admitted initial reluctance to
do so because of the acrimony between the two sides, which haven't
bargained directly with one another since the walkout began in
April.
   ``This is one that you didn't jump at so quick,'' said Usery, a
veteran mediator who served as labor secretary in the final year of
the Ford administration.
   Still, he said he would get to work immediately and hoped a
settlement could be reached by the holidays. He did not say whether
he meant Thanksgiving or Christmas.
   Mrs. Dole said the decision to appoint a ``super mediator'' was
not a sign of disappointment with the federal mediators currently
involved in the negotiations. But she said her recent visit with
Pittston strikers and her three-way meeting with company Chairman
Paul Douglas and United Mine Workers President Richard Trumka had
convinced her of the need to name a mediator of greater stature.
   ``I believe that Bill Usery is precisely the right person,'' she
told reporters.
   Added Usery: ``There comes a time that the parties themselves,
the process, needs an additional thrust, needs someone else, needs
a different voice, different suggestions, different ideas,
different everything. I hope that I'm the person who can bring this
to a stop.''
   A spokeswoman for Pittston Coal Group, Susan Copeland, said
that, ``although we have not worked with Mr. Usery in the past, his
integrity and reputation for fairness are very well known and we
look forward to working closely with him.''
   She said the company resisted the union's efforts to get Usery
involved earlier this year ``because we felt at that time that all
other bargaining possibilities had not been exhausted.''
   Trumka, in a statement, said Usery ``is familiar with the
industry, has an intimate knowledge of the significance of the
issues involved and possesses a reputation for fairness and
impartiality. A better choice for mediator could not have been
made.'' Trumka urged daily, face-to-face bargaining sessions.
   Usery said he had been in touch with Pittson, which had objected
to a union request several months ago that Usery be asked to
mediate the dispute.
   ``They called and assured me that they would give me their full
cooperation and were hopeful that a resolution would be found,'' he
said.
   Usery said he would begin private, separate discussions
Wednesday with the principals in the dispute and hoped to arrange a
face-to-face meeting soon.
   ``We'll be working at it quite rapidly,'' he said, adding that
marathon bargaining sessions were possible once he was up to speed
on the issues. Health benefits, particularly those paid to
pensioners, have been the major issue dividing the company and its
miners in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky.
   Since leaving government, Usery has headed a Washington labor
relations firm that bears his name. Among the dozens of major
strike he has mediated were a six-month strike by the United Auto
Workers against Deere &amp; Co. in 1987 and a three-week strike by
Chicago teachers in 1983.
   The Hardwick, Ga., native was appointed assistant secretary of
labor in 1969 and headed the Federal Mediation and Conciliation
Service from 1973 until Ford tapped him for the Cabinet post in
1976.
</TEXT>
