<FIRST>r w AM-HostageAwareness     10-25 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostage Awareness,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Observance Set For Captives in Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Associated Press correspondent Terry
Anderson's fifth birthday as a captive in Lebanon should refocus
public attention on the plight of Western hostages in the Middle
East, members of Congress said Wednesday.
   Senate GOP leader Bob Dole and Reps. Paul Henry, R-Mich., and
Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, called on Americans to observe Anderson's
42nd birthday Friday. They recommended wearing yellow ribbons,
ringing church bells at noon, praying for the hostages' release and
observing a moment of silence at sporting events.
   ``They will not and should not be forgotten,'' Dole, R-Kan.,
said at a Capitol news conference. ``We're asking ... that we take
action to symbolize our dedication toward winning their release.''
   Henry sponsored a congressional resolution to designate Friday
as National Hostage Awareness Day, which President Bush signed into
law Monday.
   Anderson, the AP's chief Middle East correspondent, was siezed
March 16, 1985, and is the longest held of eight Americans being
held in Lebanon.
   The lawmakers declined to discuss the U.S. government's handling
of the hostage situation or statements made this week by Iranian
President Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani and Islamic Jihad, a
pro-Iranian group holding at least two hostages.
   Rafsanjani told reporters he was in no hurry to improve
relations with the United States and gave no hint that his
government was pushing to gain the hostages' release. Islamic Jihad
reiterated its offer to swap Anderson and hostage Thomas Sutherland
for 15 Shiite Moslems jailed in Kuwait.
   ``We're trying to avoid injecting ourselves into some of the
political and policy'' matters, Henry said. ``The focus of this is
what are we in America doing to keep this situation before us.''
   Former hostages have said their spirits were bolstered by public
observances on their behalf, which they managed to hear about
despite their isolation, Henry said.
   Relatives of the hostages and former hostages will be among the
participants in a Catholic ``Mass of Hope'' Friday at Georgetown
University in Washington, said Carmella LaSpada, spokeswoman for No
Greater Love, a hostage support group.
   Besides Anderson and Sutherland, the other U.S. hostages are
Frank H. Reed, Joseph J. Cicippio, Edwin A. Tracy, Jessee J.
Turner, Alann B. Steen and Robert B. Polhill.
</TEXT>
