<DOCNO> AP891025-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1700EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-NATO     10-25 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alliance Voices Concern over Soviet Short-range Nuclear Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILAMOURA, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO defense ministers urged the
Soviets on Wednesday to reduce their short-range nuclear arsenal
and cautioned the West against dropping its guard because of the
democratic trend in Eastern Europe.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney of the United States and the other
defense chiefs welcomed Moscow's offer of unilateral cuts in
conventional forces, but said those would have little effect on the
Warsaw Pact's nuclear capabilities.
   In a statement ending a two-day semiannual meeting of the
Western alliance's Nuclear Planning Group, the ministers ``called
again on the Soviet Union to reduce unilaterally its short-range
missile systems to current NATO levels.''
   They said the Soviets maintained a ``massive superiority'' in
short-range nuclear weapons by updating their systems.
   Cheney told reporters afterward: ``The Soviet Union still
possesses enormous military capability. Their strategic capability
is more robust today than it was when Gorbachev came to power.''
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev became Communist Party chief in
March 1985.
   The NATO ministers said the alliance's nuclear warheads in
Western Europe had been reduced by more than one-third since 1979
to the lowest level in more than 20 years.
   According to Western estimates, the Soviet Union has 1,450
short-range missile launchers in Europe. NATO has 88 Lance
launchers, most of them in West Germany.
   Gorbachev has promised to withdraw 500 short-range nuclear
weapons from Europe this year.
   Two days after Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze admitted
the disputed Krasnoyarsk radar in Siberia violates the 1972
anti-ballistic missile treaty, the ministers welcomed the Soviet
offer to dismantle it.
   Their statement stressed ``the importance of full compliance
with arms control agreements'' and said NATO looked forward ``to
the prompt and full implementation of this commitment'' on
Krasnoyarsk.
   About democratic reforms spreading through Eastern Europe,
Cheney said ``there is great uncertainty about how events will
unfold in the Soviet Union'' and cautioned against a ``euphoric
attitude.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater was asked in Washington
about Shevardnadze's proposal this week during a speech to Soviet
legislators of negotiations on disbanding NATO and the Warsaw Pact.
Fitzwater replied:
   ``We don't have a position on their idea. We think NATO is
important. We expect the NATO pact to be in existence for some
time. Otherwise, we don't have any comment.''
   Defense Minister Tom King of Britain said the 16-member NATO
alliance was ``even more important now, at this time of manifest
change in the Warsaw Pact and in the Soviet Union itself.'' He said
Western defense efforts were ``no obstacle at all to improved
East-West relations.''
   All 16 NATO nations attended the Portugal meeting except France,
which does not belong to the alliance's integrated military
structure. Iceland, which has no armed forces, was present as an
observer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
