<DOCNO> AP891025-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1707EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Quake-FreewayWine     10-25 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quake-Freeway Wine,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shock Over Wine Theft From I-880 Collapse Where Trucker Died</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Napa Valley vintner Daryl Sattui feels
contempt for the thief who stole his wine after it fell from a
truck whose driver was among those killed in the collapsed Oakland
freeway.
   ``Perhaps I can see people stealing something, but when they're
stealing under those circumstances, I can think that even a thief
might not stoop to do it,'' said Sattui, whose great-grandfather,
Vittorio, started making wine in 1885. Today, none of the Sattui
wine is sold in stores, only at the winery and by subscription.
   In a rented truck, driver Gary K. Watson of Napa was northbound
on the lower roadway of the double-deck Nimitz Freeway when the
quake hit. His cargo, headed for shipment to customers, was 70
nine-liter cases of wine from the V. Sattui Winery in St. Helena.
   Neither Sattui nor most of the people from the winery personally
knew Watson, who was a temporary hire for the upcoming holiday
season.
   Watson's truck was crushed and Watson was killed along with at
least 38 others. But four plastic-foam-packed cases of Sattui wine,
some of it the $100-a-bottle 1981 cabernet sauvignon reserve,
plummeted 40 feet to the street.
   For six days, the surviving bottles sat on the street, skirted
by rescue workers in the desperate search for survivors from the
pancaked tons of concrete and twisted steel. At one point they were
gathered and stacked neatly under the freeway, out of the way.
   They had become an eloquent symbol of priorities amid the death
and destruction. Rescuers looked at the wine, but nobody touched it.
   ``I ain't thinking about it at all, much less taking it or
drinking it,'' a man said the night of the earthquake. ``Besides,
it would be wrong, real wrong, to take anything from this horrible
place that ain't yours.''
   On the seventh day, Monday, somebody stole the bottles.
   ``Makes my skin crawl,'' rescue worker Warner Brown told the San
Francisco Chronicle. ``Whoever got it, he can have it. ... I bet
some guy thought about that nice wine all week ... temptation
finally just got the better of his sense. Deep down, he doesn't
really want that wine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
