<FIRST>r w AM-Hollings-BudgetLaw     10-25 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hollings-Budget Law,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Don't Call It Gramm-Rudman-Hollings, Pleads Hollings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of insisting that his name be
welded to a law requiring sharp cuts in the federal deficit, Sen.
Ernest F. Hollings wants a divorce from the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings
deficit reduction act.
   ``I want a divorce because they are using the law as a shield to
hide behind, instead of as a sword to spur us in the right
direction,'' the South Carolina Democrat said in an interview
Wednesday.
   ``I want a divorce on grounds of infidelity and irreconcilable
differences,'' he said, abandoning his once-strong campaign to make
sure the legislation was referred to as Gramm-Rudman-Hollings
instead of just Gramm-Rudman.
   Hollings accused his partners in shaping the act, Sens. Warren
Rudman, R-N.H., and Phil Gramm, R-Texas, of succumbing to a numbers
game in which figures are shifted from column to column, the budget
debate is dominated by smoke and mirrors, and the defict goes up,
not down.
   ``I think that's blasphemy,'' he said. ``I need a divorce.''
   Hollings said that the process actually worked in the first two
years after the passage of the defict reduction bill in 1985.
   ``We cut $11.3 billion,'' he said.
   But then, Hollings said, an agreement between Congress and the
White House ``started the monkeyshines and the subterfuge.''
   ``It was a game of `anything you can do, I can do better,'' he
said.
   ``And we know it's fraudulent.''
   Hollings accused Gramm of arguing for truth in budgeting while
at the same time ``leading the pack'' on the Senate floor to take
the bailout of the faltering savings and loan industry out of the
budget process.
   Hollings complained of the use of other ``tricks and dodges'' to
avoid the money bite in the law he helped create.
   For example, he said that a savings of $2.9 billion was claimed
by moving a payday at the Pentagon to Sept. 29 from Oct. 1, placing
it in the 1989 fiscal year instead of the current 1990 fiscal year.
   For a while, he said, the annual deficit actually did turn
modestly downward.
   ``Now we're going up and up; we're not even going in the right
direction,'' he said.
</TEXT>
