<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     10-25 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Sales Approved</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has been given the go-ahead
to buy up to 16 million metric tons of U.S. grain in the year that
began Oct. 1, the Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   John B. Campbell, acting undersecretary for international
affairs and commodity programs, said the clearance to buy more
grain resulted from recent communication between the two countries.
   Under a long-term grain supply agreement, which began its
seventh year on Oct. 1, the Soviets are committed to buy at least 9
million tons of wheat and corn each year, with a maximum of 12
million tons allowed without further consultations.
   If more than 12 million tons are desired, the United States must
give its approval.
   So far in the 1989-90 year, the Soviets have bought 7.87 million
tons of corn, 143,700 tons of soybeans and 430,000 tons of soybean
meal. No wheat has been sold yet for delivery in 1989-90, but the
agreement specifies that at least 4 million tons must be purchased.
   Last year the Soviets bought a record of more than 21.7 million
tons of U.S. grain, including more than 16.3 million tons of corn
and nearly 5.4 million tons of wheat.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat or 39.4 bushels of corn.
</TEXT>
