<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Volunteeers     10-25 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Volunteeers,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Popular TV Shows Highlight Volunteerism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and the three major commercial
television networks unveiled plans Wednesday to air episodes on
``The Cosby Show'' and other popular programs in the hope of
getting viewers to volunteer in the fight against hunger and
homelessness.
   The president, surrounded by television stars and network
executives at the White House, warmly applauded the initiative.
   ``The days when TV and the movies glorified violence and drugs
and crime are fading,'' the president declared. ``And in place of
these negative images, we're seeing a more positive message of
caring, of compassion and of hope.''
   The networks _ ABC, NBC and CBS _ have agreed to air during the
first three weeks of December at least two episodes of six major
shows devoted to hunger, homelessness and other problems that
volunteers can tackle.
   The shows, in addition to ``The Cosby Show,'' include
``Cheers,'' ``Murder She Wrote,'' ``Head of the Class,''
``Thirtysomething'' and ``Designing Women.''
   At the end of each show, viewers will be invited to call a toll
telephone number to receive for a $2 charge a guide to volunteering
as well as the phone number of a volunteer center in the caller's
area. The United Way and other organizations are also participating
in the project, dubbed ``Prime Time to End Hunger.''
   ``In that book, you can find what you can do, where you can go
and how you can help,'' said Khristyne Haje of ``Head of the
Class,'' one of five performers who joined Bush on stage in the
Rose Garden.
   ``It's time _ prime time _ to end hunger and drug abuse and
homelessness,'' declared Bush.
   ``Television provides a window into the homes of millions of
Americans every single night,'' said Bush. ``From the comfort of
our homes and the company of our families, your shows are going to
make us think and think hard about people who are hungry, homeless,
those without hope, and how we can help them.''
   ``These shows can be catalysts to greater community
involvement,'' he said, adding, ``I hope that every TV set in
America is tuned in to your shows those first three weeks in
December.''
   Asked afterwards if they agreed that violence and drugs were
``fading'' from the television screen, actress Joan Van Ark said
the industry is toning things down.
   Van Ark, who plays Valenne Ewing on ``Knots Landing,'' a spinoff
from Dallas, said, ``They have definitely cut back on J.R.'s trip
to the bar cart.''
   And now, whenver an actor gets into a car, ``the seat belts go
on instantly,'' she added.
   It is important to deliver such messages ``gently,'' she said,
and not to ``suddenly pull the plug on violence.''
</TEXT>
