<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2101EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Baby'sBlood     10-25 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby's Blood,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Treatment Of Infant Over Parents' Objections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge granted doctors permission to give
blood transfusions to a premature baby Wednesday over the
objections of the infant's parents, who oppose the procedure
because of their religious beliefs.
   However, Superior Court Judge Paul A. Lowengrub said doctors at
Our Lady of Lourdes Medical Center in Camden may only give a
transfusion in the event of a medical emergency.
   And a court-appointed medical guardian will make the decision to
give the infant blood if alternative treatments are exhausted,
Lowengrub said.
   The infant has not yet needed a transfusion, but hospital
officials sought the order as a precaution after learning of the
parents' objections to the procedure.
   The infant, weighing nearly five pounds, was delivered six weeks
prematurely by Caesarean section Sunday. The baby was pale and was
kept on a ventilator for the first 48 hours, according to court
documents.
   Neonatal specialists at the hospital said the infant could be at
risk because of low blood pressure and a low hemoglobin rate. The
hospital even reduced blood sampling to conserve the infant's blood
supply, according to Dr. Margaret Fernandes, chief of the
neonatology unit.
   Lowengrub first signed a temporary order Tuesday allowing
doctors to perform blood transfusions if necessary. After a hearing
Wednesday, the judge extended his order for the duration of the
infant's hospitalization.
   The parents of the baby boy, identified in court documents only
as ``Baby Caban,'' had objected to the procedure, saying it was
against their beliefs as Jehovah's Witnesses to allow the
transfusion of blood or blood products into their bodies.
   Followers of the faith believe transfusions go against the
teachings of the Bible, citing a passage of Leviticus that reads:
``Whatsoever man ... eats any manner of blood, I will cut him off
from among his people.''
   ``What they want to do is follow their religious tenets,'' said
Carl A. Price, the parents' attorney, who would not identify the
Willingboro couple. ``They want to be able to make the decision
about any medical treatment that they would receive and their child
would receive.''
   Lowengrub, however, rejected their arguments.
   ``Parents may choose to become martyrs themselves, but they
cannot make martyrs of their children,'' the judge said. ``The
right to belief is absolute, but the exercise of that belief is
not.''
   Under Lowengrub's order, the couple will make all other medical
decisions for their child.
   Michael Brennan, the hospital's attorney, said the hospital has
sought similar orders at least twice, but has never had to give
transfusions to patients who objected.
   He said the infant's condition has improved and he may not need
a transfusion.
</TEXT>
