<FIRST>r w AM-KennedyCenter     10-25 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kennedy Center,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kennedy Center Chairman Announces Plans to Resign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph P. Davidson announced Wednesday he will
resign as chairman of the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing
Arts when his contract expires in February 1991 because of
differences with the center's board of trustees.
   Davidson, a former Time Inc. executive, took command of the
national arts center less than two years ago. He is reported to
have drawn complaints from the Kennedy Center board of trustees for
being a poor manager and the focus of personality clashes.
   The 45-member board accepted Davidson's advance notice of his
departure with praise for his ``dedication to the center and his
many management and programming initiatives.'' The board refused
any further comment beyond its five-paragraph statement.
   ``I arrived at my decision after several discussions with the
board and the realization that we had different priorities and
different expectations of each other,'' Davidson said in a separate
statement.
   ``These differences happen in institutions of all kinds and, as
regrettable as they may be, I fully understand the need for a
change for the sake of the institution,'' he said. Davidson did not
explain what those differences were.
   Davidson, 62, was hired in February 1988 to succeed Broadway
producer Roger L. Stevens, the founding chairman who officially
retired last August after a lengthy transition period.
   A search committee led by trustee James Evans was appointed to
find a successor to Davidson, who said he hoped a candidate could
be named by mid-1990.
   Reports of Davidson's disagreements with the trustees surfaced
after the board's last meeting three months ago.
   The trustees were said to have become increasingly upset by
Davidson's aloof management style, his arbitrary treatment of the
Kennedy Center staff and his failure to attend important social
functions.
   The Washington Post reported earlier Wednesday that a recent
internal poll disclosed that a clear majority of 28 trustees did
not want Davidson to remain.
   Davidson receives $125,000 annually as chairman and chief
executive officer of the Kennedy Center, the white marble cultural
center on the Potomac River which opened in September 1971 as the
only official memorial to President John F. Kennedy.
   Davidson was reported to have received a $4 million ``golden
parachute'' when he agreed to take early retirement in 1988 as
chairman of the executive committee of the Time Inc. board of
directors. Stevens, his predecessor at the Kennedy Center, served
as chairman without salary.
</TEXT>
