<HEAD>Officials Stunned by Cocaine Charges Against Police Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROCKTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges that the police chief stole
cocaine stunned city officials, who described him as a warrior
against drugs, but a prosecutor told the court the chief admitted
using cocaine for five years.
   ``My first reaction is absolute shock,'' said City Councilor
Gregory Buckley. ``He has done a terrific job working on the crime
and drug problems in my section of the city.''
   Chief Richard Sproules, a 25-year department veteran and a
former narcotics officer, pleaded innocent Tuesday in Brockton
District Court and was released on his own recognizance. He was
suspended from the department with pay until the case is resolved.
   Sproules, 45, was arrested after a lengthy state police probe
linked him to the disappearance of cocaine from the police
station's evidence room, said Lt. Paul Studenski.
   In Tuesday's court hearing, special prosecutor John Kivlan said
Sproules ``admitted to investigators, in substance, that over a
five-year period, he has been using cocaine on a daily basis.''
   Bruce Edmands, an attorney for Sproules, said his client would
not comment on the case. He said the statements attributed to the
police chief about drug use were taken out of context, and he
called the case ``weak, tenuous at best.''
   ``It's a tough time for the family and we're trying to deal with
it here,'' he said.
   Sproules also worked as a soccer coach at Bridgewater-Raynham
High School.
   ``The kids liked him,'' school Superintendent Edward O'Donoghue
said. ``He carried out his responsibilities in an exemplary way.''
   Sproules has been removed from his coaching duties pending the
outcome of the case, O'Donoghue said Wednesday.
   Brockton is a city of 95,000 people 23 miles south of Boston.
