<FIRST>r a AM-StudentExchange     10-25 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Student Exchange,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Say Stereotypes Often Begin At Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suburban students see Detroit as a city of
rat-infested, rundown buildings where murder and drug-dealing are
rampant. City students see the suburbs as havens of expensive cars,
plush homes and spoiled brats.
   Some of them traded places Wednesday after swapping stories the
day before, and both found out how wrong they were.
   ``They think we all have perfect lives,'' said Shannon Doak, a
17-year-old senior at Dearborn's Edsel Ford High School. ``There
are drugs in the suburbs, too. You just don't hear about it.''
   Hearing about the differences and learning to recognize and
respect them are the aims of the exchange arranged by New Detroit
Inc., an urban coalition founded in 1967 after race riots
devastated much of the city.
   ``The teachers see that the students have a different attitude,
just with the one day they spend in another school,'' Vivian
Buffington, a race relations consultant who organized the program,
said Wednesday.
   The New Detroit exchange program was started four years ago to
promote intercultural harmony and slow racial prejudice among
teen-agers.
   Students, chosen to participate through a variety of methods,
say some of their biggest misconceptions come from home.
   ``My parents don't know both sides, and I think I can help them
see that Detroit isn't what they think it is,'' Aliza Pearlberg, a
17-year-old senior at Southfield-Lathrup High School, said after
Tuesday's session at Mercy College in Detroit.
   Curtis Davenport, from the Interfaith Center for Racial Justice
in Mount Clemens, said students find a conflict between what they
learn at sessions like Tuesday's and what they hear at home.
   ``It's tough for them because a lot of their parents are trying
to socialize them in different beliefs,'' Davenport said.
   In Tuesday's sessions, students from the city and outlying
suburbs formed groups of 30 and played games designed to raise
consciousness to racial equality.
   One game required students from suburbs to draw their
impressions of the city while students from Detroit drew their
concepts of the suburbs.
   ``I get upset that people think you're a charity case if you
come from Detroit,'' said Wade Brown, a 17-year-old Detroit
resident and senior at University Liggett School in fashionable
Grosse Pointe Woods. ``They think that you have only one parent and
live in a slum.''
   Participants in this week's program, one of two held each school
year, were 354 students and 48 teachers.
</TEXT>
