<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1759EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Lebanon     10-25 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Lebanon,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Members Of Congress Plan Lebanon Trip Despite Security Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of Congress plan a trip to Lebanon
to urge Christian leader Michel Aoun to accept a proposed peace
plan, despite warnings from the State Department that their
security cannot be guaranteed, sources said Wednesday.
   Reps. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, and Nick Rahall, D-W.Va., both of
Lebanese-American descent, are seeking a meeting with Gen. Aoun,
the leader of Lebanon's predominantly Christian army who has
withheld his acceptance of the proposal to end the country's
14-year civil war, the sources said. They spoke only on condition
of anonymity.
   Rahall's office declined to discuss his trip, saying ``we can
neither confirm nor deny it, for security reasons.'' A spokesman
for Ms. Oakar said he could not obtain information about her plans.
   The White House, meanwhile, rejected any U.S. attempt to
influence Aoun. ``That's ... an internal matter for Lebanon and the
various factions there to deal with,'' said presidential spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater.
   President Bush did discuss the prospects for peace in Lebanon in
telephone calls Monday and Tuesday with Pope John Paul II,
President Francois Mitterrand of France and King Fahd of Saudi
Arabia, Fitzwater said.
   Bush expressed hope the plan ``would be a step in the direction
of Lebanese reform,'' said Fitzwater.
   The plan, adopted by 63 Lebanese legislators after three weeks
of closed-door meetings in Saudi Arabia, would shift political
control from the Christian minority to the Moslem majority in an
attempt to end the country's 14-year civil war.
   Aoun, who declared a ``war of liberation'' in March to drive the
40,000 Syrian troops from the country, called on the Lebanese
lawmakers to reject the plan when it comes up for a vote next month
because it fails to set a deadline for a Syrian pullout.
   Oakar and Rahall are no strangers to the dangers of Lebanon. In
1982 they visited Beirut at the height of the Israeli invasion to
offer their support for the Lebanese people and condemn the
fighting.
   But State Department officials said the situation now is far
more dangerous because the U.S. Embassy has been evacuated and the
two lawmakers would be completely dependent for their security on
their Lebanese hosts.
   ``We don't oppose their talking to him (Aoun), but we can't
offer any support or help if they get in trouble,'' said one
official, who spoke only on condition of anonymity.
   State Department guidelines prohibit travel by Americans to
Lebanon, in most cases. ``The situation in Lebanon is so dangerous
that no U.S. citizen can be considered safe from terrorist acts,''
according to the guidelines.
   U.S. passports are invalid for travel to Lebanon unless special
permission is obtained. Violation of this ban can be punishable by
imprisonment or a fine, the guidelines say.
   There are eight Americans missing in Lebanon, all believed to
have been kidnapped in the past five years by pro-Iranian radicals.
   The embassy was evacuated last month after Aoun made veiled
threats to take American hostages in order to draw attention to his
fight for expulsion of the Syrians.
