<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-HongKong     10-25 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Hong Kong,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Nearing Action on Vietnamese Boat People in Hong Kong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hong Kong cannot accommodate much longer 43,000
Vietnamese boat people who mainly are economic refugees, Britich
Foreign Secretary John Major said Wednesday.
   ``It is soon going to be necessary to tackle the thorny problem
of involuntary repatriation,'' Major told the House of Commons in
response to a question about the refugees in the British colony.
``It is not reasonable to accept that they will have to stay in
Hong Kong forever and I cannot _ and will not _ accept that.''
   ``We are seeking to cajole and persuade the Vietnamese boat
people to return, but I now have to recognize that the problem in
Hong Kong is acute and getting worse and cannot be borne much
longer,'' Major said.
   Some legislators of the governing Conservative party and the
Labor opposition expressed concern over Major's comments.
   Gerald Kaufman, Labor's foreign affairs spokesman, said the
refugees left Vietnam because the country was poor and that they
had to be dealt with in a humanitarian way.
   ``I think if we are going to have a solution which is humane yet
effective ... economic aid to Vietnam on a substantial scale has
got to be part of the answer,'' he told Channel 4 News.
   James Lester, a Conservative, said the United Nations and the
European Economic Community should help improve life in Vietnam.
   ``Unless we can do that many of us will have grave concerns
about repatriation,'' he said.
   A Foreign Office spokesman said that the 13,000 Vietnamese who
arrived in Hong Kong before 1988 qualified for refugee status
because of religious or political persecution.
   However, the vast majority of the 43,000 Vietnamese who have
arrived since June 1988 are expected to be disqualified on grounds
they left their homeland only to seek a better living elsewhere,
the spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   Only 386 refugees have agreed to return home from Hong Kong
voluntarily since September 1988, he said.
</TEXT>
