<FIRST>r w AM-TeacherPact     10-25 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher Pact,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>College Presidents Agree To Increase Minority Teachers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five college presidents signed an agreement
Wednesday to work together to increase the representation of
blacks, Hispanics and other minorities in the teaching profession.
   Under the agreement, the institutions will work with local high
schools with large minority student bodies to identify 550 students
in grades nine through 12 with potential to develop the
self-confidence and sense of achievement essential for good
teachers.
   A ``Memorandum of Understanding and Intent'' was signed by the
presidents of the City College of New York, Xavier University of
Louisiana, Fordham University, Hostos Community College of New
York, and two institutions of the Ana G. Mendez Educational
Foundation in Puerto Rico, Metropolitan University and the
University of Turabo.
   Officials said the high school students will move through a
rigorous four-year program of Saturday and summer courses,
including field trips and university visits. They will receive
guidance in choosing a college or university and help in seeking
financial backing through scholarships, loans and grants.
   The students' college programs will include special seminars and
workshops, student exchange programs, and hands-on teaching
experience. Students in two-year colleges will be urged to go on to
four-year institutions, and outstanding students will be encouraged
to enter masters or doctorate programs.
   ``We have selected a clear goal: to develop a major,
comprehensive and collaborative model program to increase the
number and enhance the preparation of minority elementary and
secondary school teachers,'' said the agreement. ``We propose to
accomplish this by pooling resources whenever appropriate and
necessary and carrying out joint programs that can serve as model
for institutions nationwide.''
</TEXT>
