<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1831EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-RiotTrial     10-25 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riot Trial,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Delays Effort to Move Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense efforts to move the trial of a police
officer charged in the fatal shooting of a black motorcylist
suffered a setback Wednesday when the judge cut off the hearing and
resumed screening jurors.
   Lawyers for Colombian-born Miami officer William Lozano contend
he cannot get a fair trial on two manslaughter charges in Miami
because jurors might fear that an innocent verdict would touch off
rioting.
   Lozano's shooting of Clement Lloyd, 23, who was being chased by
police, led to three days of racial violence in January. The
suspended officer is also charged in the death of Lloyd's
passenger, Allan Blanchard, 24, killed in the subsequent crash.
   Lozano said Lloyd tried to run him over and he fired in
self-defense. Some witnesses disputed his account and called the
shooting unwarranted.
   The January riot was the fourth related to police slayings of
black men in Miami during the 1980s; two disturbances followed
acquittals of officers.
   Dade Circuit Judge Joseph Farina had sharply limited the
documents and witnesses defense attorney Roy Black could use to
request the change of venue, and on Wednesday, after they were
submitted, indicated he was in no hurry to rule on the issue.
   He cut off the defense presentation, and spent the rest of
Wednesday completing preliminary screening of a pool of more than
220 potential jurors.
   ``There very well may be post-trial difficulties,'' said Farina.
``But we don't need individuals testifying to that.''
   The case was recessed until Monday, when questioning of jurors
will continue. The questioning of jurors, with 15 minutes per side
for each potential juror, could take three weeks, attorneys said.
   Out-of-town depositions are being taken the rest of the week.
   ``Clearly we're disappointed,'' Black said outside the
courtroom. ``It's unfair to have a trial with jurors who are
concerned with something other than guilt or innocence.''
   Prosecutors has sought to quash Black's subpoenas, but did not
dispute the threat of violence in case of acquittal.
   ``There is a degree of probability that a riot will occur,''
said Roy Wood, an assistant Dade County attorney.
   Black had also fought for a change of venue in the case of
officer Luis Alvarez, who in 1984 was acquitted in the 1982 video
arcade shooting of Nevell Johnson. Both the slaying and the
innocent verdict led to disturbances.
   But the attorney said the situations are different.
   ``The atmosphere in this courthouse and the atmosphere in the
community are far worse this time,'' Black said.
</TEXT>
