<SECOND>AM-Finland-Raisa,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Gorbachev Gets a Lesson in Soviet History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Finland-Soviet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raisa Gorbachev got a lesson in 19th
century Russian history Wednesday while her husband, President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, discussed more current affairs with Finnish
leaders.
   Mrs. Gorbachev attracted a small crowd as she visited the
National Museum and an outdoor monument to composer Jean Sibelius,
who wrote the celebrated piece ``Finlandia.''
   She was almost invisible among bodyguards and umbrellas lifted
against the chilly drizzle.
   Mrs. Gorbachev was accompanied by Tellervo Koivisto, wife of
Finland's president; Soviet writer Vasily Bilov; and Valentina
Fedotova, editor of the magazine Soviet Woman.
   Dressed in a dark blue, pinstripe suit with a white blouse and
high-heel suede shoes, Mrs. Gorbachev stretched the museum visit to
almost an hour.
   She paused repeatedly to question her guide, C.J. Gardberg, head
of the Finnish Museum Authority.
   The tour included the throne Czar Alexander I used when opening
the first parliament in Finland after Russia seized it from Sweden
in the early 19th century.
   Finland was a Soviet Grand Duchy for over 100 years until the
1917 revolution.
   Mrs. Gorbachev arrived in Finland on Wednesday with her husband
on a three-day visit.
