<FIRST>r w AM-US-S.Africa     10-25 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-S. Africa,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says More Sanctions Against South Africa Inappropriate Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Wednesday further sanctions against South Africa would be
inappropriate now because of steps the country's new government is
taking toward the black majority.
   Baker said he refused to ``choose sides'' in the Commonwealth
dispute in which British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher refused
to go along with a call by other Commonwealth leaders for further
sanctions.
   Instead, he reiterated that the United States is committed to
ending apartheid by assisting blacks in South Africa economically
and politically and would work through diplomcy to resolve
conflicts.
   ``We're going to continue to work with our allies to support
change in South Africa, and we're going to try and continue to work
with (the U.S.) Congress to develop a bipartisan approach,'' Baker
said.
   He said action taken by President F.W. de Klerk and his
government in recent weeks ``is clearly a step in the right
direction, and I think that that step argues for continued patience
with respect to the question of further sanctions.''
   ``I think it would be inappropriate now to move forward with
further sanctions in the light of the efforts of that new
government _ obvious efforts of that new government to move in the
right direction,'' Baker said.
   Baker didn't refer specifically to steps taken by the de Klerk
government such as freeing of imprisoned black leaders and
permitting anti-apartheid demonstrating.
   The United States has said since September that it doesn't think
sanctions should be increased now but that it might re-evaluate its
position if negotiations between the South African government and
blacks fail to achieve progress by next summer.
</TEXT>
