<FIRST>r i AM-EastGermans-Embassy     10-25 0114</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germans-Embassy,0114</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans At Prague Embassy Can Travel West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 East Germans in the West
German Embassy will be allowed to travel to West Germany as
thousands of others have done, the official news agency CTK
reported Wednesday.
   It said the East German Embassy had been authorized to give them
permission to emigrate. The dispatch was nearly identical to one
from ADN, the official East German agency, and gave no details.
   Almost 60,000 East Germans have fled East Germany since
mid-September through Hungary, Czechoslovakia and Poland. More than
15,000 of them had taken refuge at the West German embassies in
Prague or Warsaw.
</TEXT>
