<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2315EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;LsBorrowing     10-25 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls Borrowing,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>RFC Bonds Snapped Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors on Wednesday snapped up the first of
what will be $30 billion in special government bonds sold to
finance the savings and loan bailout.
   Buyers bid an average yield of 8.15 percent on $4.52 billion in
30-year bonds issued by the Resolution Funding Corp., called
Refcorp.
   The premium over regular Treasury 30-year bonds, which yielded
7.88 percent on Wednesday, was 0.27 percentage points, about what
Treasury Department officials were expecting.
   Economist David Jones of Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co., a government
securities dealer in New York, said investors demand the premium
because the government guarantee of interest payments on the
Refcorp bonds is not as strong as the full faith and credit
guarantee given direct government borrowing.
   ``Considering all of that, I think it was really well bid for.
The bonds were really well received and came in at about the spread
expected,'' he said.
   In the fiscal year ended Sept. 30, the government borrowed $20
billion for S&amp;Ls directly. The complex funding compromise put
together by the administration and Congress calls for an additional
$30 billion in borrowing through Refcorp by Sept. 30, 1991. Regular
quarterly auctions are planned.
   The Refcorp bonds, which the Bush administration favored, have
the advantage of keeping $30 billion out of the federal budget
deficit. However, Jones said that if the interest rate difference
holds at 0.27 percentage points, taxpayers will wind up spending
$2.43 billion extra for that accounting maneuver.
</TEXT>
