<FIRST>u i AM-UN-USDues     10-25 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-US Dues,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>United States Pays $65 Million of UN Dues _ A Day Late</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering
delivered a $65 million check for America's U.N. dues Wednesday, a
day later than intended.
   The U.S. check was meant to be a birthday gift delivered Tuesday
on United Nations Day, commemorating 44 years since the U.N.
Charter came into force on Oct. 24, 1945.
   The State Department sent an envelope that was to have included
the check Tuesday to the U.S. Mission, but someone forgot to
include the check, an official said.
   Pickering instead had to wait another day for the $65 million
check, said the official, who was familiar with the mix-up and
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said in
mid-October that the United Nations had only $68 million in its
General Fund, barely enough to meet expenses through the end of the
month.
   The United States is the U.N. member most in arrears. Before the
latest payment, America owed more than $495 million to the regular
budget and $200 million more for peacekeeping activities.
   The $65 million will be applied to the 1989 U.S. dues of $216
million. The U.N.'s annual budget is about $776 million.
   Beginning in 1985, the Reagan administration began withholding
some of its the U.S. dues to protest what it said was the
organization's anti-Western bias, inefficiency and budget overruns.
   But in September 1988, Reagan announced he was pleased with the
world body's progress toward budget reform, staff cutbacks and a
new spirit of consensus and cooperation.
   Reagan left the details of paying the arrears to President Bush.
   U.S. Congressional subcommittees have given preliminary approval
for payment of $205.5 million toward the full 1990 fiscal year
assessment of $216 million.
   However, they have rejected State Department requests for $46
million more to pay some of the arrears, citing financial
constraints imposed by the U.S. federal budget deficit.
</TEXT>
