<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Rebuild     10-25 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Rebuild,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slow Rebuilding from '87 Quake Damage is Sober Forecast for Bay Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITTIER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents and merchants are still
rebuilding their lives and businesses two years after the Whittier
Narrows earthquake, painting a sobering forecast for cities heavily
damaged in the San Francisco quake.
   Patience, care and drive are the virtues earthquake veterans
here recommend for the communities in the San Francisco Bay region
and south to Santa Cruz County that were jolted Oct. 17 by an
earthquake that registered 7.1 on the Richter scale.
   ``The recovery effort is a function of the spirit of the people
affected by the disaster,'' said Whittier City Manager Tom Mauk.
   Once the community comes out of shock, plans for rebuilding must
be made right away, he said.
   ``It takes a longer time than anybody thinks,'' Mauk said.
``There's a lot to do and the key is you've just got to run and
sprint through it.''
   Speed should be tempered by organization and care for those
going through the process of applying to government agencies for
loans and grants and looking for building contractors, said Bill
Lewis, manager of the building rehabilitation department and code
enforcement.
   ``You always have opportunists,'' Lewis said. ``Unfortunately
some of those opportunists are what they call contractors.''
   The 5.9-magnitude earthquake of Oct. 1, 1987, and a
5.3-magnitude aftershock three days later caused more than $350
million damage in greater Los Angeles, including more than $78
million damage to suburban Whittier.
   About 5,000 homes and businesses were damaged.
   Lewis said the city of Santa Cruz, which was badly damaged in
last week's quake, is ``looking at from two to four years before
everything is put back together.
   ``It's just a massive undertaking,'' he said.
   ``I'm still running very, very skinny,'' saidAnthony Gonzalez,
who operates a bicycle shop in Whittier that's located next door to
a two-story building laced with earthquake cracks and surrounded by
a chain-link fence.
   ``It's not a positive thing having that building next door,'' he
said.
   Most evidence of the quakes _ collapsed walls, shattered glass
and toppled chimneys _ has long since been cleared away, and the
town of 73,000 bustles with traffic and shoppers. But it is clear
that repairs and replacement of what was lost will go on for years.
   The battered Whittier Theater still slumps in the ruins of its
facade and a boarded-up supermarket waits behind a chain-link fence
for wreckers to finish what the earthquake began nearly 25 months
ago.
   A pancaked parking structure at the Whittier Quad shopping
center is gone, along with a multi-story department store that was
the centerpiece, but new stores have yet to take shape on the
freshly graded land.
   A dozen lots remain empty in the quaint Village business
district, some behind fences bearing optimistic slogans: ``Toward
the Future,'' ``Better than Ever'' and ``Developing With Beauty.''
   About 30,000 people visited assistance centers in Southern
California after the Whittier quake. More than 14,000 applicants
got grants for home repairs from the federal Emergency Management
Agency and the Small Business Administration approved 8,400 loan
applications totaling about $150 million.
</TEXT>
