<FIRST>r i AM-SovietSailor     10-25 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Sailor,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescued Soviet Sailor Wants to Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet sailor rescued after drifting in the
Pacific Ocean for 67 days made an unsanctioned solo trip out of the
Soviet Union ``for the adventure of it,'' but he wants to return,
his rescuer said Wednesday.
   Konstantin Rybinster, 30, was brought to this U.S. territory
Wednesday by the container ship USS President Roosevelt.
   ``He wants to return to Russia,'' said Ren W. Vurpillat, captain
of the Roosevelt. ``He spoke to a representative of the State
Department who speaks Russian and he told him he wants to go back.''
   Rybinster, a professional seaman, initially had wanted to reach
San Francisco when he left the Soviet port of Vladivostock on June
2 in a 20-foot sailboat, according to Vurpillat and Charles Kirk,
acting U.S. officer in charge of immigration on Guam.
   Rybinster told authorities the mast on his sailboat broke Aug.
14. The vessel drifted until last Friday, when the Roosevelt
spotted Rybinster's boat near Wake Island, 1,300 miles northeast of
Guam.
   The sailor said he had packed enough food and water for 40 days
and survived on fish and rainwater for the remainder of his ordeal,
Kirk said.
   Rybinster declined to speak with reporters upon his arrival. He
was whisked away in a white van to the Immigration and
Naturalization Service office in Agana.
   Kirk said Rybinster does not want to defect and although his
trip was not authorized, ``he has no qualms about going home.''
   He said Rybinster probably would be returned to the Soviet Union
via Japan in the next few days.
</TEXT>
