<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Libya     10-25 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Libya,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libyans Barred From Entering Italy for `Day of Mourning'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Wednesday blocked more than 800
Libyans who arrived by boat to mark a ``day of mourning'' declared
by Col. Moammar Gadhafi for Libyans deported during Italian
colonial rule.
   The Libyan cruise ship Garnata arrived in port but police barred
the passengers from disembarking because they lacked entrance
visas, Italian officials said.
   The Libyans held up huge photos of Gadhafi and signed a
statement addressed to the Italian government saying they had made
a ``voyage of peace'' to visit the graves of relatives.
   Authorities said 846 Libyan passengers were on board.
   Libyan representatives met with Italian Foreign Ministry
officials in an attempt to get the Libyans into Italy, but there
was no change in the situation by late Wednesday.
   Italian news agencies, quoting unidentified sources in the
premier's office, said the Libyans would not be allowed into the
country. There was no immediate official confirmation.
   Gadhafi, as in other years, set aside Thursday as a day of
mourning for Libyans deported to Italy during colonial rule from
1911 to the end of World War II. Libya says at least 4,000 Libyans
were deported and that Oct. 26 is the 78th anniversary of the first
deportations to remote Italian islands.
   The Libyans on board the cruise ship planned to visit the graves
of relatives and take part in demonstrations in Rome and other
cities on Thursday.
   ``If they don't get the permits to enter Italy, they will go
back to Libya,'' Libya's ambassador, Abdel Rahman Shalgam, told
reporters in Rome.
   In Rome, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said authorities had
agreed to allow about 200 Libyans to come by plane but were taken
by surprise when Gadhafi sent the ship to Naples with 800 people
aboard.
   ``When 800 people arrive at a single port without visas, even if
you wanted to allow them to enter it would take days,'' said the
official, speaking on condition of anonymity as is customary.
   About 170 Libyans with valid visas did arrive by plane and
traveled to the tiny Italian island of Ustica to visit a cemetery
where Libyan deportees were buried.
   The Italian news agency ANSA quoted one of the Libyan crew
members aboard the ship as saying, ``They are all without visas
because they didn't have time to apply for them. It usually takes a
month to get them from the Italian embassy, but the trip was
arranged only a week ago.''
   All flights and international telecommunications will be halted
in Libya for 12 hours Thursday in observance of the day of
mourning, the official Libyan news agency JANA announced earlier
this week.
   The day is part of Gadhafi's persistent demand that Italy pay
reparations for its colonial occupation.
   The Italian government, however, says Italy met its obligations
with payment of an idemnity of 1.5 million British pounds, at the
time worth $6.7 million, under a 1956 agreement with the then
Libyan monarchy.
   Gadhafi deposed the monarchy in a 1969 coup.
</TEXT>
