<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Greece-Terrorism     10-25 0130</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Greece-Terrorism,0133</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Charges Two Arabs in Cruise Ship Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magistrates court Wednesday charged two
Arabs in the deadly attack on a Greek cruise ship in July 1988, a
court spokesman said.
   The court charged Adnan Zosad and Hajak Jaballah with
premeditated murder, causing premeditated explosions, premeditated
arson and the illegal possession and use of weapons.
   Nine people died when the attackers opened fire on tourists and
set off explosives on the City of Poros cruise ship as it
approached Trocadero harbor near Athens.
   A district attorney in this city near Athens issued arrest
warrants for Zosad and Jaballah in January.
   However, investigators have not been able to determine whether
the two escaped from the ship, or were killed or injured in the
explosions.
</TEXT>
