<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2236EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Amnesty-Executions     10-25 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amnesty-Executions,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran, Saudi Arabia Lash Out at Critics of Their Death Penalties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei on
Wednesday lashed out at Amnesty International for complaining of
human rights abuses in Iran, calling the group a Western ``tool.''
   In Riyadh, Saudi officials were quoted as saying criticism of
the kingdom's use of the death penalty is anti-Islamic.
London-based Amnesty has taken Saudi officials to task over the
issue.
   In its annual global survey of human rights released Wednesday,
Amnesty said 142 executions had been announced by Iran last year.
However, it said it had learned of at least 1,700 secret executions.
   The rights group, which opposes capital punishment, issues
periodic lists of people executed or jailed for political reasons.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency of Iran, monitored in
Nicosia, quoted Khamenei as saying that Amnesty ``issues lists now
and then for fun, to impress other nations and discourage them from
sympathizing with the Islamic Republic.''
   ``In their propaganda, our enemies refer to drug traffickers as
political dissidents,'' Khamenei said at a gathering in Tehran.
   By its own figures, Iran has executed more than 1,000 purported
drug traffickers since December.
   Amnesty and some other independent rights groups believe many
political prisoners have been hanged as drug smugglers.
   ``All this propaganda is aimed at marring the image of the
Islamic Republic,'' the Iranian news agency quoted Khamenei as
saying.
   In an interview distributed by the official Saudi Press Agency,
Interior Minister Prince Nayef bin Abdel-Aziz was quoted Wednesday
as stressing that Saudi Arabia is a theocratic state ruled by
Islamic law.
   ``These are laws from God inspired to His Prophet (Mohammed),''
he was quoted as saying.
   Under that law, Islamic courts may prescribe beheading by the
sword and crucifixion for those convicted of heresy or murder, the
chopping off of hands and feet for thieves, and stoning for
adulterers.
   In Saudi Arabia, convicted murderers are routinely beheaded in
public squares in front of mosques after Friday prayers.
   While the interview did not specifically mention Amnesty, Saudi
Arabia's beheading of 16 Moslem Shiites of Kuwaiti nationality last
month brought condemnation by Amnesty and other groups.
   The 16 were convicted by Islamic courts of planting bombs at the
height of the Islamic pilgrimage to Mecca on July 10. One Pakistani
pilgrim was killed, and 16 other pilgrims were injured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
