<DOCNO> AP891025-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-FBISettlement     10-25 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI Settlement,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Agrees To Pay $170,000 To Settle Surveillance Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said Wednesday it will
pay $170,000 to settle a lawsuit by a woman who claims her late
husband was illegally discredited by the FBI's Cointelpro domestic
surveillance program.
   The settlement ends a dispute over information the Justice
Department says would endanger national security if it were
publicly disclosed in the course of the litigation.
   The department invoked the state-secret privilege to protect the
information, but an appeals court ruled that the plaintiff could
proceed with the lawsuit notwithstanding government concerns about
national security.
   The Justice Department appealed the ruling to the Supreme Court
but as part of the settlement will withdraw its petition for
high-court review of the case.
   The Justice Department said it agreed to pay Lillie Albertson
$170,000 to settle her claim that the FBI forced her late husband's
expulsion from the Communist Party in 1964 by making it appear that
he was an FBI or police informant.
   Mrs. Albertson had claimed that FBI agents in New York planted a
fictious report in a car used by party members to make it appear
that her husband was an informant.
   As part of the settlement, Mrs. Albertson agreed to drop her
lawsuit along with a Freedom of Information Act claim for release
of government documents, the department said.
   Both sides stipulated that the settlement was not ``an admission
of liability or fault'' by the U.S. government or any employees,
the department said.
   Mrs. Albertson also agreed to join the Justice Department in
asking the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here to vacate last
April's opinions on the state-secret question. This would mean the
appellate court decision would not have any legal significance as a
precedent.
   In a split decision, a three-judge panel rejected the Justice
Department's request that it order dismissal of the lawsuit in the
ground that state secrets would be revealed.
   The court rejected the Justice Department's assertion that
``evidence of the government's activities of 20 to 30 years ago
will result in the disclosure of state secrets today.''
   In an unusual move, the court published a censored version of a
dissent by Judge Douglas Ginsburg. Twelve of the 18 pages of
Ginsburg's opinion were deleted because they contained classified
information.
   Ginsburg said the government had a ``legitimate and compelling
interest in preventing disclosure of exceedingly senstive national
security information.''
   He cited an affidavit by Assistant FBI Director James H. Geer,
head of the bureau's intelligence division, that disclosure of
evidence would ``pose a serious risk to the personal safety'' of
government informants and ``cause serious damage'' to national
security.
   Kate Martin, an attorney for the American Civil Liberties Union,
which represented Mrs. Albertson, called the settlement a victory
for her client.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891025-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2035EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Abortion-Flips 1stLd-Writethru   10-25 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Flips, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0805,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifteen House Members Switch on Abortion Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf pvs `The 10 ...' with 1 graf to CORRECT that
the 10 opposed, sted favored, the amendment and that they voted to override,
sted sustain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen House members _ including four
Republicans _ who had earlier opposed a measure to finance
abortions for poor women in the case of rape or incest sided
Wednesday with the pro-choice faction by voting to override
President Bush's veto.
   ``I've thought a lot about this,'' said Frank Pallone, D-N.J.,
saying he concluded it was a woman's decision whether to have an
abortion. ``I don't think I've been elected to come down here and
make those decisions for them.''
   But he was among the few who had a true change of heart on the
issue.
   Rep. William Natcher, D-Ky., who led debate for the Democrats,
is chairman of the subcommittee that produced the massive spending
bill for labor, health and education programs, which contains the
expanded Medicaid coverage for abortions.
   Natcher voted to override Bush's veto but said he is not in
favor of abortion.
   ``I have never voted for an amendment or a bill that legalized
abortion,'' said Natcher, who voted `no' Oct. 11 when the House
took a pro-choice turn by approving 216-206 the amendment to
include rape and incest as reasons a woman could get Medicaid to
pay for her abortion.
   ``I like George Bush. He's wrong this time,'' he said before
voting to override.
   An aide to Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., said her boss has always
been in favor of a woman's right to an abortion in the case of
rape, incest or to save the life of the mother.
   His problem with the amendment added Oct. 11 was with an
unrelated section relating to hypodermic needles for drug addicts.
   The needle language was modified by the time the bill got to the
president, so Gekas had no reason to want the bill vetoed, said his
press secretary, Joelle Ziemian.
   Rep. John Duncan, R-Tenn., voted to override the veto because he
supported the many programs, other than abortion, that would be
funded by the bill, said his spokesman.
   ``He did not see today's vote on a abortion, but for education
and (other) programs,'' said aide Jim Edwards.
   Rep. William Broomfield, R-Mich., who also opposed the Oct. 11
language known as the Boxer amendment, issued a statement after his
vote Wednesday to override the president's veto, saying:
   ``I just don't believe that anyone who is a victim of rape or
incest should be denied this right. If it is legal for someone who
can afford it, how can we make it illegal for a victim of rape or
incest who is poor?''
   The other 10 members who opposed the Boxer amendment but voted
to override Bush's veto were Reps. James Clarke, D-N.C.; George
Darden, D-Ga.; Sam Gibbons, D-Fla.; Lee Hamilton, D-Ind.; Matthew
McHugh, D-N.Y.; Charles Pashayan, R-Calif.; Carl Perkins, D-Ky.;
Nick Rahall, D-W.Va.; Bruce Vento, D-Minn.; and Jamie Whitten,
D-Miss.
   Meanwhile, three House members who had supported the Boxer
amendment sided with Bush's veto.
   Both Reps. Helen Bentley, R-Md., and Porter Goss, R-Fla., said
they supported a woman's right to an abortion in the cases of rape,
incest or to save her life, but are opposed to using federal funds
for the procedure.
   They both said that the amendment proposed by Rep. Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif., that they favored was on preference, not funding,
and that their vote to sustain the Bush veto was consistent with
their opposition to the use of federal money for abortions.
   Rep. Alfred McCandless, R-Ala., said his vote to sustain Bush's
veto had nothing to do with abortion. He said he opposes the level
of funding for the three agencies in the appropriations package,
and that he still believes, as demonstrated by his vote Oct. 11 in
favor of the Boxer amendment, that a woman has a right to a
federally funded abortion in cases of rape, incest or to save her
life.
</TEXT>
