<FIRST>r a AM-NBC-Israel-SAfrica     10-25 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NBC-Israel-SAfrica,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Helps South Africa Build Missile, Network Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African missile built with technology
provided by Israel made its first flight this summer from a South
African testing range, NBC News reported Wednesday.
   Citing unidentified intelligence sources and a CIA document, the
network said Jerusalem has been engaged in a partnership with
Pretoria to develop a nuclear missile capability for South Africa.
   NBC said Israel provides missile technology in return for a
continuous supply of enriched uranium for its own nuclear warheads,
and the use of a long-range test site.
   The network said the Overberg test range in South Africa and a
missile assembly building at the site were built for the use of
both countries, and that Israeli engineers have worked there for
several years.
   The CIA document said the first test resulting from the joint
project took place July 5 when a missile flew 900 miles southeast
from the test site to the Prince Edward Islands off South Africa,
NBC said.
   The document identified the South African state arms maker
Armscor as the builder of the missile, and said Israeli technology
was provided through Urdan Industries Ltd., based outside Tel Aviv,
NBC reported.
   The network said Israeli sources identified Gen. Chagay Regev, a
former senior aide to Israeli defense minister Yitzak Rabin, as
overseeing the project from Israel's embassy in Pretoria.
   NBC said that in response to its report, Rabin's office said it
would not comment on its missile program, and that South African
Foreign Minister Pik Botha also declined to comment.
</TEXT>
