<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Lebanon     10-25 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli-Backed Militia Expels 28 Lebanese From Security Zone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israel-backed militia expelled 28
Lebanese from Israel's security zone in southern Lebanon Wednesday
after three of their relatives defected from the militia to a rival
group, a spokesman said.
   The 28 family members, all from the Shiite Moslem village of
Ayta ech Chaab _ about a half-mile from the Israeli border _ were
ordered to leave the zone by the South Lebanon Army militia.
   Antoine Lahad, the ex-Lebanese army general who commands the
militia, issued the order after deciding the three militiamen, ages
18, 19, and 21, defected to the Shiite militia Amal, a spokesman at
Lahad's headquarters here said.
   The Syrian-backed Amal, which opposes Israeli control in
southern Lebanon, had claimed Monday it captured the three men
while they were supposedly hunting game.
   Lahad's militia is mainly made up of Christians, although it
includes some Shiites. It is a 2,500-man force that is trained,
equipped and paid by the Israeli military.
   Israel set up the security zone as a buffer to protect its
northern border when it pulled the bulk of its troops out of
southern Lebanon in 1985 after a three-year occupation.
   The zone is about 75 miles long and 2{ to 12 miles deep. It has
a population of about 200,000 Lebanese Christian, Druse and Moslems.
</TEXT>
