<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2249EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-Poland     10-25 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Poland,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Partisan Clash In Senate Over Aid To Poland And Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican and Democratic senators clashed
Wednesday on the magnitude of aid to non-communist governments in
Poland and Hungary with Democrats accusing President Bush of
committing ``billions for war but only small change for peace.''
   Republicans counterattacked, charging Democrats with attempting
to solve Poland's serious economic problems with a flood of
taxpayers' money which they said would only serve to bail out
``failed socialist dinosaurs.''
   ``We have to be very careful and pragmatic about what we propose
to do,'' said Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas. ``There
should not be a contest about how much money we can drag out of the
U.S. Treasury.''
   ``Some have complained that there are those in this body who are
doing this to embarrass the president of the United States; that is
simply wrong,'' said Sen. Joseph R. Biden, R-Del., who managed the
Democratic version of the bill on the Senate floor.
   ``What we are trying to do is to give shape to American
policy,'' Biden said. ``The only real issue is the level of
commitment.''
   Democrats said the Bush administration may lose a historic
opportunity to end the Cold War and encourage the spread of
democratic institutions and free enterprise throughout Eastern
Europe and ultimately in the Soviet Union itself.
   The debate comes after months of partisan squabbling about aid
levels for Eastern Europe which some say is on the verge of
peaceful change from communism to democracy.
   Under pressure to do more, Bush has little by little expanded
his aid proposal to its current level of $451 million over three
years.
   The House last week voted for an $840 million package of grants
and loans for the two countries. The Senate Foreign Relations
Committee had earlier urged adoption of a three-year $1.2 billion
aid plan.
   Senate Democrats now seek passage of a proposal sponsored by
Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., to authorize a total $989 million in
grants and loans over three years.
   The Simon bill includes $125 million in food aid, $200 million
in currency stabilization loans, $200 million in trade credit
insurance guarantees, $40 million in environmental aid, and $320
million for Poland and $80 million for Hungary to promote
development of private enterprise.
   Dole offered a substitute measure boosting the Bush proposal by
about $100 million to $585 million over the three-year period and
tying assistance to the development of a capitalist economy.
   Several Democrats used the debate to renew a drumbeat of
criticism against an administration they say is passively watching
from the sidelines as history takes a momentous turn.
   ``When asked for dramatic new steps, the administration takes a
wait and see attitude,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt. ``When
asked for a solid commitment of aid, it instead offers a few words
of encouragement.
   ``Why is this administration so willing to commit billions for
war but only small change for peace?'' Leahy asked.
</TEXT>
