<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2347EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-IndustrialExplosions     10-25 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Industrial Explosions,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion at Wyoming Plant Kills One, Injures 11; 1 Hurt in New Haven
Blast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plant Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion ripped through an Amoco Production Co. gas
processing plant near Evanston, Wyo., Wednesday afternoon, killing
one man and injuring 11 people, company officials said.
   The force of the blast hurled several workers out of the
building and toppled a wall, according to Amoco spokesman Dick
Brewster.
   Another explosion Wednesday at a chemical and insulation plant
in New Haven, Conn., left one man seriously burned and sent plumes
of black smoke billowing over the city, authorities said.
   Five workers from the Wyoming plant were airlifted to Salt Lake
City hospitals following the 1 p.m. explosion. Four of them were
taken to the University of Utah's Intermountain Burn Center, where
they were in serious condition with burns and lacerations, hospital
officials said.
   The fifth man was taken to LDS Hospital with multiple fractures,
said hospital spokesman Tim Madden.
   Otho ``O.J.'' Reed of Evanston died at Evanston Regional
Hospital after attempts to revive him failed, according to hospital
spokeswoman Joan Rosenthal. Two workers were admitted to Evanston,
and four others were treated and released.
   The blast occurred as workers tried to install a gas compressor
unit in a compressor building of Amoco's Anschutz Ranch East gas
processing plant about 15 miles south of Evanston, Brewster said.
   Company officials were unsure what sparked the explosion, but it
appears it was caused by a gas leak.
   The fire in the building was brought under control by Amoco
crews before local firefighters arrived, Brewster said.
   The New Haven explosion and fire at the Acme Division of the
Allied Products Corp. was quickly put out with dry chemicals stored
inside the plant, said Fire Chief John Riordan. He said the cause
of the fire was under investigation.
   The injured man came running out of the plant with his pants
still on fire and yelling, ``Help me,'' said a co-worker, David
VanWinkle.
   The employee rolled on the grass in a desperate attempt to put
out the flames before VanWinkle, 29, was able to put out the fire
with an extinguisher he grabbed inside the building, he said.
   The victim was in critical condition at Yale-New Haven Hospital
with burns.
   VanWinkle said he and the victim were responsible for baking
silicon-treated fiberglass.
</TEXT>
