<FIRST>r a AM-CourtroomOutburst     10-25 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Courtroom Outburst,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant in Rape-Murder Case Angrily Swears at Judge, Prosecutor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defendant in the rape and murder of a
pregnant doctor angrily swore at a prosecutor and judge Wednesday
in a courtroom outburst that ended with the accused killer
handcuffed and taken away.
   ``I'm leaving, man! I'm leaving, (expletive)! You in trouble!''
Steven Smith screamed as prosecutor James Kindler cross-examined a
defense psychiatrist who testified the suspect was too deranged to
be prosecuted.
   Several jurors stared in surprise at Smith, who was standing at
the defense table. The defendant then said softly: ``There's
nothing I can do about it, man. I'm telling you straight out.''
   The turmoil was sparked when Kindler asked Dr. Daniel Schwartz
if Smith could be faking insanity to receive lenient treatment.
   State Supreme Court Justice James Leff then cleared the jury
from the room and instructed Smith he would tolerate no further
outbursts _ which prompted another explosion from the defendant.
   ``Well what the (expletive) is that, judge? ... You want me to
stop it? I can't control it! Listen to me, man, I'm not normal,
man, at all, at all,'' said Smith. ``That's what got me into
trouble here now. ... I'm here to get help, brother.''
   Smith was then handcuffed and led from the courtroom. Leff
brought the jury back, and cross-examination of Schwartz continued.
   Smith, 23, is on trial for the rape and murder of Dr. Kathryn
Hinnant, 33, originally of Lake City, S.C., in her fourth-floor
office at Bellevue Hospital on Jan. 9. She was five months pregnant.
   Schwartz, chief of forensic psychiatry at Brooklyn's Kings
County Hospital, said Smith, who has been in and out of mental
hospitals for the past decade, appears to have a psychosis related
to schizophrenia.
   Defense lawyer Marvyn Kornberg admitted in opening remarks that
Smith committed the crimes charged, but he argued that his client
is insane and therefore not responsible for his actions.
</TEXT>
