<FIRST>u w AM-Army-Kwajalein 1stLd-Writethru   10-25 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Army-Kwajalein, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0809,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Releases Environmental Study of SDI Affect on Kwajalein Atoll</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to delete reference to island being uninhabited.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision will be made later this year on
plans to move forward with a number of Star Wars experiments at
Kwajalein Atoll in the Marshall Islands, the Army said on Wednesday.
   There are some 2,900 U.S. personnel at the Army's missile test
facility on the island.
   Army spokesman Lt. Col. Dick Bridges said the Army has concluded
an environmental impact statement on whether programs connected
with the Star Wars program _ formally known as the Strategic
Defense Initiative _ would have a significant environmental affect
on the atoll.
   The Army wants to provide ``test range facilities and support
services'' on the island, the Pentagon said in a statement.
   ``The proposed SDI tests at the U.S. Army Kwajalein Atoll
include the sensing and tracking of re-entry vehicles launched by
missiles from California and Hawaii,'' the statement said.
   Such a segment of the space-based anti-missile system envisions
rockets intercepting and destroying enemy missiles during the
middle and latter stages of their flight.
   In 1987, the Pentagon ordered an extensive environmental impact
statement, after a preliminary report found that the acceleration
of the Star Wars program would have no significant impact on any
U.S. facility, with the exception of Kwajalein.
   At that time, the Pentagon said, ``Potential impacts include the
possible degradation of water quality around the islands; the
possible degradation of the marine habitat ... and possible
socio-economic impacts as a result of population increases.''
   But after the latest study, Bridges said, the Army ``believes we
can minimize any adverse affects on the environment'' if it goes
through with its proposed actions on the atoll.
   The Army will not move forward with any action until a 30-day
period passes, during which opponents of the action may file
protests if they wish, Bridges said.
</TEXT>
