<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Watsonville     10-25 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Watsonville,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Department Pleads With Tent City Residents to Move</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tent cities that spread out in parks
and vacant lots after the deadly Oct. 17 earthquake are unhealthy
and dangerous, firefighters and health officials said Wednesday.
   ``Our plan is not to physically move people but to convince them
that their options are better at other places,'' Fire Chief Gary
Smith said at a news conference Wednesday in Callaghan Park, where
about 160 people have set up camp.
   Some of those living in the tent cities were driven from their
homes because of damage. But fright has kept many others outside
even if inspectors have certified them sound.
   Still others refuse to move to Red Cross shelters because
they've gathered belongings into the tents _ things like sofas and
televisions _ that aren't allowed into the shelters.
   But Smith said there is concern that tent dwellers who are
cooking on charcoal braziers could be taking them in the tents,
creating fire and health hazards.
   Central Coast College student Enrique Alvarado, one of the tent
encampment's organizers, said he would try to persuade people to
move but would let them decide for themselves.
   Many of the people living in the tent cities refuse to enter any
building because they feel unsafe, said Patricia Mendez, a county
employee.
   About 1,200 Watsonville residents were displaced by the quake
and aftershocks. The quake killed dozens of people, injured
thousands and caused more than $7.1 billion damage throughout
Northern California. Watsonville, a poor agricultural community
just a few miles from the epicenter, was especially hard it.
</TEXT>
