<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2333EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-EarthquakeHazards     10-25 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Earthquake Hazards,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves More Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate approved legislation Wednesday
night boosting by $20 million the federal effort to lessen the
hazards posed by earthquakes and to reduce the losses they cause.
   The legislation, sponsored by Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn., whose
own state lies across an earthquake fault, was adopted on voice
vote without debate. It now goes to the House.
   It increases the authorization for earthquake hazard programs
from the present $85 million to $105 million and expands the
mission of agencies responsible for increasing earthquake
preparedness.
   For example, the bill directs the preparation of model building
codes to make structures more resistant to quakes and expands
education and training programs.
   It also directs the U.S. Geological Survey to do further work on
the exact location of fault lines and to establish a center for the
international exchange of earthquake information.
   Of the additional $20 million authorization, $8 million would be
used for a study to determine why some buildings withstood last
week's earthquake in San Francisco while others did not. The
remaining $12 million would be used for earthquake preparedness.
   The actual $20 million is contained in the earthquake relief
provisions of the stopgap appropriations bill sent to President
Bush by the House earlier Wednesday. Under the rules of Congress,
every appropriation must be accompanied by an authorization bill
that sets a spending ceiling.
</TEXT>
