<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0746EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w PM-Byrd Adv26   10-25 1056</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Byrd, Adv26,1091</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thu PMs, Oct. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Byrd Flexes Senate Muscle in New Position</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a week of closed-door bargaining with
the White House, Democratic Sen. Robert C. Byrd stepped before
television cameras to announce a compromise adding $1.1 billion to
President Bush's anti-drug program.
   His Republican counterpart, Sen. Mark Hatfield of Oregon,
quickly cautioned that they still needed to make sure Senate
leaders would accept the deal.
   ``I don't have to,'' the courteous, white-haired Byrd informed
Hatfield quietly _ but not so quietly that reporters couldn't hear.
``He kinda left it up to me.''
   A year after he relinquished his powerful post as Senate
Majority Leader, much of what happens in the Senate still is up to
the 71-year-old sixth term Democrat from West Virginia.
   _When Byrd believed lobbyists were getting out of hand, the
Senate approved his bill restricting their activities. It may well
be the only ethics legislation enacted this year.
   _When Bush proposed a drug initiative Byrd considered
inadequate, Byrd used his post as Senate Appropriations chairman to
force negotiations with the White House on expanding the program
and give Democrats a legislative success on a high-profile bill.
   _As the Senate's senior Democrat, he also claimed the title of
president pro tempore, third in line to the presidency. It's been
mostly a ceremonial post until now, but Byrd is overseeing a near
doubling of its budget for staff and other support and
strengthening his influence in the process.
   _He has been unabashedly funneling federal dollars into his
poverty-stricken home state. The 1990 military construction bill
orders the Pentagon to accelerate spending on West Virginia
projects to $49 million this year _ more than 10 times what the
Defense Department proposed.
   Until Byrd stepped down after six years as majority leader, the
Senate's top official had never before given up the job and
remained in Congress.
   Byrd's decision reflected in part a dissatisfaction with his
old-school, formal and sometimes quirky approach to the job.
Procedure often seemed more important than policy.
   In the wake of another presidential loss, the Democrats also
wanted someone who could better counter the White House on
television.
   There was much speculation that Byrd would simply take care of
home-state concerns and attend to his cherished study of Senate
history.
   But that is not his way.
   ``Whatsoever thy hand findeth to do, do it with thy might,''
Byrd says, precisely quoting Ecclesiastes 9:10, the King James
Version. ``I have that sense of duty. I follow it meticulously.''
   ``I think he's been freed'' by giving up the role of party
leader, says Linda Peek, his former spokeswoman. ``Anybody who knew
him, knew that he wasn't going out to pasture,'' she said.
   Byrd was known for seemingly endless meetings as majority
leader, hoping to enlist as many Democrats as possible on any given
issue. He says he still tries to be fair, but, ``I don't have to
concern myself with developing a consensus.''
   Beyond his titles, Byrd's influence permeates the institution
he's called home since 1959.
   Many of the people he appointed when majority leader stayed
behind to oversee a broad swath of the machinery that operates the
Senate.
   In real estate alone, Byrd probably reigns over more of the
Senate wing of the Capitol than anyone else, with his two suites of
offices and support staff rooms. When Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, goes to work in the morning, it's in the Robert
C. Byrd Rooms.
   Both Byrd and Mitchell say there's no friction between them,
although others point to some instances.
   For example, on the Senate floor Mitchell looked up from some
work and asked Byrd if he needed a vote on one of his bills, a
motion the leader would make. Byrd politely told him he already did
it.
   Republicans note that Byrd's drug plan was developed almost
entirely within the appropriations committee, implying it was
foisted upon Mitchell. The two Democrats deny that too.
   Byrd brushes aside suggestions that personal clout is what gave
his drug plan priority over those of others who sought to take on
Bush on the politically popular topic. He just knows how to work
the system and line up support, he said.
   ``One could not be expected to walk into the Senate as a
freshman and do that kind of work,'' he said. ``There has to be
some knowledge of how this machine operates, and some experience in
dealing with other senators.
   ``And I've had ample experience,'' he says.
   Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., says what Byrd has done so far is
``just the tip of the iceberg.''
   ``I think now he has the time and the position to focus his
attention on creating legislation,'' he said. Byrd is a powerful
presence for his party, Sasser said, who ``by force of personality
is very intimidating to members on the other side of the aisle.''
   Away from the spotlight, Byrd has been using his position as
appropriations chairman to take care of the folks back home, as his
work on the military spending bill shows.
   He's also made clear that he will represent West Virginia
interests without any help from intermediaries. His anti-lobbying
bill was a reaction against the hiring of consultants by West
Virginia University to seek a government grant.
   But he's never far from the center of action.
   North Carolina Republican Jesse Helms, reacting to a federally
supported exhibit including homosexual photographs, was tying the
Senate into knots in his effort to prohibit spending by the federal
arts agencies on anything that might be considered offensive.
   But when Helms tried to get the Senate to pass an amendment
instructing Byrd's committee against compromising with the House,
Byrd put his foot down.
   ``I am not going to follow the instructions of this amendment or
any other amendment or resolution that might be introduced on this
subject,'' Byrd declared. The Senate then tabled, or killed, the
Helms amendment.
   A House-Senate compromise emerged, much watered down from what
Helms wanted, which would establish a panel to oversee federal arts
endowment policy.
   A third of that panel will be appointed by the president, a
third by the speaker of the House, and a third by the president pro
tempore of the Senate _ Robert C. Byrd.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu PMs Oct. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
