<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0454EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-Julia'sBack Adv01-1stAdd   10-25 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Julia's Back, Adv 01 - 1st Add,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday AMs, Nov. 1, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: to buy.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   And who but Julia Child could get away with explaining yeast
dough in terms of burps: ``The main ingredients of flour are starch
and gluten. It's the starch in the dough that feeds upon the yeast,
belching forth gas that pushes up the gluten.''
   Child nurtures you through bread-baking, explaining how yeast
works, what flour to buy, what kneading is all about. Photographs
make it clear just how the dough should look along the way.
   And how can anyone resist trying a souffle when she writes:
   ``The souffle is undoubtedly the egg at its most magnificent,
the egg in all its puffing power. How impressive is the chocolate
or cheese souffle, its head rising dramatically out of its dish,
and swaying ever so slightly as it is borne to the table.''
   In a bow to health, she includes ``cream'' soups made with
pureed rice. But she also suggests adding heavy or sour cream ``if
you like.'' She also offers a fat-free ``heaven-sent'' poached
chicken and recommends a cast-iron grill to cook meat without fat.
   But she writes: ``I, for one, would rather swoon over a few thin
slices of prime beefsteak, or one small serving of chocolate
mousee, or a sliver of foie gras than indulge to the full on such
nonentities as fat-free gelatin puddings.''
   Child grew up in Pasadena, Calif., in a home with a hired cook,
and did not take a cooking lesson until she was in her 30s.
   She graduated from Smith College in 1934 and after writing
advertising copy for a short time, joined the Office of Strategic
Services, the forerunner of the CIA. She was sent off as a clerk to
Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), where she met Paul Child, a career diplomat
10 years her senior, in 1943.
   They married in 1946 and remain very close; she often talks in
terms of ``we.'' He recently moved to a nursing home near their
Cambridge, Mass., home. They have no children.
   ``They just never came,'' she said matter-of-factly. ``I would
be very happy to be a grandmother at this point.'' But in addition
to her book, Child is busy these days working to improve the status
of food professionals through the American Institute of Wine and
Food, which she co-founded, and the James Beard Foundation in New
York.
   Two years after their marriage, the Childs were sent to Paris,
where she enrolled at the Cordon Bleu cooking school. She was
considered a bit odd by her friends, who all had hired help in the
kitchen.
   ``I'd been looking for my life's work all along. And when I got
into cooking I found it. I was inspired by the tremendous
seriousness with which they took it.''
   In France she also met Simone Beck and Louisette Bertholle, who
needed an American collaborator for the first volume of ``Mastering
the Art of French Cooking.'' Nine years in the making, it was
published in 1961 with a foreword that began: ``This is a book for
the servantless American cook who can be unconcerned on occasion
with budgets, waistlines, time schedules, children's meals, the
parent-chauffeur-den mother syndrome, or anything else which might
interfere with the enjoyment of producing something wonderful to
eat.''
   And it ends: ``Above all, have a good time.''
   Two years later, when Child was 51, WGBH in Boston launched
``The French Chef'' series, and for 206 meals, she entertained and
cajoled and encouraged viewers to do as she did.
   ``I happened to be the right woman at the right time,'' she said
with modesty, noting that John F. Kennedy had a French chef at the
White House and more Americans were traveling abroad.
   ``Suddenly people began considering food with a capital `F'.''
   Besides, she was fun to watch, perhaps partly because of the
on-air disasters, the first of which occurred with an apple
charlotte.
   ``As I was looking, it did a slow collapse. You could hear the
tears in my voice.'' To cover, she told viewers: ``You don't want
it too stiff.''
   But the mistakes taught viewers how to make repairs, and made
her more familiar.
   And since it's the good company that counts, her advice to
others who make mistakes: ``Don't apologize ever. It's very bad to
apologize because people will say, `That wasn't very good, was it?'
''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Nov. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
