<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Spain     10-25 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Spain,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Securities Commission To Fine Drexel Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Securities Commission has
decided to issue its largest-ever fine for fraud against the
defunct Spanish unit of the U.S. securities firm Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., a newspaper reported.
   Madrid's El Mundo daily said Tuesday the commission's directors
recently approved a 70-million-peseta, or $615,000, fine against
DBL Capital Markets Espana SA for ``very serious'' civil
infractions of trading rules.
   The paper said the commission must receive government approval
before issuing the fine, which at five times the illicit profits
earned represents the maximum penalty permitted under law.
   A spokesman for New York-based Drexel said: ``There's been no
official decision. It's still under consideration and obviously we
can't comment.''
   But sources said they believed the fine would be lower and that
a final decision was still some time away.
   Drexel, which recently pleaded guilty to unrelated fraud charges
in the United States and has pledged to toughen securities law
compliance, closed the 27-employee Spanish unit in July,
acknowledging ``improper behavior.''
   A Spanish commission probe confirmed that the Drexel unit
fraudulently made 400 applications for shares worth $59 million in
the April 20-May 6 partial privatization of the state-controled
Repsol S.A. oil firm, the paper said.
   The probe showed the Drexel unit used the names of private
citizens without their authorization to circumvent restrictions
designed to assure the widest distribution of shares, then sold the
acquired shares to 17 foreign institutional investors for a profit
of $123,000.
   The commission began its investigation in June after a private
individual said his bank had authorized the purchase of Repsol
shares without his knowledge.
   El Mundo said the U.S. parent company would be legally
responsible for paying the fine since the Spanish unit has been
liquidated.
   Drexel in September pleaded guilty to six U.S. felonies and
began paying $650 million in penalties to settle a range of
criminal securities fraud charges.
</TEXT>
