<DOCNO> AP891025-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0216EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GroundwaterContamination     10-25 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Groundwater Contamination,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Says USDA Failing to Warn About Groundwater Contamination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate Agriculture subcommittee chairman has
accused the Agriculture Department of not sufficiently warning
farmers about the dangers of fertilizers and pesticides to
groundwater.
   The department's Extension Service ``calculates that 46 percent
of U.S. counties contain groundwater susceptible to contamination
from pesticides and fertilizers,'' said Sen. Wyche Fowler, D-Ga.,
chairman of the subcommittee on conservation and forestry.
   He said Tuesday that wells are not systematically tested,
research is not keeping up with the problem and national data on
fertilizer and chemical damage to groundwater in each of the states
is not available.
   ``It should come as no surprise then, that farmers have poor
information on the consequences of the practices they employ _
beyond this year's yield,'' Fowler said.
   ``The U.S. Extension Service, which our farmers rely on for so
much of their information, has not taken adequate steps to educate
them about the possible consequences of polluting our water
supplies with pesticides and fertilizers,'' he said.
   Furthermore, he said, the extension service is not providing
much guidance to farmers about alternatives to chemical use.
   During a hearing on water quality, Fowler said he had recently
been informed that extension service agents were getting paid by
chemical companies to be consultants.
   Jay Vroom, of the National Agricultural Chemical Association,
said he had not heard of that happening, but said that the chemical
manufacturers have long relied on information from extension agents
and land grant universities.
   Terry Nipp, director of the water quality initiative at the
National Association of State Universities and Land Grant Colleges,
said it's widely known that fertilizer and pesticide dealers have a
great deal of influence with how farmers use chemicals.
   ``Yet there is no national program to certify, train or provide
educational materials to the dealers,'' Nipp said in testimony to
the Fowler's subcommittee.
   He said the extension services would like to do more, but don't
have the money or personnel.
   Fowler asked Nipp why extension agents were criticizing the
system known as low intensity sustainable agriculture, which relies
on organic procedures for increasing yields and controlling pests.
   ``Like all institutions, there is a certain amount of inertia,''
said Nipp. But he said there have been some ``fairly religious
conversions'' by extension agents to organic methods.
   Fowler said he called the hearing to help determine what kind of
regulations pertaining to groundwater should be in the 1990 farm
bill.
   ``We simply cannot continue to encourage farmers to maximize
program benefits at the expense of the environment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
