<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAL Bjt   10-25 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL, Bjt,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Stock Volatile; Pilots Haven't Given Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plunge, and then a late rally, in UAL Corp.
stock is keeping many eyes on the parent company of United
Airlines, despite its board's insistence that it is backing away
from an immediate sale.
   In Tuesday's trading on the New York Stock Exchange, UAL
finished down $8.37{ at $170 a share, rallying on late buying
interest after dropping more than $32 early in the day.
   The closing price represented just over half the $300 a share
originally offered by a buyout group that included UAL's management
and pilots.
   The United chapter of the Air Line Pilots Association said
Tuesday it was undaunted in its quest for an employee-owned airline.
   ALPA spokesman Hank Krakowski said the late rally in UAL's stock
price might be a sign of possible takeover interest from outside.
   ``We told our pilots tonight on the telephone hotline that we
know, from sources, that someone is accumulating UAL stock, but who
that is we do not know,'' Krakowski said.
   The company's board said late Monday the Chicago-based airline
would remain independent while directors examine alternatives to
the $6.75 billion offer that collapsed earlier this month.
   Pat Friend, a spokeswoman for the Association of Flight
Attendants, another union involved in the original buyout attempt,
said her union was not happy with the board's stand.
   ``We don't know what anyone's going to do at this point in
time,'' Friend said. ``All we're saying is that we believe the
board of directors have made a mistake because they have not taken
any action to protect the company from hostile takeovers.''
   Airline analyst Stephen Dexter with Kemper Financial Services
Inc. said the UAL board's statement gives the pilot-management
group breathing room to regroup and possibly come back with another
buyout proposal.
   ``All the messages here are, `Let's take a breather, stand back,
let management run the company.' It's a holding pattern until a
firm bid hits the table,'' Dexter said.
   Krakowski said the pilots continued to work behind the scenes in
an attempt to put together another package.
   ``The players, the pilots, their financial advisers ... haven't
packed up their bags and gone home by any means,'' he said. ``We'll
just regroup and see what we can do in the future.''
   Robert Decker, an airline analyst with the Chicago investment
firm Duff &amp; Phelps Inc., said the decline in UAL's stock is
``making any potential bid cheaper all the time. It's just a
reaction to the board's decision to do nothing.''
   And the more the stock price falls, the more attractive UAL is
to hostile raiders, Decker said.
   Stock prices declined broadly in heavy trading early Tuesday, in
part due to concerns about UAL, though there was some recovery
after noon. The pilot-management group's announcement Oct. 13 that
it was unable to obtain financing for its bid helped trigger a
190.58-point drop in the Dow Jones industrial average and launched
the downward slide for UAL.
   The widely followed market index finished down 3.69 Tuesday at
2,659.22 after a day of volatile movement.
   In addition to the inability to raise financing, the buyout
suffered another major setback last week when British Airways PLC _
which was to contribute $750 million in equity in exchange for a 15
percent stake in UAL _ pulled out of the buyout group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
