<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   10-25 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car and Truck Sales Slump</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculation that the hot pace of car and truck
sales in late summer would cool is coming true, with automakers
reporting a 20.5 percent drop in vehicle sales in mid-October
compared with the same period last year.
   Part of the analysts' predictions of weak sales in October came
from consumers' fear of price increases for 1990-model cars, which
were introduced this month, and attractive buyer incentives in
August and September.
   The combination apparently proved too much to resist for some
consumers who had planned to buy cars this fall. Car sales reported
Tuesday by the Big Three automakers fell more than 20 percent each,
with light truck sales not far behind.
   The eight major automakers with U.S. plants said they sold
vehicles at an average daily rate of 28,156 during Oct. 11-20,
compared with a rate of 35,407 during the same time last year.
Overall car sales were off 19 percent while truck sales were down
22.8 percent.
   As the 1990 model year opened, automakers announced price
increases they blamed mostly on federal safety requirements,
including driver-side air bags or automatic safety belts.
   General Motors Corp. announced a 3.4 percent average price
increase for its 1990 model cars, Ford Motor Co.'s prices rose an
average of 4.9 percent and Chrysler Corp.'s went up 5 percent on
average.
   The manufacturers also carried over cash rebates or low-interest
financing packages to some 1990 cars and trucks, but they didn't
match the level of incentives on 1989 models.
   Some dealers still have 1989 cars and trucks in stock, but the
majority sold now are 1990 models.
   The mid-October sales decline, when tacked on to the 11.9
percent drop in early-October sales figures, worked out to a 16.5
percent decline in vehicle sales during the first 20 days of the
month compared with the same period last year.
   ``We borrowed some business from October, November and
December,'' said Herb Adcox, owner of Herb Adcox Chevrolet in
Chattanooga, Tenn., and the incoming treasurer of the National
Automobile Dealers Association. ``That usually happens when you
have a strong close (to the model year) like this.''
   In September, car and light truck sales by the eight companies
were up 8.2 percent over the same month last year. In August,
vehicle sales were up 13.1 percent compared with August 1988.
   So far this calendar year, car and truck sales are running 2
percent behind the last year's pace, the second-best on record. Car
sales are down 3 percent and light-truck sales were down 0.2
percent.
   GM reported its car sales were down 24.8 percent during
mid-October compared with last year, while GM's light truck sales
were off 26 percent. For the year-to-date, GM's car sales were down
6.8 percent while truck sales were up 1.4 percent.
   Ford said its mid-October car sales ran 21.2 percent behind last
year and truck sales were down 24.2 percent. For the year, Ford's
car sales were 0.6 percent behind last year and truck sales were
down 2.7 percent.
   Mid-October car sales at Chrysler were down 23.7 percent and
truck sales were off 17.5 percent. Since the first of the year,
Chrysler's car sales were 11.5 percent behind last year and truck
sales were down 0.4 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
