<FIRST>r f PM-Ford-Jaguar Bjt   10-25 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford-Jaguar, Bjt,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Files Notification That It May Go After All of Jaguar</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Lin'' in 4th graf cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. says it's ready, more than a year
early, to bid for all of Jaguar PLC's outstanding stock, but that
it may not go after the British luxury carmaker when the time comes.
   Ford apparently will have to wait until the end of next year
before it could move to acquire more than 15 percent of the company
because of an ownership roadblock written into Jaguar's bylaws.
   A suitor can acquire more than 15 percent of the stock before
then, but it must be approved by Jaguar's board of directors. And
that seems unlikely in Ford's case.
   The notification by Ford on Monday to the Securities and
Exchange Commission that it was prepared to bid for all of the
stock stemmed from an SEC requirement, said Ford spokeswoman Lin
Cummins.
   ``It is a legal requirement by the SEC that once you became a 5
percent stockholder in the company, you have to disclose your
intentions concerning the issuer, which is Jaguar,'' she said.
``It's not saying that we are going after it.''
   Ford and General Motors Corp. have made separate moves to
acquire chunks of Jaguar _ Ford through stock purchases that Jaguar
has called unwelcome and GM through friendly negotiations with
company.
   GM and Ford, the nation's Nos. 1 and 2 automakers respectively,
apparently want a luxury automobile to add to their stables, and
Jaguar, which has fallen on tough financial times, seems to fit the
bill.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Ford stock fell 75 cents a share
to close at $49.125 Tuesday, and Jaguar's American depositary
receipts rose 12.5 cents to close at $11.25 in over-the-counter
trading.
   On Tuesday, Ford reported a 22.4 percent decline in sales of its
cars and light trucks during mid-October compared with the same
time last year. Jaguar, like other overseas automakers, won't
report U.S. sales until the first of next month.
   Because of Jaguar bylaws, no outside individual or company may
acquire more than 15 percent of its stock before Dec. 31, 1990,
without a vote by Jaguar's board of directors. After that date,
there are no provisions in place that would thwart a hostile
takeover through stock purchases.
   Jaguar has said it wants to remain independent.
   Ford announced Sept. 19 that it planned to acquire 15 percent of
Jaguar's stock, and received U.S. regulatory approval for the
purchase. By Monday, Jaguar said Ford had accumulated 21.9 million
shares, or about 12 percent, of the company's outstanding stock.
   A Ford move to acquire all of Jaguar's stock may be dealt a blow
sooner than the end of next year.
   Jaguar Chairman John Egan has said he hopes to make an
announcement to shareholders within a month about the matter,
spokesman Tom McDonnell of Jaguar's U.S. subsidiary said Tuesday.
   It is possible that such an announcement would involve GM, which
reportedly has been negotiating to buy up to 30 percent of Jaguar
stock within the next few years.
   ``We are continuing in our discussions with Jaguar regarding
several possible business arrangements, including manufacturing,
marketing and other activities,'' GM spokesman Ron Theis said
Tuesday. He said Egan said last week the discussions included a
product for the European market.
   ``We have declined to get any more specific than that,'' Theis
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
