<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-25 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mostly lower in early European
trading today. Gold prices rose.
   Trading was quiet, and foreign currency dealers said the market
was waiting to hear what U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan would say about monetary policy in testimony before the
U.S. House banking subcommittee later in the day.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.55 yen to a closing 141.55 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 141.60 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday's
prices, included: 1.8374 West German marks, down from 1.8390;
1.6121 Swiss francs, up from 1.6120; 6.2415 French francs, down
from 6.2475; 2.0723 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0860; 1,347.75
Italian lire, down from 1,349.00; 1.1712 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1723.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6080 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6065 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $368.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $367.75. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $368.35.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $368.30 compared with $367.50 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.72 to close at a bid $386.63.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.14 a troy
ounce, up from Tuesday's $5.12.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
