<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0726EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-25 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Down In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost ground against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo today and stock prices fell in afternoon trading, erasing
earlier gains.
   The dollar finished trading at 141.55 yen, down 0.55 yen from
Tuesday's close of 142.10 yen. After opening at 141.57 yen, it
stayed in a narrow range between 141.40 and 141.79 yen.
   ``Recently the U.S. currency hasn't been falling much in Tokyo
because Japanese investors still have large dollar demands,'' said
Yuji Nakao, a trader with Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   But he said traders in other countries had become less
interested in the dollar because of recent declines in U.S.
interest rates.
   Lower interest rates in a country tend to make its currency less
attractive to investors.
   Japanese participants also were concerned about recent losses on
the New York Stock Exchange following its big plunge two weeks ago,
he said.
   On the stock market, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed
84.15 points, or 0.24 percent, ending the day's trading at
35,442.40. The index, which lost 58.97 points the previous day,
gained 71.90 points in the morning, but fell back in afternoon
trading.
   The index started falling as investors began selling issues to
take profits from the morning gains, dealers said.
   ``Many participants also stepped off to the sidelines to wait to
see the performance of the New York market tonight,'' said Kazuhiro
Nomura, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co. Ltd.
   The New York Stock Exchange's Dow Jones industrial average of 30
major issues lost about 80 points on Tuesday, its largest tumble
since Oct. 13, when it fell more than 190 points.
   Nomura said arbitrage deals by some participants to make profits
from price gaps between the spot and futures markets also helped
cause the Nikkei's afternoon fall.
   But he said there were no negative economic elements in the
Tokyo market discouraging participants.
</TEXT>
