<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0757EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Saturn-LaFauve     10-25 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Saturn-LaFauve,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oversupply of New Cars Won't Affect Saturn, Company President Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A projected glut of new cars over the
next two years won't affect production plans at General Motors
Corp.'s Saturn plant because the compact model will attract buyers
of imports, Saturn's president said.
   ``We're not after people who are already driving Chevrolets.
We're after the import buyers,'' R.G. ``Skip'' LaFauve said Tuesday.
   LaFauve refused to provide production figures for the new car,
but said its design had been refined and it will compete directly
against the Toyota Corolla.
   LaFauve and Richard Hoalcraft, international representative for
the United Auto Workers, participated in the state Department of
Labor's second annual Labor-Management Conference here Tuesdy.
   They spent much of their time talking about the company's
relationship with its workers. The Saturn plant, which is scheduled
to begin production next summer, will operate under an innovative
labor-management agreement.
   The new approach includes union participation in much of the
decision-making involved in plant operations, LaFauve said. Union
members participated in decisions on equipment design, suppliers,
and even the selection of Saturn's advertising agency.
   At full capacity, about 3,000 people will work at the plant,
under construction in Spring Hill, about 40 miles southwest of
Nashville.
   Hoalcraft said the labor-management arrangement is
``participatory membership where I look out for your stakes and
equity as a member of the union and you look out for my stakes and
equity.''
   ``We have geared ourselves to do what's right for the business _
none of this wrangling,'' Hoalcraft said.
</TEXT>
