<DOCNO> AP891025-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0800EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Mercedes     10-25 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mercedes,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two New Roadsters Introduced by Mercedes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROSSE POINTE SHORES, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of new two-seat
roadsters and a new four-wheel-drive sedan and station wagon will
lead Mercedes-Benz's fight to hold its share of the growing luxury
car market, a company executive says.
   Eric Krampe, president and chief executive officer of
Mercedes-Benz of North America Inc., said Tuesday he expected the
luxury market to grow to about 840,000 cars next year, about 10,000
more than 1989 sales.
   Krampe also said he expected the company to keep or slightly
increase its 75,000-car-a-year sales pace of 1989. The four cars
that the West German automaker introduced will lead a list of 17
models into the next decade.
   The 300SL, with a base price of $73,500, and the 500SL, which
costs $10,000 more, replace the Mercedes 560SL, a roadster the West
German automaker had been producing for 18 years.
   Mercedes also is selling a sedan and a station wagon, carrying
300E and 300TE designations respectively, with automatically
engaging four-wheel-drive, a first for the company.
   Some of the competition Mercedes will face in 1990 will come
from Japan.
   Toyota Motor Corp. last month began selling its Lexus luxury
cars and next month, Nissan Motor Corp. will begin selling its
Infiniti line.
   ``They will try to take customers from the United States
(automakers) as well as Europeans,'' Krampe said. ``What the effect
will be still has to be seen. There is no clear picture yet.
   ``We do view them with a lot of respect,'' he said. ``We believe
they will be worthy competitors.''
   The median price for a Mercedes in 1989 was about $45,000,
Krampe said, slightly above the $40,000 price for the
top-of-the-line Lexus or Infiniti model. Krampe doubted speculation
that the Japanese companies were keeping their prices low in order
to grab larger shares of the U.S. luxury-car market.
   ``They are certainly out with an interesting price,'' he said.
``I think it would be very disrespectful to say they buy market
share. I'm not happy that they're around at these prices, but I
understand why.''
   Krampe said he expected the two new SL models to account for
about 8,000 in sales apiece and the four-wheel-drive cars, called
4Matic, will account for about 1,000 in sales each.
   The four-wheel-drive system is a complex series of sensors that
automatically add front-wheel-drive to existing rear-wheel-drive
when certain limits of wheel spin, engine speed and other factors
are passed. Drivers have to do nothing for the system to engage or
disengage.
   Next year, Mercedes plans to introduce two new turbodiesel cars,
which should amount to about 4,000 in sales in 1990. Krampe
acknowledged reports that the new turbodiesels do not meet
stringent California air quality standards, meaning that the state
with some of the company's largest markets will be off limits for
the diesel cars.
   The rest of the country, he said, accounts for 75 percent of
Mercedes sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
