<DOCNO> AP891025-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 0858EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-USTradeReaction     10-25 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-US Trade Reaction,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Officials Oppose U.S. Proposals for Free Farm Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's minister of agriculture, forestry and
fisheries on Wednesday opposed new U.S. proposals for the
liberalization of farm trade, saying they were impractical.
   Michihiko Kano told a Parliament committee, ``We believe there
are some problems in the realization of the U.S. proposals from a
standpoint of the world agricultural situation and the position in
which Japanese farmers are being placed,'' a parliamentary official
said.
   ``Japan will maintain its current stand,'' particularly its
policy of self-sufficiency in rice, the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, quoted Kano as saying.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills and Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter announced in Washington Tuesday a four-point
package calling for all farm trade import barriers to be turned
into tariffs and gradually reduced over 10 years, and for the
abolishment of all export subsidies in five years.
   Under the proposals, to be submitted Wednesday to international
farm trade liberalization talks in Geneva, Japan would be able to
protect its rice production with a high tariff at first, but would
have to gradually lower it to nearly zero in 10 years.
   Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu told the parliamentary committee
the government would continue to implement a policy of
self-sufficiency on rice.
   Japanese officials maintain that rice, as a staple food, should
be protected, and that Japan should continue its policy for
security reasons.
   The Japanese government regulates the domestic rice market,
buying much of the rice produced by Japanese farmers and reselling
it to consumers at lower prices, which are still several times the
world market level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
