<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1038EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Markets-Congress 2ndLd-Writethru   10-25 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Congress, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>New SEC Head Tells Congress About Market Movements</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to include that remarks were prepared.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new head of the Securities and Exchange
Commission told a congressional panel today the handling of Wall
Street's 190 point plunge on Oct. 13 shows ``the value of the
market improvements adopted during the past two years.''
   SEC Chairman Richard C. Breeden, who noted ``I was sworn into
office just two weeks ago today,'' was the star witness before a
House panel on market reform, his first public appearance since
taking office.
   It also was Breeden's first public questioning since the Dow
Jones industrial average plunged 190.58 points on Oct. 13.
   The Dow Jones average, a key market indicator, rebounded to
close up 88.12 points the following Monday. After a week of gentler
fluctuations, it seesawed again Tuesday, finishing the day with a
slight decline of 3.69 points at 2,659.22.
   ``We learned important lessons from the market turbulence of
Oct. 13 and Oct. 16 and the market's responses to it,'' Breeden
said in testimony prepared for the House Energy and Commerce
Committee's telecommunications and finance subcommittee.
   ``The volume surges and volatility experienced on those two days
exemplify fundamental changes in our markets; they were not
isolated instances. We should not panic in the face of these
events, however. For what was demonstrated on Oct. 13 and 16 was
the strength and resiliency of the nation's markets.''
   He noted that more shares were traded in one hour during the
Oct. 13 slide ``than were traded on the average full day in 1985''
and three times the market's average daily volume 10 years ago.
   Breeden also said communication among the financial markets was
excellent and circuit-breakers, temporary trading halts in options
to slow market volatility also worked well.
   Legislation is pending in both the Senate and the House that
would expand the SEC's powers to monitor the markets in several
ways, some of them opposed by various segments of the industry and
one _ giving the SEC the power to halt trading in emergencies _
opposed by Breeden himself.
   The other proposed changes include giving the SEC authority to
request reports on large securities and options trades. This power
would enhance the SEC's surveillence abilities to track who's
trading what to whom. Another would require rules for assessing the
financial soundness of holding companies that are the parent
companies of broker-dealers.
   The other witnesses slated to testify are: Edward I. O'Brien,
president of the Securities Industry Association, a trade
association representing 600 securities firms; and George S.
Bissell, chairman of the Boston-based Keystone Group of mutual
funds.
   The market reforms proposed by Congress include giving the SEC
chairman the authority to halt trading for up to 24 hours in
emergenies. Currently, only the president can order such a shutdown.
   But Breeden has said he does not want that power and does not
think it should be exercised.
   In written answers to Senate staffers' questions during
confirmation hearings for the SEC post, Breeden said such authority
would create too much uncertainty about when the markets would
close and for how long.
   ``In a crisis, this uncertainty and the related rumors
concerning its likelihood could have seriously adverse
consequences,'' he wrote last month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891025-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1041EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Markets 1stLd-Wriethru f0001 10-25 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets, 1st Ld-Wriethru, f0001,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall Street Takes Another Roller-Coaster Ride; Other Markets React</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with six grafs to UPDATE with today's activities. Picks
up 6th graf pvs, In other ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street took on a calmer tone today
following Tuesday's roller-coaster ride in which stock prices swung
wildly, depressing the dollar and boosting demand for U.S. Treasury
bonds.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off 6.35 to 2,652.87
in the first half hour of trading today. But in the broader market,
rising stocks held a small edge over losers.
   The Dow average plummeted as much as 85 points on Tuesday before
rebounding and closing down 3.69 points at 2,659.22.
   Analysts said the tone for Tuesday's market gyrations was set by
two factors: speculation that a collapsed deal to buy United
Airlines parent UAL Corp. signaled a continued ebbing of the
takeover tide, and concern that a slowing economy would lead to
weaker corporate profits.
   On Wall Street, program trading strategies involving millions of
shares of stock helped accentuate wild declines and rebounds in
stock prices, some analysts said.
   ``It was almost all computerized program trading that gave us
tremendous violent price swings,'' said Dennis E. Jarrett, a
technical analyst for Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. ``I don't think you
could put your finger on any underlying economic statistic.''
   In other financial markets Tuesday, the dollar ended lower
against most major currencies, moving in tandem with the stock
market and reflecting concern from foreign investors about the
shakiness of the U.S. financial markets.
   But U.S. Treasury bonds posted moderate gains, with the
bellwether 30-year bond up { point, or $5 per $1,000 face amount.
Treasury bonds, which are guaranteed by the government, are
considered a safe haven at times of financial instability.
   Stock market observers initially attributed the downturn to the
decision late Monday by UAL to forego an employee-management buyout
for the time being, and a surge Tuesday in computerized program
selling involving stock-index futures.
   In such program selling, traders using sophisticated computer
programs take advantage of minute price discrepancies between
stock-index futures and the actual stocks on which the futures
contracts are based.
   The UAL buyout group's Oct. 13 announcement that it couldn't
raise financing for its $6.75 billion bid, and program selling that
followed, were considered key factors in the Dow's 190-point plunge
that day. Stocks regained much of their losses last week, however.
   ``It's certainly reminiscent of Friday the 13th ... although
it's not a replay,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer
for First Albany Corp. in Albany.
   Analysts said program trades dominated Tuesday's buying and
selling.
   ``I didn't see a lot of individuals, or even institutions,
participating,'' said Johnson. ``By and large they seemed to be
fence sitting.''
   Gene Jay Seagle, vice president and director of technical
research at Gruntal Financial Inc., said program trading was
accelerating the current bearishness apparent in the stock market.
   ``What we have here is an intermediate correction in an
otherwise bull market,'' he said. ``(But) we've just seen it happen
in a matter of days instead of weeks as we normally do.
   ``We're getting compressed moves both on the upside and the
downside ... due to program trading.''
   Johnson said the fixation on the collapse of the UAL buyout
represented concerns about the future of leveraged buyouts.
   ``It's not the final nail in the coffin of leveraged buyouts or
acquisitions, but it's pretty darn close to it,'' he said. ``The
LBO business had been the principal drive of the stock market for
most of 1988 and 1989.''
   Analysts also pinned the blame on the lower stock prices on
weakness in the economy and its effects on corporate profits. Those
concerns were magnified by a government report Tuesday showing that
orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods declined 0.1 percent during
September.
   ``The economy's heartbeat is not very strong and that isn't good
news for stocks,'' said A.C. Moore, director of research at Argus
Research in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
