<DOCNO> AP891025-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Greenspan-Fed 2ndLd-Writethru   10-25 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greenspan-Fed, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenspan Opposes Congressional Effort for More Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs, editing to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
today he opposes a bill that would subject the central bank to more
supervision from Congress and the administration.
   However, congressional supporters of the measure said it was
needed to make the secretive central bank more accountable for its
actions, which can have enormous impact on the $5 trillion U.S.
economy.
   ``The Federal Reserve must take actions that, while sometimes
unpopular in the short run, are in the long-run best interests of
the country,'' Greenspan said, adding that ``the independence of
the Federal Reserve has, in practice, served the country well.''
   Greenspan was the lead-off witness as a House Banking
subcommittee opened hearings to examine how the central bank and
its chairman, often called the second most powerful man in America,
reach decisions on setting interest rates.
   Greenspan said the Fed was opposed to a bill sponsored by Reps.
Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., and Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., which would require
Fed officials to meet at specified times with the administration
and release immediately results of its closed-door deliberations.
   While rejecting these proposals, Greenspan did endorse another
measure sponsored by Rep. Stephen Neal, D-N.C., that would write
into law that the Fed's chief mission is to eliminate inflation and
establish a deadline of 1994 for having done so.
   Greenspan said, however, that wringing inflation out of the
economy over the next five years would have short-tem costs in
terms of slower growth.
   The Hamilton-Dorgan proposal also calls for the Fed's budget,
which currently is not reviewed by either Congress or the
administration, to be subject to review and would require that the
Fed's books be audited each year by congressional auditors. It also
would make the chairman's term start one year after the start of a
presidential term.
   Greenspan said all those changes would compromise the political
independence of the Fed, which he said was essential to the central
bank's main role of fighting inflation.
   In arguing for his proposal, Hamilton said, ``The purpose of our
bill is to increase the accountability of the Federal Reserve to
the American people by making the workings of the Fed more open and
by establishing a formal channel of communications between
policymakers.''
   The Hamilton-Dorgan measure originally called for the secretary
of the Treasury to be added to the Fed's key policy-making body,
the Federal Open Market Committee.
   That panel, composed of members of the Federal Reserve Board and
presidents of the Fed's regional banks, meets secretly eight times
a year to set interest rate policies. Decisions aren't made public
for six weeks after a meeting, and even then only abbreviated
minutes of the closed-door sessions are made available.
   The revised Hamilton-Dorgan bill drops the effort to put the
Treasury secretary on the Fed's policy board and instead calls for
the Fed panel to meet twice each year with the Treasury secretary
and other top administration officials. It also calls for the
immediate release of the minutes of the meeting.
   Neal's measure does not include any penalties if the Fed fails
to meet the five-year deadline for eliminating inflation.
   Consumer prices have been rising at an annual rate of 4.4
percent through the first nine months of this year.
   Current law directs the Fed to ``promote effectively the goals
of maximum employment, stable prices and moderate long-term
interest rates'' but says nothing about the trade-offs between
these sometimes-conflicting goals.
   ``The law as it is presently written is so broad that the Fed
can do anything and say that they are following the law,'' Neal
said in arguing for his proposal.
   Neal's original legislation was much more specific in calling on
the Fed to reduce by 1 percent a year until it had reached zero
inflation.
   His new version, revamped to meet Greenspan's objections, simply
calls for the elimination of inflation in five years and
paraphrases language Greenspan has used to say that ``inflation
will be deemed to be eliminated when the expected rate of change of
the general level of prices ceases to be a factor in individual and
business decisions making.''
   Even the revised bills are given little chance of passing
Congress, especially in light of objections from key members of the
Senate Banking Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891025-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1118EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Soviet-Ruble 1stLd-Writethru   10-25 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Ruble, 1st Ld-Writethru,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Announce Big Decrease in Ruble's Value For Travel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with details of devaluation. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Bank announced today that it was
dramatically devaluing the ruble for people and businesses needing
convertible currency to travel abroad.
   The new rate of 6.26 rubles to the dollar is a tacit admission
that the ruble is not worth anything near the existing official
rate of .6277 per dollar.
   It means that Soviet travelers, instead of receiving $1.59 per
ruble, will instead get about 16 cents.
   The announcement, reported by the official Tass news agency,
indicated the standard rate will remain in effect for most
transactions, such as for foreign firms doing business in the
Soviet Union and for most international trade with the West.
   ``The special rate will be used by banking institutions in the
U.S.S.R. when selling hard currencies ... to citizens traveling
abroad on personal matters and when purchasing such currencies,''
Tass said.
   ``It will also be used when selling hard currencies ... to
state, cooperative and other public and other enterprises for
business trips of their workers abroad.''
   One Western diplomatic analyst, speaking on condition he not be
identified, said the announcement could mark ``an initial step
toward eventual convertibility of the ruble'' on international
currency exchanges. But the source called it too small a step to
have any obvious effect on the Soviet Union's foreign trade status.
   Because the ruble cannot be freely exchanged for dollars, yen,
marks and other hard currencies, it has virtually no value outside
the Soviet Union.
   Soviet citizens have long been allowed to exchange just 200
rubles for travel abroad. Tens of thousands of Soviets making trips
to the West thus trade rubles for dollars on the black market and
smuggle cash out of the country.
   A tremendous increase in the number of Soviets being permitted
to travel abroad under the more open climate created by President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms has been blamed by Western observers
for a sharp decline in the black-market value of the ruble.
   A spokesman for the Council of Ministers, which approved the
measure, characterized the change as an attempt to attract more
foreign tourists, curb the black market and encourage Soviet
citizens with hard-currency bank accounts to exchange them for
rubles, thus increasing the state bank's hard-currency reserves.
   The announcement did not indicate foreign tourists would be
allowed to buy rubles at the new rate, so it was not clear how the
move could affect foreign tourism.
   The spokesman, Valery Ovcharenko of the Council of Ministers
press office, told The Associated Press the new rule would take
effect Nov. 1.
   The new rate, if accompanied by a lifting of the limit on
official exchanges, would give Soviet travelers a more attractive,
legal alternative than the black market for buying hard currency.
   The growing disparity between the official rate and black-market
rates tends to feed anxieties about the nation's tenuous economic
condition.
   Tass gave no explanation for the devaluation, and Igor
Kozlovsky, deputy chief of the joint currency economics department
of the Finance Ministry, refused to give more details on the
decision. He would say only that it had been approved by the
Council of Ministers.
   The Council of Foreign Ministers in December ordered up a plan
for partial convertibility of the ruble, beginning with a 50
percent devaluation on Jan. 1, 1990.
   Making the ruble convertible would destroy the Soviet pricing
system, under which industrial goods and raw materials are cheap
and consumer goods are expensive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
