<DOCNO> AP891025-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Prechter Adv29   10-25 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Prechter, Adv 29,0896</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Oct. 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>Detroit's Convertible King, a Transplanted Michigander from Bavaria</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a 22-year-old exchange student, Heinz Prechter
decided to stay in the United States to pursue an auto sunroof
business.
   His decision grew into the ASC Inc. car conversion empire, and
at age 47, Prechter is spending weeks at a time at a new ASC
facility, back in his native West Germany.
   The man who left boyhood in rural Bavaria to chase the American
dream now has a foothold for expansion in the European Economic
Community of 1992 and beyond.
   ``We are a company with truly worldwide activities. For a small
company like ours, that's unusual,'' he said.
   Prechter, who became a naturalized U.S. citizen in 1972, has
built a reputation in Detroit economic development circles and a
role in Republican politics that includes advising the president on
international competitiveness.
   He said he realized early that stability for ASC would depend on
international marketing, in Japan and in Europe. A recession in
Detroit earlier this decade punctuated the lesson.
   Between jet trips to West Germany, Prechter recently led a
visitor through a chrome-decorated studio at ASC's Southgate
headquarters.
   Getting his hands on the cars still makes him smile, and he
showed how the convertible top drops into concealment on a gold
special-edition Ford Mustang.
   Also gleaming under the lights were Audi, Porsche, Acura, Toyota
convertibles made by ASC, and a bright yellow soft-top Jeep.
   Raised in rural postwar West Germany, ``I grew up as a farm boy
and of course there were no cars,'' Prechter said.
   He left home at 13 to work as an apprentice in his uncle's auto
coach-building shop in Nuremburg, attending high school at night.
He went on to engineering school, and traveled to the United States
in 1963 to attend San Francisco State University as an exchange
student in engineering.
   In 1965, he quit school but decided to stay in the United
States. He moved to Los Angeles and opened American Sunroof Co.
with $750 worth of tools in a two-car garage rented from custom car
designer George Barris.
   Prechter began selling hand-cut, hand-formed metal sunroofs, new
to the United States at the time. A visiting Ford Motor Co.
executive asked him to do prototype work for Ford, and Prechter
soon moved his business to Michigan.
   ASC Inc. now has about 30 facilities and employs about 3,000
people crafting special editions, convertibles and prototypes for
the Big Three U.S. carmakers and overseas makers including Toyota,
Porsche and Saab.
   The newest plant, in Heilbrun, West Germany, does the
convertible conversion of the Porsche 944 Cabriolet. Prechter also
owns an interest in Karosserie Werke in Weinsberg, which does
advanced bodywork for makers such as BMW, Porsche, Ford,
Volkswagen, Opel and Fiat.
   In the industrial area south of Detroit, Prechter is dubbed the
``Duke of Downriver'' because of his holdings.
   He owns Heritage Network Inc., including a chain of 16 suburban
newspapers; the Heritage Development Corp. real estate company; the
Presidential Inn near the ASC complex in Southgate; and the
Portside Inn restaurant in Wyandotte. He owns a 5 percent interest
in Security Bancorp Inc. He doesn't reveal figures on his privately
held enterprises.
   Prechter said he allocates one-fourth of his time for community
and political affairs. He is chairman of the Downriver Metroplex
Alliance, a business and community leaders' group.
   He is active in Detroit economic development groups as well. He
was one of about a dozen investors who saved Detroit's London Chop
House from closing by purchasing the culinary landmark in January.
   Prechter is a busy Republican fund-raiser. He was active in
fund-raising events that brought in nearly a million dollars for
President Bush's campaign.
   ``It's now day one after the election and I'm dead tired,''
begins a handwritten note of thanks from Bush that Prechter keeps
on his desk.
   ``He was very active in raising money for the president and for
the state party, in 1988 in particular,'' Michigan Republican Party
Chairman Spencer Abraham said. ``He's clearly somebody who has a
real, honest, philosophical commitment to the political process.''
   His opinion appears to matter, though he has no interest in
seeking office himself. The Prechters attended a White House state
dinner for the visiting prime minister of Australia, and Prechter
was seated next to Secretary of State James Baker III.
   ``My vision always was to make a difference in what I do,'' he
said. ``I first and foremost want to be a businessman.''
   That means pursuing international ties he began establishing in
1971, when few courted Asian business.
   Now he tries to unravel European import restrictions and other
red tape, to prepare for the planned integration of the European
Economic Community in 1992, when trade barriers theoretically will
be abolished.
   European business leaders rely more heavily than Americans on
business and social contacts within a rigid old boy network,
Prechter said. ``We are not used to the strict conformist
orientation of society there.
   ``America is such a flexible place, and such an easy place. That
is one of the reasons we are not an export-oriented country.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday Oct. 29</NOTE>
