<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1306EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Railroads     10-25 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Railroads,0301</SECOND>
<UNK>Norfolk Southern Reports Third Quarter Earnings Down 16.1 Percent</UNK>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norfolk Southern Corp. reported Wednesday
that third-quarter earnings declined 16.1 percent because of a
decrease in non-coal revenues and rising expenses.
   Earnings for the third quarter was $150.5 million or 87 cents a
share, the railroad and transportation company said. Earnings for
the third quarter of 1988 totaled $179.4 million or $1 a share.
   Arnold B. McKinnon, the company's chairman, president and chief
executive officer, said the decline in merchandise revenues
reflected a flattening of the economy.
   ``There were some bright spots,'' he said. ``Strong exports and
utility markets produced a 2.4 percent growth in coal revenues,
while increased production at the new auto plants on our lines
accounted for a 2.4 percent increase in automobile revenues.''
   Earnings for the first nine months of 1989 totaled $458 million
or $2.61 a share, up 0.4 percent from the first nine months of 1988
when earnings totaled $456.1 million or $2.51 a share.
   Transportation operating revenue was down 1.8 percent to $1.14
billion for the third quarter of 1989 when compared to the third
quarter of 1988. Of that amount, railway revenues declined 1.8
percent to $903.3 million and motor carrier revenues dipped 1.7
percent to $238.8 million.
   Total transportation operating expenses increased 5.4 percent in
the third quarter, to $941.4 million, and 7.9 percent for the first
nine months, to just under $2.8 billion.
   For the nine months, total transportation operating revenues
were $3.43 billion, up 3.8 percent from $3.30 billion a year
earlier. Railway operating revenues rose 3.9 percent and motor
carrier revenues rose 3.2 percent.
   Nine-month transportation operating expenses rose 7.2 percent,
with railway expenses up 7.9 percent and motor carrier expenses up
4.9 percent.
  
</TEXT>
