<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Steel     10-25 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Steel,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Drop At Bethlehem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. said Wednesday that
weakening steel markets helped cut its third-quarter earnings by
more than half to $46.9 million, or 53 cents per share.
   In the 1988 third quarter, Bethlehem earned $101.4 million, or
$1.18 per share.
   Sales fell 7.9 percent from $1.32 billion to $1.22 billion in
the comparable three-month periods.
   ``We anticipate that steel market conditions will exhibit a
further moderate decline in the fourth quarter as the automotive
sector remains weak and customers continue to adjust inventories,''
said Walter F. Williams, chairman of the nation's second-largest
steelmaker.
   The company's steel-related segment operated at a loss of $8
million during the quarter and $128 million loss for the first nine
months. Operating losses were $80 million and $97 million
respectively in the 1988 periods.
   Nine-month profits fell nearly 42 percent from $337 million, or
$4.17 per share, to $196 million, or $2.28 per share. Sales slid
slightly from $4.16 billion to $4.10 billion.
</TEXT>
