<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar firmed against most foreign
currencies in European trading Wednesday. Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said trading was directionless in the absence of any
fresh market-moving news.
   ``The market has been quiet, the dollar seems to show a tendency
to rise a little bit,'' said a trader at a large U.S. bank in
Frankfurt.
   Traders said they are awaiting Thursday's U.S. third quarter
gross national product data, which should provide further clues on
the American economy and whether the U.S. Federal Reserve will ease
monetary policy soon.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell to a closing 141.55 Japanese yen from
142.10 yen Tuesday. Later, in London, it rose to 141.60 yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6090 from $1.6065 late
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.8410 West German marks, up from 1.8390; 1.6129 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6120; 6.2520 French francs, up from 6.2475; 2.0740 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.0860; 1.1745 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1723; and 1,350.00 Italian lire, up from 1,349.00.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $368.25 a troy ounce,
up from $367.75 bid Tuesday. In Zurich, gold closed at $368.70 an
ounce, up from $367.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.72 to close at $386.63 an
ounce.
   Silver fell in London to $5.11 a troy ounce from $5.12 late
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
