<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-GMSubsidiaries     10-25 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-GM Subsidiaries,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>GMAC, Hughes Earnings Drop, EDS Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GM Hughes Electronics Corp., builder of the
Galileo Jupiter probe released last week, said Wednesday that
employment cuts and lagging General Motors Corp. auto production
cut its third-quarter earnings 18 percent.
   General Motors Acceptance Corp., the automaker's finance and
mortgage arm, said an interest pinch cut its July-September
earnings 3 percent from the third quarter of 1988.
   Electronic Data Systems Corp. said new data processing contracts
with savings and loan associations helped boost its earnings by 12
percent.
   GM's major subsidiaries reported their earnings Wednesday. GM is
scheduled to report consolidated earnings Thursday, as are Ford
Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp.
   GM Hughes Electronics reported net income of $147.8 million, or
37 cents per share of GM Class H stock _ the issue dependent on its
performance _ down from $179.6 million, or 45 cents a share, in the
third quarter of 1988. Revenue for the quarter was $2.58 billion,
down from $2.63 billion a year earlier, the company said.
   The company said an 8.4 percent decline in domestic GM vehicle
production cut use of its Delco electronics products. It reported
$24 million in retirement, severance and other costs for the
quarter in connection with an 8 percent employment cut announced in
June at Hughes Aircraft.
   For the first nine months of the year, the company said it had
net income of $598.2 million, or $1.48 a share, on revenue of $8.47
billion, compared with $632.6 million, or $1.58 a share, on revenue
of $8.19 billion in the 1988 period.
   GM Hughes Electronics had 1988 revenue of $11.2 billion.
   GMAC, the largest unit with 1988 revenue of $13.5 billion, said
net income for the three months ended Sept. 30 dropped to $234.5
million from $241.9 million in the third quarter of 1988. GMAC
doesn't report earnings per share; it doesn't have a separate stock
issue dependent on its performance.
   GMAC said it financed or leased 676,000 new cars and trucks in
the United States in the quarter, up 35 percent from a year
earlier, but borrowing costs averaged 9.38 percent, up from 8.45
percent.
   Net income for the first nine months was $859.5 million, down
from $930.2 million in the first nine months of 1988, GMAC said.
   EDS reported quarterly net income of $110.9 million, or 93 cents
per share of GM Class E stock, up from $95.9 million, or 79 cents a
share a year earlier. Revenue was $1.37 billion, up from $1.22
billion a year earlier, the company said.
   For the first nine months, EDS reported net income of $315.8
million, or $2.62 a share, on revenue of $4.03 billion, up from
$280.7 million, or $2.30 a share, on revenue of $3.54 billion in
the first nine months of 1988.
   EDS had 1988 revenue of $4.84 billion.
</TEXT>
