<DOCNO> AP891025-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Advertising-Disabled Adv29   10-25 1138</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Advertising-Disabled, Adv 29,1176</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>Disabled Cast In Mainstream Commercials</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A burly bearded man uses sign language to
communicate with his pal as they belly up to the bar in a beer
advertisement.
   An ad for laundry detergent shows a man in a wheelchair
sky-hooking a soap packet into the washing machine. An ad for a
Southern bank shows a mother getting her children off to school and
settling down to ``read'' her bank statement, written in braille.
   Advertisers have been making greater use of people with
disabilities in mainstream commercials, designed to show the wide
appeal of their products and services.
   Advocates for the more than 37 million ``physically challenged''
Americans have welcomed this increased visibility. But they say the
disabled still are under-represented.
   ``Advertisers have been a bit timid,'' said Arney Rosenblat,
spokeswoman for the National Multiple Sclerosis Society and an
advocate of more disabled people in advertising. ``They always try
to get sexy girls and project a mainstream idea of what everyone
wants to look like using their product.''
   But she said a growing awareness of the economic clout of the
disabled and pressure on Congress to forbid discrimination against
the disabled are having an impact.
   She said the disabled have an estimated $40 billion a year in
spending power, an appealing target for manufacturers who have
shown keener interest in getting messages to narrowly defined
audiences.
   ``Five years ago, you couldn't name one company (using disabled
people in commercials) but now there are 10 or more,'' Ms.
Rosenblat said.
   They include Anheuser-Busch Companies Inc., Colgate-Palmolive
Co., Wachovia Bank &amp; Trust Co., Ralston Purina Co., Apple Computer
Inc., Citicorp, Nike Inc. and General Motors Corp.
   Athletes in wheelchairs have been popular, including a Nike
commercial that featured racer Craig Blanchette.
   But advocates for the disabled say they are even more encouraged
by ads that integrate average people with disabilities into
real-life vignettes.
   Ralston, for instance, showed a blind man and his guide dog in a
recent commercial for Purina Dog Chow; Citicorp cast a businessman
in a wheelchair with a briefcase on his lap in an ad that showed
people hurrying to work; and a Dayton Department Stores ad included
a boy in a wheelchair among a half-dozen youngsters trimming a
Christmas tree.
   Levi Strauss &amp; Co., the apparel maker from San Francisco, was
among the first to integrate disabled people into general
advertising.
   In 1984, Levi used a man in a wheelchair as one of several
people shown in a commercial for Levi's 501 blues, and has used a
woman in a wheelchair, a hearing-impaired woman using sign language
and an amputee on crutches.
   ``We have never used them deliberately except when it seemed
appropriate for the situation,'' said Alan Jewett, an executive at
the Levi ad agency, Foote Cone &amp; Belding.
   Fast-food leader McDonald's Corp. has made prominent use of the
disabled.
   Its captioned ``Silent Persuasion'' ad a few years ago showed
two deaf students using sign language on a study break. Another ad
called ``Best Friends'' showed a typical day for two junior high
girls, one in a wheelchair.
   ``Our view is that since a large percentage of our commercials
deal with `slice of life' situations, you don't ignore people who
are a large part of society,'' said Chuck Ebeling, spokesman for
the Oak Brook, Ill.-based company.
   In an ad for Budweiser that ended an 18-month run late last
year, Anheuser-Busch showed a dozen scenes of friends enjoying a
beer _ a group of graduates in their gowns, some aging veterans at
a reunion, a father and son on a porch.
   In one shot of a crowded bar, a bearded man can be seen using
sign language as he talks with a pal standing beside him.
   ``Great catch!'' the admakers said the deaf man tells his friend
as they watch television. ``Want another Bud?''
   Colgate-Palmolive admakers cast a man in a wheelchair for a Fab
One Shot commercial that ran last year. The commercial showed
people tossing the detergent packet into the washing machine from
odd angles to the tune ``Sweet Georgia Brown.''
   Ariel Allen, vice president of creative services at Colgate,
said she previously had received letters encouraging her to use the
disabled in ads, and felt it would be appropriate for this
commercial.
   The man selected for the ad played in a basketball league for
the disabled, she said, and he provided ``something extra that
happens from both a human and a selling point of view.''
   Wachovia Bank &amp; Trust Co. of Winston-Salem, N.C., has been
running ads for months that draw attention to its services. The
bank has been printing bank statements in braille for blind
customers since the 1970s but had not advertised it until earlier
this year.
   The commercial shows a woman at her door as her children leave
for school. She turns back into the house and takes some papers off
a table. But it is only when she is seated and scanning the papers
that viewers see they include a statement written in braille which
the woman reads by passing her fingers over the raised dots. She is
blind.
   Advocates for the disabled say they want to see more. Disabled
people make up 15 percent of the population but far fewer in ads.
   Laura Slutsky, founder of Peoplefinders Inc., a New York-based
agency that specializes in finding non-professional talent for
commercials, said none of the 50 or so advertisers she works for
have asked for disabled people, although she expects that to change.
   Jerry Saviola, director of casting services at Grey Advertising
in New York, said advertising agency people may simply not be
``sensitive enough to the whole situation'' to request disabled
people for roles.
   Sometimes even when a disabled person is required for in a
commercial, admakers can stumble.
   Bill Demby, the Vietnam vet who lost both legs in the war and
starred in a commercial that showed him playing basketball with
artificial legs made by DuPont Co., said he almost backed out of
the commercial.
   He said one person involved in making the ad indicated he would
manipulate a camera to make it appear Demby could jump much higher
than he actually could.
   In a telephone interview from his home near Washington, Demby
said the comment upset him because he didn't want to mislead
anybody about what artificial legs could do for an amputee.
   ``But they assured me they would try to keep a reign on'' the
offending admaker, Demby said, and he made the ad.
   He said he's happy with the result and thinks it reflects well
on both the disabled and veterans. ``The only difference between
disabled people and others are what we use as transportation,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
