<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Surge; Wheat Sags</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of corn and soybeans shot higher,
but wheat prices sagged at the close of trading Wednesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   This week's light trading continued for a third day, with little
outside news of any consequence affecting prices, said Susan
Leighty, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Lack of export demand and beneficial rains for both the South
American and U.S. winter crop was hurting wheat prices, Ms. Leighty
said.
   Supporting futures prices was new Soviet interest in the
agricultural markets, as the Soviet Union purchased 50,000 metric
tons of Argentine meal and 350,000 metric tons of corn from
Yugoslavia since Tuesday, said Victor Lespinasse, a floor trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   At the close, wheat was 1} cents to 5} cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.03} a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 2{ cents higher, with December at $2.42{ a bushel; oats
were \ cent to 1\ cents lower, with December at $1.45} a bushel;
and soybeans were 2{ cents to 5} cents higher, with November at
$5.66{ a bushel.
