<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1632EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-COCOM 1stLd-Writethru f0135 10-25 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-COCOM, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0135,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Allies Argue Over Sensitive Exports to Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs bg'ng, COCOM, comprised ..., to CORRECT it
to 15 NATO nations sted 16; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Wednesday confronted 16 allies
pressing to ease controls on sensitive high technology sales to
Communist governments in light of rapid changes in the Soviet bloc.
   A U.S. source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, acknowledged
before the meeting that Washington was all but isolated by allies
who want greater trade with fewer restrictions.
   At the same time, the source said, the U.S. delegation feels
that some countries, including West Germany and Italy, have not
strengthened export controls as promised.
   The meeting of COCOM, the Coordinating Committee for
Multilateral Export Controls, was expected to end Thursday. Until
then, not even its location was to be disclosed.
   COCOM, comprised of the 15 NATO nations and Japan and Australia,
regulates trade in items to Soviet bloc nations.
   The U.S. Embassy said three issues would dominate the agenda:
streamlining the list of restricted items, improving export
controls and discussing political developments in the East.
   COCOM's list of restricted items threatens to drive a wedge
between the United States and its European allies.
   U.S. officials contend that, in a new atmosphere of openness,
Soviet engineers are acquiring restricted Western technology at
what may be an unprecedented rate.
   European governments insist the Bush administration is dragging
its feet, reviewing the list item-by-item and retaining simple
items that reached Moscow long ago.
   They argue that changing philosophies in Eastern Europe put
political and economic pressure on them to expand trade.
   Increasingly, COCOM partners accuse the United States of using
the list to stifle foreign competitors of American manufacturers.
They say that some U.S. companies are also guilty of infractions.
   Recent U.S. intelligence findings report that more than 5,000
machine tools have been sold illegally to the Soviet Union over the
past five years. The Kremlin depends on Western high-precision gear
for manufacturing military equipment.
   Before the meeting Wednesday, Reginald Bartholomew, U.S.
undersecretary of state for security assistance, visited Rome to
warn that Olivetti might be banned from selling some items in the
United States.
   The Italian manufacturer was alleged to have exported to the
Soviet Union machine tools used for making fighter aircraft
engines. Olivetti also was reported to have sent technicians to the
Soviet Union.
   In a well-publicized case last year, Japan's Toshiba Machine Co.
was accused of selling sophisticated equipment to the Soviet Union
in violation of COCOM regulations.
   The United States claimed the equipment helped the Soviets build
quieter, harder to detect submarines, and it slapped severe
sanctions on Toshiba Machine and prohibited it from exporting to
the United States for three years.
   On Wednesday, another Japanese firm, Tomei Shoji, was convicted
of exporting electronic products to communist North Korea in
violation of COCOM rules. The trading firm and one if its employees
were fined a total of $4,900. Two other employees were given
six-month prison terms.
   Specialists say part of the problem is the political role of
export industries in national economies.
   Earlier this year, Defense Department officials showed The
Associated Press an internal report identifying West Germany as
``the greatest single source of transfers of sensitive technology''
to the East.
   The report blamed pressure from German business on a government
eager for links to East Germany and the Soviet Union.
   Even France, regarded as a relatively effective COCOM partner,
has allowed serious leaks.
   Earlier this year, French officials said they were investigating
the apparent role of a government adviser in illegal sales to
Moscow of machine tools used in making warplanes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891025-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1639EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Oil-Reshuffling     10-25 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil-Reshuffling,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Oil Companies Continue Reshuffling As Domestic Reserves Dwindle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business News</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobil Corp.'s plan to trim its U.S. exploration
and production business reflects an industry-wide trend toward
bolstering their shrinking reserves by boosting overseas
exploration, analysts said Wednesday.
   Mobil's announcement on Tuesday followed similar restructurings
earlier this year by other major oil companies, including Texaco
Inc., Amoco Corp. and Occidental Petroleum Corp.
   Mobil, the nation's second-largest oil company after Exxon
Corp., said in its third-quarter earnings report that it had taken
a $40 million provision for the restructuring costs.
   The oil giant said it planned to transfer and terminate
employees over a two-year period ``to reduce costs and focus
efforts in areas where the projected financial returns are most
attractive.''
   Details of the reorganization were not immediately available,
but Mobil spokesman John Lord said an announcement was planned for
Friday.
   ``Mobil has been selling off a great number of small properties
since the early 1980s,'' Lord said. ``This (restructuring) is part
of that.''
   Analysts familiar with Mobil's strategy said the announcement
was not a surprise given the general industry trend to cut U.S.
drilling costs and focus exploration overseas, where the
probability of finding large reserves is greater and financial
exposure is lower due partly to more favorable tax and royalty
rates.
   ``We're going to see more and more announcements by other
majors,'' said Paul Ting, analyst with the investment firm
Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   Low crude oil prices over the last few years and heavy
exploration costs in the United States have discouraged many
companies from pumping more money into domestic oil drilling.
   Crude prices have hovered in the $18 to $20 a barrel range in
recent months, and as low as the $12 range last year.
   More importantly, analysts say, the U.S. oil patch may be nearly
bone dry, with little oil left outside of the Gulf of Mexico,
Alaska and offshore California. The last major U.S. oil find was in
the late 1960s in Prudhoe Bay, Alaska.
   Industrywide, domestic production fell by more than 500,000
barrels a day during the first nine months of this year compared
with a decline of about 200,000 barrels a day during 1988.
   ``Basically, the U.S. has been drilled over for oil. The large
deposits are in geologically hostile areas or off limits due to
environmental concerns,'' said Philip J. Kehl, an analyst with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Most oil companies, including large independents, are
reshuffling assets abroad because of declining U.S. output, Kehl
said.
   ``Areas outside the U.S. are considered a more cost-effective
use of oil drilling funds,'' he said.
   In 1986 Mobil announced a major restructuring of its upstream
operations _ exploration and production _ as part of an
industry-wide shakeout due to plummeting oil prices.
   Last March, Texaco announced the reorganization of its U.S.
upstream operations into two regions as part of an overall
restructuring to increase the company's profits worldwide. The move
included the streamlining of regional and divisional offices and
trimming of management.
   Amoco followed with an announcement in late March that it was
cutting its U.S. exploration and production workforce by 800. Amoco
said at the time that its domestic operations would continue to
shrink through divestment of marginal and non-strategic properties
while international activities would grow.
   Occidental continued the trend in recent weeks with the
announcement that it had ceased all U.S. exploration and was
expanding its drilling overseas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
