<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Anheuser-Busch     10-25 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Anheuser-Busch,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>3rd-Qtr Earnings Rise 5.2 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anheuser-Busch Companies Inc. said Wednesday
its third-quarter profit rose 5.2 percent from a year ago on a
revenue increase of 6.1 percent, but warned that price cutting
could slow future earnings growth.
   The company, which is the world's largest brewer and also makes
snack foods, said earnings for the quarter ended Sept. 30 were $238
million, or 83 cents per share, up from $226 million, or 78 cents
per share, last year.
   Sales in the quarter rose to $2.70 billion from $2.55 billion in
1988.
   The company said it sold a record 21.4 million barrels of beer
in the quarter, up 4.2 percent from a year ago.
   For the first nine months of the year, the company said its beer
sales accounted for 41.9 percent of the industry's sales, up from
40.6 percent as year earlier.
   But August A. Busch III, chairman and president, said
Anheuser-Busch is being challenged by competitors who have begun to
heavily discount their premium brands.
   ``We have been very reluctant to discount our high quality
premium brands to the same extent as our competitors,'' Busch said.
But he said some discounting is required to avoid further losses in
sales volume.
   Busch said the financial impact of the price cuts will be lower
earnings growth than anticipated for the last half of 1989 and the
year 1990. But he said the move should eventually pay off in an
even stronger market position and in higher earnings.
   For the first nine months, the company earned $639 million, or
$2.23 per share, up 8.2 percent from $590.4 million, or $2.01 per
share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month sales of $7.3 billion in the first three quarters of
last year.
   The company recently agreed to purchase four Sea World Parks,
two other theme parks and certain land near the parks from Harcourt
Brace Jovanovich Inc. for $1.1 billion. The deal is expected to be
closed in November, Anheuser-Busch said.
</TEXT>
