<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market drifted through a mixed session
Wednesday in an atmosphere of uncertainty after Tuesday's dramatic
swings.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 5.94 to 2,653.28.
   But advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 8 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
784 up, 700 down and 474 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 155.65 million
shares, down from 237.96 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 184.54 million shares.
   The Dow Jones industrial average plunged about 80 points in
early trading Tuesday, and then rebounded to recoup most of its
loss, finishing down 3.69 points.
   Analysts said that typified the recent volatile behavior that
has put many investors on their guard.
   In addition, traders seemed reluctant to make big commitments in
advance of the government's report Thursday morning on the gross
national product for the third quarter of the year.
   The figures are expected to show a continued slowing of economic
growth, possibly setting the stage for lower interest rates but
also raising questions about the outlook for corporate profits.
   The brokerage firm of Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. estimates
that third-quarter GNP will show an increase at an annual rate of
1.5 percent to 2 percent, after adjustment for inflation, down from
2.5 percent in the April-June quarter.
   DuPont turned in one of the best performances among the Dow
Jones industrials, climbing 2{ to 117]. The company reported higher
third-quarter earnings, raised its dividend and disclosed plans for
a 3-for-1 stock split.
   Among other blue chips, Philip Morris dropped 1 to 43{;
McDonald's lost 1\ to 31{, and International Business Machines fell
1[ to 101~, while American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was up ] at 43{.
   UAL fell 9 to 161. The stock has gyrated wildly in recent
sessions after plans for a buyout by a labor-management group ran
into trouble.
   Computer Associates International led the active list, down } at
12~. On Tuesday the company reported lower earnings for the quarter
ended Sept. 30.
   Comprehensive Care tumbled 4} to 3|. The company posted a loss
for its fiscal quarter ended Aug. 31 and said it was negotiating an
extension of its bank debt.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $6.27 billion, or 0.19
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .53 to 189.52.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 1.91 to 390.92, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was down 1.20 at 342.50.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
1.19 to 462.89. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 375.92, down .44.
