<DOCNO> AP891025-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2104EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ChipLaboratory     10-25 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chip Laboratory,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Opens Advanced Chip Laboratory; Will Add X-Ray Etching</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto POU1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. dedicated
a $500 million computer chip laboratory Wednesday and said it would
share its research on X-ray etching with another U.S. chipmaker,
Motorola Corp.
   IBM spokesman Paul Bergevin said the Advanced Semiconductor
Technology Center in East Fishkill, N.Y., was ``the nation's most
advanced semiconductor development laboratory and on a par with any
anywhere in the world.''
   The upstate New York laboratory will eventually house the
nation's first privately owned machine for etching computer chips
with X-rays, IBM said.
   IBM scientists are already experimenting with X-ray etching at
Brookhaven National Laboratory in Upton, N.Y. Motorola will pay an
undisclosed amount of money to send its engineers to Brookhaven to
participate in the IBM research for 21 months.
   The X-ray work at Brookhaven will be transferred to the new
laboratory in East Fishkill in 1991, at which time the investment
in the laboratory will total about $500 million, Bergevin said.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher attended Wednesday's
dedication ceremonies, along with Robert Noyce of Sematech and
Sanford Kane of U.S. Memories Inc. The two organizations are
intended to bolster America's standing in computer chips.
   Bergevin said IBM was discussing sharing its X-ray etching
research with other U.S. companies out of an interest in
strengthening the overall U.S. semiconductor industry.
   Scientists say future generations of computer chips will be so
densely packed with circuitry that regular light will be too fuzzy
to etch the circuit lines. X-rays have shorter wavelengths, so they
can draw finer lines.
   Japanese companies are working intensively in X-ray etching.
Bergevin said ``we're certainly on a par with the very best
efforts'' of the Japanese.
   The East Fishkill laboratory will consolidate semiconductor
research now done at chipmaking plants in East Fishkill and Essex
Junction, Vt., and at IBM research headquarters in Yorktown
Heights, N.Y.
</TEXT>
