<DOCNO> AP891025-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Ames     10-25 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ames,0803</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discounter Aims at Strong Retailing Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Ames Department Stores Inc. decided to
bring Zayre stores into the corporate fold, there were doubts that
the discounter had selected an acquisition that would fit in easily
or enhance its operations.
   A year later, Ames is putting the finishing touches on what it
calls the single largest U.S. retail conversion ever. On Thursday,
254 former Zayre stores will open their doors under the Ames name.
   The 12-month process has turned Ames into a dominant discounter
in the Northeast and the fourth-biggest discount retailer in the
country with expected sales this year of $5 billion. The three
leading discounters are K mart Corp., Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and the
Target Stores division of Dayton Hudson Corp.
   Peter B. Hollis, Ames president and chief executive officer,
said integrating Zayres has demonstrated Ames' ability to handle
change, a necessary skill for mass merchants to have in a business
where prosperity depends on being able to adapt to shifting
consumer tastes and shopping habits.
   ``Retailers who fail to change will fall by the wayside,''
Hollis said in an interview.
   Ames had considerable experience with acquisitions before it
bought Zayre Corp.'s discount store division in October 1988 for
$778 million. About 500 of Ames' 693 stores in 20 states and
Washington were the products of acquisitions; Ames has doubled its
size twice in the past 4 years.
   ``We are a company that are accustomed to acquisition. And we
are accustomed to change,'' said Hollis.
   Retail analysts say Zayre posed a tough challenge for Ames.
   At the time Ames came on the scene, Zayre stores in some areas
were suffering from a reputation for shoddy merchandise and poor
service. Under Zayre Corp., which has restructured the retail
operations it retained and changed its name to TJX Cos. Inc.,Zayre
stores weren't making money.
   Also, Zayre was technologically behind Ames, lacking the
advanced cash registers and other hardware needed to accomodate
computerized inventory controls.
   Industry analysts say the use of sophisticated inventory
management techniques _ employing state-of-the-art technology _
might be even more important for discounters than for regular
retailers. Discounters must carefully monitor costs to maintain
their slimmer profit margins.
   Ames went in and refurbished Zayre stores to give them a more
customer-friendly layout and a better merchandise mix. Staff had
the concept of customer service drilled into them.
   Technology was upgraded. Ames made a $30 million investment in
cash registers and back-office equipment to speed customer
check-out, streamline store data collection and provide the
foundation for further improvements, such as bar-code scanning.
   Hollis said the use of scanning had to be postponed within Ames
for a year while the Zayre stores were being made compatible. It is
being tested now and should be in place next year.
   As in Ames' original stores, the former Zayre stores are
carrying more national brands in apparel, for instance.
   ``We have completely remerchandised everything carried in Zayres
stores,'' said Hollis.
   Retail analysts generally give Ames high marks for its long-term
strategy but have taken a wait-and-see attitude about the near
future.
   Ames lost $20.7 million, or 72 cents a share, in the first half
of this year due to the costs of transforming Zayre and
disappointing retail sales. Hollis has said the full year will turn
out to be profitable.
   Retail analyst Elizabeth Armstrong of Prescott Ball &amp; Turben
said the ``acquisition of Zayre will test their ability for some
time because it was a major acquisition.''
   But she said it could pay off.
   ``The combination with Zayre is going to give Ames quite a lot
of power,'' she said. ``The environment is competitive and will
continue to get more competitive but good management can do well.''
   Henry Jicha Jr., an analyst with Wood Gundy Corp., thinks Ames
can thrive under its current management.
   ``Ames prides itself on its management capability, I think
justly so, '' said Jicha.
   Ames' performance in the fourth quarter, by far the most
important time for retailers, will provide an indication if
customers like what Ames has done.
   ``The proof of the whole pudding is going to come in the fourth
quarter,'' said Jicha. He is recommending purchase of Ames stock
based on a projected return to profitability this year and a sharp
jump in earnings next year.
   In addition to the 254 renamed Zayre stores, Rocky Hill,
Conn.-based Ames owns 61 others that are retaining the Zayre name.
Ames said its research indicated that the markets in which the 61
operate _ mainly Miami, Chicago, Washington and Baltimore _ had
strong customer loyalty to the Zayre name.
</TEXT>
