<FIRST>s f BC-Midway Adv29   10-25 0927</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Midway, Adv 29,0959</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Oct. 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>While UAL Founders In Takeover Trauma, Little Midway Thrives Across
Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES REINDL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midway Airlines Chairman David R. Hinson is
behind the wheel of his company car _ a late-model domestic station
wagon _ snaking through a single lane of rain-soaked traffic slowed
by construction.
   The contractor widening the roads outside Midway Airport had
promised to keep two lanes open. Hinson picks up his car phone and
orders a secretary to complain.
   ``You've got to stay on top of these contractors all the time,''
he says.
   Hinson's conservative car and attention to detail reflect the
attitude that has made this scrappy regional carrier survive the
past decade, to become what the 56-year-old chairman and former
fighter pilot calls ``an airline airline.''
   Midway, the last U.S. airline certified in the era of regulation
and first new one to fly under deregulation, marks its 10th
anniversary Wednesday.
   Although it has less than 1 percent of the national air-travel
market, Midway's business is expanding quickly at a time when
rivals are worried about keeping passengers. In November, the
carrier is opening a second hub in Philadelphia and offering
first-class service.
   Midway also is unencumbered by the kind of takeover trauma
preoccupying its larger Chicago neighbor, United Airlines parent
UAL Corp.
   ``We realize that even though we're growing rapidly, we're
smaller than most of the carriers _ but we're an airline airline,''
Hinson said in an interview.
   An original investor in Midway, Hinson sees the airline as a
regional carrier providing many of the same services offered by
larger competitors: flights to many cities, a frequent-flier
program and international links.
   ``It's a nice little airline, no doubt about it,'' said John V.
Pincavage, a partner at The Transportation Group Ltd., a New
York-based investment bank that specializes in airline securities.
   Midway has achieved that status through attention to customer
service, a conservative balance sheet and avoiding direct
competition with large airlines, Hinson said.
   Department of Transportation figures on domestic airlines for
the first nine months of 1989 show Midway ranks among the top 10
for the fewest passenger complaints, at an average 1.46 per 100,000
passengers, and in honoring reservations, bumping an average 1.6
passengers per 10,000 boarded.
   Midway started as a cut-rate airline offering penny-a-mile fares
in its first promotion on Nov. 1, 1979, when three DC-9s flew to
Cleveland, Detroit and Kansas City.
   The carrier now serves 51 cites with a fleet of 64 planes from
Midway Airport, 11 miles southwest of Chicago's Loop. That is about
half the distance from downtown to O'Hare International Airport.
   Earlier this year, Midway signed a $2 billion deal with
McDonnell-Douglas Corp. for 74 new jets and agreed to pay $244
million for 33 twin-engine turbo-prop commuters from a West German
manufacturer.
   While its capacity has steadily increased, earnings have varied.
Two years of modest profits followed a first-year loss. Midway then
logged three losing years through 1985, when Hinson became chairman
and chief executive officer.
   The company since has since reported three consecutive
profitable years, although earnings fell last year. One explanation
for the slump was a drop in passenger traffic blamed on Midway's
slow response to triple-mileage frequent flier incentives offered
by other airlines.
   ``We made a mistake,'' Hinson said.
   Midway earned $6.5 million, or 60 cents a share, on revenues of
$412 million in 1988, vs. $18.6 million, or $1.70 a share, on
revenues of $346.9 million in 1987.
   The airline earned $8 million, or 62 cents a share, on sales of
$233 million for the first six months this year, vs. $4.3 million,
or 27 cents a share, on $192 million in revenues for the
year-earlier period.
   Analysts who follow airline stocks see Midway as a solid
performer in a volatile industry. But the airline's $205.6 million
acquisition of Eastern Airlines assets at Philadelphia
International Airport could hurt Midway's financial performance in
the next two years.
   Hinson is counting on the airline's lock on Midway Airport to
help pay the cost of developing the Philadelphia hub.
   ``We have this chasm to get across, but we can fund that out of
Chicago,'' he said. ``It would be a big mistake for us to go to
Philadelphia and try to be successful if we didn't have a pretty
good airline here in Chicago.''
   In an increasingly competitive industry, Julius Maldutis, an
analyst with Salomon Brothers Inc. in New York, said Midway has a
strong future.
   ``They have a very important market niche in terms of the Midway
Airport dominance that they have successfully developed,'' he said.
   ``I think more importantly, they have one of the strongest
managements in the airline industry in terms of developing that
niche, because it basically boils down to management.''
   Midway's success has spawned persistent rumors of a takeover,
but no deal has surfaced. Midway management treats the 9.6 percent
stake purchased earlier this year by Ampco-Pittsburg Corp. as a
``normal business investment,'' said airline spokeswoman Sandra
Allen.
   But when its crosstown neighbor UAL was in the midst of takeover
negotiations in August, Midway's board strengthened the company's
``poison-pill'' defense against hostile suitors.
   ``I mean prudent boards do those things,'' Hinson said. ``But
the board's instructions to me and my feeling as well is that we're
going to operate Midway like any business.
   ``If somebody insists on buying the company and they offer a
price that's so high that the board feels they must accept it, then
we'll sell the company, obviously.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Oct. 29</NOTE>
