<FIRST>r f AM-LIN-McCaw     10-25 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LIN-McCaw,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>LIN Says McCaw Will Have To Extend Partial Tender Offer for LIN Shares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LIN Broadcasting Corp. said Wednesday that McCaw
Cellular Communications Inc. will have to extend its $2.75 billion
offer for about 40 percent of LIN's shares.
   The McCaw offer of $125 a share for 22 million of LIN's shares
is currently scheduled to expire Friday, but LIN said McCaw will
have to extend it because McCaw has failed to announced sufficient
committed financing for the deal.
   LIN said federal securities regulations would require McCaw to
keep its offer open five days after announcing fully committed
financing.
   McCaw, the nation's largest cellular telephone company that has
been pursuing LIN since June, said in a statement that it was
``moving forward with our financing beyond the initial round of
commitments.''
   The Kirkland, Wash.-based McCaw said last week that it had
received $1.2 billion in financing commitments from three banks
that are highly confident they could arrange a syndicate of banks
to commit the balance of the $4.5 billion in financing needed
within a few weeks.
   McCaw wants to arrange financing for more than the costs of the
tender offer alone because it intends to buy Metromedia Co.'s
half-interest in a cellular franchise in New York City for $1.9
billion as well.
   ``The issue now at hand is will LIN conduct a fair auction,''
McCaw said in Wednesday's statement.
   New York-based LIN has taken no position on the McCaw offer, and
won't do so until it hears from BellSouth Corp., the regional
telephone company based in Atlanta with whom it has a separate deal
to merge cellular telephone operations.
   A spokeswoman for BellSouth said the company expects to respond
to the McCaw offer for LIN soon, but could not say when.
   In national over-the-counter trading Wednesday, LIN rose 50
cents a share to $109.25 while McCaw rose 50 cents a share to
$40.50.
</TEXT>
