<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-25 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures End Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices ended mixed Wednesday with
the crude oil market under pressure from growing concern about
excess OPEC production.
   Analysts said the crude market largely ignored an American
Petroleum Institute report that showed a decline in oil inventories
last week.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude,
finished 10 cents lower at $19.62 a barrel. January crude ended
down 3 cents at $19.52 a barrel while contracts for later delivery
advanced.
   Refined products traded on the exchange also closed mixed. The
November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 0.61 cent to
53.40 cents a gallon and later contracts also rose.
   November heating oil lost 0.1 cent to 58.44 cents a gallon and
December declined 0.20 cent to 58.67 cents a gallon, while
contracts for later delivery showed gains and losses.
   Analysts said API statistics released after the close of trading
on Tuesday showed that inventories of crude and products declined
in the week ended Oct. 20. Although the data should have been
bullish, concern about rising oil production dampened the markets'
enthusiasm, traders said.
   ``The markets sagged as traders continued to express some
concern over higher OPEC production as well as evidence of sluggish
U.S. demand,'' said Andrew Lebow, senior broker and analyst with
E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc.
   The API data showed that crude stocks fell 6.3 million barrels
to 336.5 million barrels; total gasoline supplies were down 2.1
million barrels to 223.2 million; and heating oil declined 374,000
barrels to about 120 million barrels.
   Industry estimates suggest that the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries is continuing to increase production. OPEC
output recently swelled to more than 22 million barrels a day, well
above its official quota of 20.5 million barrels a day.
   Various OPEC members also have suggested recently that the
cartel will raise production further as worldwide demand for OPEC
oil increases in coming years.
   Nevertheless, U.S. demand is expected to decline, putting
downward pressure on oil prices.
</TEXT>
