<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kemper Financial Services Inc. has stopped doing
business with four Wall Street firms involved in computerized
program trading, saying the strategy had scared away investors by
increasing stock market volatility.
   The Chicago-based money manager on Wednesday cited what it
called the ``disruptive and destabilizing influence'' of the
trading strategy, which some blame for worsening the 1987 crash and
the recent Friday the 13th plunge.
   Kemper, which has about $7.5 billion in its stock portfolio out
of $57 billion in total assets under management, said it had ended
equity business with four firms that conduct program trading for
their own accounts. It did not identify the firms.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes, responding to lower
interest rates, climbed 4.3 percent in September to the highest
level this year, a real estate trade group said.
   The National Association of Realtors said Wednesday existing
single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 3.63 million units last month. The sales rate had increased by
4.5 percent in August.
</TEXT>
