<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
defended his agency's political independence and warned that
proposals to make the central bank more accountable to Congress and
the administration could hamper its fight against inflation.
   Greenspan was the lead-off witnesses Wednesday as Congress
launched its first major review in more than a decade of the
operations of the Federal Reserve and its chairman, often called
the second most powerful man in the country because of the Fed's
power over interest rates.
</TEXT>
