<FIRST>r f AM-Boeing    10-25 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing, </SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists Union Swings Into High Gear in Boeing Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A production-halting strike against Boeing Co. is
only strengthening the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers, union president George Kourpias said Wednesday.
   Addressing reporters at the District Lodge 751 hall after two
days of visiting picket lines in Wichita, Kan., Portland, Ore., and
the Seattle area, Kourpias vowed the union would spare no effort or
expense to win.
   ``I am here to tell you personally that the international union
is totally committed to seeing this strike through to victory,''
Kourpias said.
   In a room containing 20 eight-foot tables loaded with bread,
canned goods and other food, plus a wall lined with food cartons
five to six high, all donated, he cited similar support for
striking Pittston Co. coal workers and Eastern Airlines employees.
   Carla Bowman, a striker and union volunteer worker, said food
donations amounted to $5,000 to $10,000 at the district lodge alone.
   ``I am certainly proud to be associated with the working people
here at Boeing who are leading the fight for fairness and justice
for working families here and throughout the land,'' Kourpias said.
   The union represents 57,800 Boeing workers nationwide, including
43,300 in the Seattle area, 12,000 in Wichita, 1,700 in Portland,
and a few hundred at scattered sites in California, Hawaii, Utah,
Montana, Wyoming and other states.
   Union members voted 85 percent to strike rather than accept a
three-year contract.
   The contract offers pay increases of 4 percent the first year, 3
percent the second and 3 percent the third; bonuses of 8 percent of
gross pay in the first year and 3 percent in the second;
cost-of-living increases to cover inflation; a 20 percent reduction
in mandatory overtime; and higher benefits.
   Since the strike began Oct. 4, Boeing has announced orders for
68 aircraft worth $4.3 billion and has delivered 11 planes, all of
which were virtually complete before the walkout.
   The only talks during the strike collapsed after less than four
hours Oct. 18, and no more meetings have been scheduled.
   Major issues are wages, mandatory overtime, pensions, health and
welfare payments and standards for promotions.
   Distribution of strike pay of $100 a week per striker begins
Thursday. The last paychecks for work done before the strike were
issued last week.
   Neither Kourpias nor district lodge president Tom Baker would
predict how long the strike could last.
   Kourpias said fewer than 1 percent of union-covered workers were
crossing picket lines.
   With a strike fund of $95 million and 850,000 members paying
into the fund weekly, strike pay of $100 a week could be maintained
``as long as it takes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
