<FIRST>r f AM-Soviet-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru   10-25 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Coal Miners Strike in Same Area as Summer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with warning about possible
rationing. Picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, This summer ...; Also moved on
general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet workers at six mines called strikes
Wednesday in Arctic Circle coalfields that were hit by large-scale
walkouts last summer, the region's strike leader said.
   About 5,000 miners had voted for walkouts by Wednesday evening
and up to 20,000 at 12 mines were expected to strike, said Valentin
Kopasov, chairman of the Vorkuta area strike committee.
   The strike violated a law passed this month by the Soviet
legislature setting arbitration procedures for would-be strikers
and banning walkouts in such vital areas as energy, defense and
transportation.
   First Deputy Premier Lev Voronin said this month that power
stations and public utilities had 4.5 million fewer tons of coal on
hand than at the same time last year due to the summer strikes.
   He said miners would have to work harder to avoid rationing of
heat, light and electricity this winter.
   This summer, strikes in virtually all the Soviet Union's major
coalfields, from Central Asia in the south to the Vorkuta fields in
the far north, paralyzed much of its coal industry. The miners, who
demanded better working conditions and consumer supplies as well as
more financial independence for their mines, went back to work
after the government conceded to almost all their demands.
   But this week, miners in Vorkuta and in the western Siberian
mining town of Mezhdurechensk declared the government had failed to
come through on some of the promised benefits.
   About 20,000 Mezhdurechensk miners staged a two-hour warning
strike Monday despite officials' protests that they were showing
disrespect for the new law.
   The Vorkuta strikers demanded the government fulfill its
promises of this summer and punish officials who had gone back on
their word. They also wanted official status to be granted to new
committees formed to defend workers' interests, Kopasov said.
   As he spoke Wednesday by telephone from Vorkuta, word arrived at
strike headquarters that the town's chief prosecutor had ordered
officials at one of the striking mines to give him a list of the
walkout's organizers, Kopasov said.
   He said that made the strike leaders expect a crackdown from
local authorities.
   At a news conference Tuesday, the head of the Interior Ministry
troops that have been sent in to quell major unrest around the
Soviet Union in recent months said his soldiers would not be called
on to repress any renewed strikes.
   ``That is a political-legal question. We handle only massive
disorders,'' said Col.-Gen. Yuri Shatalin.
   This summer's coal strikes involved virtually no violence.
Strikers policed their own ranks and the authorities generally
refrained from intervening.
   But that was before the new law on strikes, when the strikers'
legal status was unclear. The government has not indicated what its
response to such open defiance of the new law will be.
   There has been no report of reprisals against the Mezhdurechensk
workers who struck Monday.
   Kopasov said the Vorkuta strikers also were demanding
publication of an appeal to the country's workers that called for
solidarity and condemned the new strike law.
   The law ``is aimed at depriving workers of the right to the
extreme measure of striking, and at distancing the worker from the
process of democratization,'' it said in part.
   The strikers also put forth several political demands, including
that the country's legislature consider doing away with the article
in the constitution that makes the Communist Party the ``leading
and guiding force of Soviet society,'' Kopasov added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891025-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1906EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Campeau     10-25 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Campeau,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Class-Action Suit Filed Against Retail Empire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A class action lawsuit was filed Wednesday on
behalf of a group of Campeau Corp. shareholders alleging officials
of the struggling real estate and retailing giant misled them about
its ability to repay a huge debt.
   The lawsuit was brought in U.S. District Court against the
Toronto-based Campeau, chairman Robert Campeau and other top
executives.
   Campeau owns a range of department stores in the United States
and is perhaps best known for its purchase of Bloomingdale's, the
swank East Coast retailing chain.
   The company's $11.5 billion debt has injected uncertainty into
the corporate bond market and raised the likelihood that
Bloomingdale's and other valuable Campeau assets will have to be
sold.
   The lawsuit seeks to determine whether the price of Campeau's
common stock was artificially inflated by alleged
misrepresentations about the company's financial situation. A
damage amount isn't specified.
   ``Although Campeau Corp. incurred significant debt in connection
with its massive acquisitions throughout 1988 and until
mid-September 1989, it made positive statements regarding its
financial condition and it repeatedly reassured the investing
public that it would be able to repay its debt,'' the suit said.
   ``The motivation for this deceit was that Campeau needed
additional financial capital from private and public sources,'' it
said.
   The lawsuit was filed on behalf of all people who purchased
Campeau stock between April 1 and Sept. 19, when the company
disclosed it reached an agreement with one of its major
stockholders, Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd., on a $250 million
loan to help the company meet interest payments due on its bonds
and help its stores pay for winter and spring merchandise.
   The lawsuit said news of the company's financial restructuring
sent the price of Campeau stock tumbling and caused substantial
losses to shareholders.
   The loan from Olympia &amp; York was be used to provide cash for
Campeau's two retail units, Allied Stores Corp. and Federated
Department Stores Inc.
   Besides Bloomingdale's, Campeau's U.S. retail operations include
the Jordan Marsh, Stern's, Ralphs, Lazarus, Burdines and
Rich's-Goldsmith's chains.
   Campeau said last month that Bloomingdale's probably would have
to be sold as part of a restructuring to reduce the company's debt
exposure.
   A Japanese newspaper reported Wednesday that Tokyu Department
Stores Ltd., a large Tokyo-based retailing chain, had offered $1.3
billion to buy Bloomingdale's. Campeau declined to comment on the
report in the daily Nihon Keizai Shimbun.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891025-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 2136EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-LuxuryTrain 1stLd-Writethru f0106 10-25 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Luxury Train, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0106,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Company Will Provide Luxury Train Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that train will be attached to Amtrak
train sted use Amtrak rails; Edy in 4th graf is cq. Also moved on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand pianos and haute cuisine.
Mahogany and gold. A Florida company is bringing European-style
luxury trains to the U.S. rails _ for a price.
   Refurbished Pullman cars will carry passengers coddled by an
on-board staff between Chicago and Washington, D.C., beginning Nov.
15. The cars will be pulled behind Amtrak's regularly scheduled
train over the route.
   A preview excursion between Panama City and Atlanta is set to
leave Friday with about 55 passengers for a one-time trip.
   American-European Express Railway Co. patterned the luxury
service after the storied Orient Express and its modern-day
recreation. Edy Zuger, chief executive officer of Nostalgie
Istanbul Orient Express of Zurich, Switzerland, which operates
luxury trains in Europe and Asia, is a partner in the $15 million
venture.
   Ten refurbished Pullman cars dating to the 1930s have been given
leather and mahagony interiors trimmed with brass and 24 karat
gold. Two club cars feature grand pianos. Dining cars will serve
seven-course meals on fine china.
   Passengers will have access to a fax machine and telephone along
the Chicago-Washington route that was picked in part for its
scenery, said Bill Spann, president of the Florida company. No
single seats will be available _ only sleeping compartments.
   ``Businessmen holding meetings, newlyweds, people having
affairs'' are some of the intended passengers, Spann said.
   The luxury cars will be hitched to regular Amtrak trains.
One-way fares for the cabins along the Chicago-Washington route
will range from $695 for a single to $1,450 for the biggest cabin,
called the ``Presidential.''
   Amtrak charges $103 to $356 one way between Chicago and
Washington, depending on whether the passenger is traveling in
coach or a sleeping car. Travelers on the Panama City-Atlanta
preview will pay $425 a person.
   It cost the company $1 million each to refurbish the Pullman
cars. All but one are completed.
   Spann, also president of Bay Point Yacht and Country Club in
Panama City Beach, said the service is the result of a chance
encounter he had with Zuger three years ago.
   Zuger had been looking for an American partner to set up a
luxury train operation in the United States. While vacationing at
Bay Point, he mentioned his plan to Spann, who said he would be
interested.
   Spann said he lined up investors to go into partnership with
Zuger's company, obtained the cars and made a deal to pay Amtrak up
to $5.6 million a year to pull them behind its regular Capitol
Limited.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
