<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-89 1956EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Airlines     10-25 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Airlines,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delta's Profit Up 33 Percent in Quarter; America West Up 30 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines on Wednesday reported a 33 percent increase in
quarterly net income to a record $133.1 million, attributing the
jump in part to the continuing strike against rival Eastern
Airlines.
   America West Corp., meanwhile, said its earnings increased
nearly 30 percent in the third quarter compared with the same
period in fiscal 1988.
   Atlanta-based Delta, the nation's fourth-largest airline, said
its earnings per share were $2.53 for the quarter ending Sept. 30,
compared with net income of $100 million, or $2.03 a share, a year
earlier. The period is the first quarter of the airline's fiscal
year.
   First-quarter revenue rose to $2.2 billion from $1.8 billion in
the same quarter of 1988.
   Net income for the nine months ending Sept. 30 was $408.9
million, or $8.11 a share, up 58 percent from the same period in
1988. Nine-month revenue rose 19 percent to $6.52 billion from
$5.47 billion.
   Delta's senior vice president, Thomas J. Roeck, said revenue
passenger miles for the quarter were up 14 percent over the same
quarter last year.
   He credited the increase to a more effective hub system and ``a
reduced level of service by a major competitor,'' an apparent
reference to Miami-based Eastern, where unions representing pilots,
mechanics and flight attendants have been on strike since March 4.
   Atlanta was Eastern's busiest hub before the strike.
   America West, an aggressive regional airline based in Phoenix,
Ariz., reported profit of $5.7 million, or 28 cents a share, in the
third quarter, up from $4 million, or 24 cents a share, a year
earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue for America West increased to $243.4
million from $201 million.
</TEXT>
