<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-ColumbiaSavings     10-25 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Columbia Savings,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thrift Known for Junk Bond Investments Takes Huge Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columbia Savings &amp; Loan Association
said Wednesday it lost $226.3 million in the third quarter because
it was forced by new laws to record $357.5 million in losses
related to its huge junk bond holdings.
   Columbia, the biggest junk bond investor among the nation's
thrifts, earned $16.3 million in the same period last year. For the
three months ended Sept. 30, losses amounted to $11.57 per share,
compared with earnings of 37 cents per share in the same quarter in
1988.
   Under the leadership of Chairman Thomas Spiegel, a close friend
of junk bond wizard Michael Milken, Columbia for years angered
federal thrift regulators by amassing a huge portfolio of the
high-yield, high-risk securities.
   Unlike some thrifts, however, Columbia in 1986 and 1987 made big
profits on the investments, which now constitute about 30 percent
of its $12.7 billion in total assets.
   On Wednesday, the thrift reported an accounting loss of $130.2
million resulting from the savings and loan bailout bill signed in
August by President Bush, which requires thrifts to get rid of all
their junk bond investments by 1994.
   Columbia said it also added $227.3 million to its reserves for
losses on its junk-bond portfolio, bringing those reserves to $300
million, or about 6.7 percent of its total investment in the
securities.
   The market for high-yield, high-risk securities has weakened
severely in recent months, and the accounting loss of $130.2
million could be revised for the better if it improves, the company
said.
   In the future, thrifts will have to invest in such bonds through
separately capitalized affiliates rather than using
government-insured deposits.
   Spiegel said that as Columbia refocuses on its lending business,
``we remain one of the most strongly capitalized thrifts in the
industry.''
   Under the bailout bill, S&amp;Ls were required to have tangible
capital _ the excess of real assets over liabilities _ immediately
and reach 3 percent tangible capital by the end of 1994.
   Columbia had tangible capital of 6 percent before Wednesday's
writeoffs. After taking them it has 3.6 percent, spokeswoman Lenore
Hatch said.
</TEXT>
