<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Zenith     10-25 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Zenith,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zenith Reports Third-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. on Wednesday
reported a third-quarter loss of $24.1 million, a good part of it
stemming from the computer business the company is selling.
   Zenith said its consumer electronics operations, which also
posted losses, were affected by a variety of factors.
   The company said it reduced distributor inventory levels of
color television sets, which undercut sales. It said it also shared
in the industrywide softness in the sales of video cassette
recorders.
   The quarterly loss of $24.1 million, or 90 cents a share,
compares with a $3 million profit, or 11 cents a share, during the
same quarter a year ago. Higher prices per unit helped sales
increase to $376.8 million from $360.7 million.
   Zenith announced earlier this month it is selling its computer
business to Groupe Bull of France, subject to stockholder approval.
It said the third-quarter loss from this operation was $15 million,
compared with a profit of $1 million during the 1988 period.
   Its quarterly loss from continuing operations _ its remaining
operations minus the computer business _ was $9.1 million, or 34
cents a share.
   For the first nine months, Zenith reported a net loss of $41.1
million, or $1.54 a share, compared with a $8.7 million loss, or 34
cents a share, during the year-ago nine-month period. Sales
improved to $1.11 billion from $961.2 million.
   ``Full-year 1989 consumer electronics operating profits are
expected to be better than last year's, but not as much as the $15
million improvement we forecast earlier,'' said Jerry K. Pearlman,
chairman and president.
</TEXT>
