<FIRST>r f AM-SCITelevision     10-25 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SCI Television,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>SCI Television Proposes Exchange Offer for Bondholders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SCI Television Inc., a privately held TV station
company struggling to meet payments on its $1.3 billion debt, said
Wednesday it was proposing a sweeping capital restructuring plan.
   The plan includes an offer to exchange about $665 million in
public and privately held bonds for a combination of stock and new
debt, and a deferment of a $153 million scheduled repayment of
principal due last month on $650 million in bank loans.
   SCI, which owns six television stations, said the ``overall
objective'' of its plan to realign its capital structure was to
reduce scheduled debt service requirements by an unspecified amount.
   In addition, it said the plan would give the company a chance
``to implement an orderly asset sales program.''
   A call was placed to a New York law firm said to represent
bondholders, but it was not returned.
   SCI Television, which was once part of the cable and TV company
Storer Communications, was created in 1987 when it was acquired in
a leveraged buyout.
   The company is 45 percent owned by the former shareholders of
SCI Holdings Inc., which had been organized in 1985 by the
investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. to buy the stations
from Storer, and 55 percent owned by Gillett Corp., controlled by
Nashville, Tenn.-based entrepreneur George Gillett.
   If bondholders and bankers accepted the plan, it would result in
current bondholders owning about 30 percent of the equity in the
company, Gillett with 41 percent, banks with 5 percent, the former
SCI Holdings shareholders with 15 percent and 9 percent to be
apportioned.
   Gillett would continue to manage the stations.
   The exchange offer is scheduled to expire at midnight Nov. 22.
   SCI said it must be tendered at least 90 percent of principal
amount of each series of previously issued securities under the
exchange offer for it to be obligated to make the exchange.
   The company said that in the event that the restructuring is not
completed, there ``can be no assurance that the company will not
elect to file for protection under applicable bankruptcy laws.''
</TEXT>
