<FIRST>u f AM-SharonSteel     10-25 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sharon Steel,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Proposes Reorganization of Troubled Sharon Steel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARRELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group and the largest
unsecured creditor of Sharon Steel Corp. said Wednesday they have
agreed to co-sponsor a plan to buy the company's steel operations
and bring the company out of bankruptcy proceedings.
   The investment group, including New York-based Castle Harlan
Inc. and two former Sharon executives, proposes to acquire Sharon's
steel operations by paying cash and assuming liabilities in a deal
valued at more than $300 million.
   Quantum Fund, Sharon's largest creditor with claims exceeding
$100 million on the company's bonds, would purchase up to $50
million in equity in the new company.
   ``We're hoping and offering that other creditors join with us in
that infusion,'' said Raymond Wechsler, financial adviser to
Quantum, an investment fund, and co-chairman of the committee of
unsecured creditors.
   Sharon's profitable non-steel businesses, Mueller Brass Co. in
Port Huron, Mich., and coal, copper and gold properties, would be
shifted to a new company that would be owned by creditors.
   The plan, to be filed in U.S. Bankruptcy Court within 60 days,
is contingent on financing.
   Sharon Steel filed for reorganization under Chapter ll of the
U.S. bankruptcy code on April 17, 1987, listing debts of $740
million. The company employs about 2,400 workers producing a
variety of carbon and specialty steel products.
   Despite the reorganization, Sharon has had to depend on its
non-steel operations to turn a profit.
   Walter Sieckman, former chief operating officer of Sharon and a
member of the Castle Harlan group, said another major creditor, AFC
Corp., has approved the plan. Quantum and AFC together control
about 40 percent of Sharon's debt to bondholders, he said.
   The bank group also includes former Sharon Executive Vice
President Wolfgang Jansen.
   Sieckman said the bidders assume there will be a mild recession
in the steel industry continuing through 1990. The company would
need about $100 million in capital improvements.
   He said he saw no reason to streamline Sharon's varied lines of
carbon and specialty steel products.
   ``We would like to make it bigger, more viable,'' he said.
   Herbert Minkel, a New York attorney representing unsecured
creditors, said the proposal dispels pessimistic predictions by
Sharon Steel's chief operating officer, E. Leonard Kern, who
replaced Sieckman.
   ``If you'd read some of his comments, you'd think there was no
one in the western world that would be interested in buying Sharon
Steel,'' he said.
   Kern has said Sharon Steel is losing money on its steel
operations and that unless production costs are reduced it might
not survive without continued support from its profitable non-steel
operations.
   Kern and United Steelworkers Local 1197 President Howard Clark
were not available for comment, their secretaries said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
