<FIRST>u f AM-Cineplex     10-25 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cineplex,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cineplex Odeon Founder Plans Bid for Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The feisty founder of Cineplex Odeon, North
America's second-biggest theater chain, plans to make a
multi-million-dollar bid to reclaim his company, Cineplex said
Wednesday.
   Garth Drabinsky, in concert with longtime partner Myron
Gottlieb, is putting together a deal already accepted in principle
by the company's two biggest shareholders, who together own a
majority of the stock.
   The proposal is worth 16.40 Canadian dollars a share, or about
781 million Canadian dollars for the 47.6 million shares
outstanding. However, Drabinsky and Gottlieb already control
between 7 percent and 8 percent of the stock and could join another
shareholder to make the bid, lowering their financing hurdle.
   In a statement, Cineplex said financing is still being arranged
and that the bid may not proceed. Under an agreement, the pair must
make a formal offer by Nov. 22.
   Drabinsky, who turns 41 on Friday, began his career as a lawyer
specializing in entertainment law. He founded the company a decade
ago in Toronto by building a pioneering multi-screen movie theater.
   Cineplex now owns 1,870 screens at 500 locations, all but one of
them in North America. It's the biggest chain in Canada, with 560
screens.
   The company is saddled with about 750 million Canadian dollars
in long-term debt, making the buyout package worth more than 1.4
billion Canadian dollars.
   ``We thought it was an appropriate and fair bid,'' said Sandra
Kolber, a member of a special committee of the Cineplex board
examining offers, from Montreal.
   The committee was formed following an abortive attempt by
Drabinsky in May to seize control by buying out the second-biggest
shareholder, Claridge Inc., controlled by Montreal-based
businessman Charles Bronfman.
   That move enraged MCA Inc., the Los Angeles-based entertainment
giant which owns the biggest block of Cineplex stock _ 23.6 million
shares. MCA succeeded in getting Canadian regulators to stay
Drabinsky's hand by insisting he make the same $17.50-a-share offer
to all shareholders.
   The Cineplex board then created the special committee to seek
buyout offers for the entire company. Wednesday's announcement _
with details of a bid in the works _ caps weeks of speculation,
although it left unanswered the big questions of financing and
whether there are other serious bidders.
   Neither Drabinsky nor Gottlieb responded to requests Wednesday
for comment.
</TEXT>
