<FIRST>r f BC-PanAm-Miami     10-25 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pan Am-Miami,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Announces Service Increase From Miami</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan American World Airways plans to add more than
60 flights a week from Miami as part of a winter schedule increase
on many routes once dominated by strike-hampered Eastern Airlines,
the carrier announced Wednesday.
   Beginning Oct. 29, Pan Am will start three daily non-stop
flights from Miami International Airport to Philadelphia; two daily
non-stops to Boston, and a daily flight to Raleigh, N.C., and
Charlotte, N.C.
   In addition, the New York-based carrier plans to add a third
daily flight between Miami and Washington, D.C. Service from New
York's Kennedy Airport to Fort Lauderdale, Fla., also will begin
Sunday.
   In the Caribbean, Pan Am plans to begin daily flights to the
Cayman Islands, St. Maarten and Antigua.
   Also, Pan Am plans to resume a weekly flight between Miami and
Frankfurt, West Germany, that was suspended several years ago.
   By mid-December, Pan Am is scheduled to increase the number of
daily flights out of Florida to about 140.
   Pan Am presently operates 96 daily flights from Florida,
including 46 from Miami, the carrier's busiest hub.
   Miami-based Eastern is entering the ninth month of a strike by
Machinists, flight attendants and pilots.
