<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Compaq     10-25 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Compaq,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compaq Posts 51 Percent Increase in Third-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compaq Computer Corp. announced a 51 percent
increase in earnings for the third quarter, due partly to higher
sales and investment earnings.
   The Houston-based company's net income totaled $87 million, or
$2.02 per share, on sales of $683 million, compared with earnings
of $58 million, or $1.40 per share, on sales of $502 million in
last year's third quarter.
   ``In the U.S., Compaq market share is at an all-time high,''
said Rod Canion, Compaq's president and chief executive officer.
   International sales accounted for 43 percent of the quarter's
sales, and were up 74 percent from a year ago, he added.
   For the first nine months of this year, Compaq reported earnings
of $254 million, or $5.94 per share, a 56 percent increase over the
$163.3 million, or $4.06 per share, last year. Sales totaled $2.1
billion, up from $1.4 billion.
   Compaq said the earnings for the quarter and nine months include
a non-recurring, pretax gain of $13.7 million resulting from an
increase in the carrying value of the company's investment in
Conner Peripherals Inc. The gains resulted from Conner's issuance
of additional common stock at prices higher than the carrying value
of Conner common stock owned by Compaq.
   During the quarter, Compaq purchased the former Wang
Laboratories manufacturing plant in Stirling, Scotland, which will
be used for international service and repair operations.
   Compaq makes desktop, portable and laptop personal computers
that are sold in 56 countries through a worldwide network of more
than 3,000 authorized dealers.
</TEXT>
